<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Norway-Crash 5thLd-Writethru a0840 05-06 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Norway-Crash, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0840,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>36 People Killed In Domestic Air Crash, TV Reports</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of destination in gras 2, 11</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Norwegian airliner crashed Friday night on
a domestic flight, killing all 36 people on board, the national NRK
broadcasting company reported.
   The television station said the plane crashed about 9 miles
southwest of its destination, the Norwegian Sea coastal town of
Broennoeysund, about 375 miles north of Oslo. All those aboard were
believed to be Norwegian, it said.
   The four-engine Wideroe Airline plane, carrying 33 passengers
and three crew members, was flying north from Namsos to
Broennoeysund, a distance of about 75 miles.
   ``The control tower at Broennoeysund airport lost contact with
the plane about five minutes before its scheduled landing at 8:35
p.m. (2:35 p.m. EDT),'' the broadcast said.
   Rescue work was coordinated by police and the rescue center in
the city of Bodoe just north of the Arctic Circle.
   ``Rescue personnel and four doctors reaching the crash site by
helicopters reported soon after 11 p.m. (5 p.m. EDT) that there was
no sign of survivors,'' Bodoe police chief Olav Soenderland said on
the television newscast.
   ``They reported that there was still fire and small explosions
in the severely damaged main fuselage and in debris spred around in
rough terrain,'' Soenderland said.
   The plane was a turbo-prop Dash-7.
   The national NTB news agency reported that the crash site was
about 330 feet above sea level near 890-foot-high Torghatten
mountain, which is well-known in Norway because it is shaped like a
hat and has a hole through the middle section.
   Soenderland said there were low clouds and poor visibility in
the vicinity of Broennoeysund on Friday night.
   A representative of the federal Airplane Crash Commission is to
fly to the crash site Saturday to begin an investigation.
   The crash was one of the worst in Norway since World War II.
   Forty people were killed in a domestic Braathen SAFE airline
that crashed just west of Oslo on Dec. 23, 1972.
</TEXT>
