<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CyanideDeaths     05-06 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Deaths,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deadlocked In Tampering Case; Deliberations Resume Monday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Friday told a jury to get some
rest and return Monday to resume efforts to break a stalemate in
the nation's first death-by-product-tampering case.
   U.S. District Judge William Dwyer refused to declare a mistrial
in the case of Stella Nickell despite a note from the foreman that
the jury was unable to reach a unanimous verdict after four days of
deliberation.
   Mrs. Nickell, 44, of suburban Auburn, is accused of killing her
husband, Bruce Nickell, 52, and Sue Katherine Snow, 40, also of
Auburn, with cyanide-laced Excedrin capsules in 1986.
   During the ensuing scare, three bottles containing tainted pain
relief capsules also were found on store shelves in and near
Auburn, and Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Myers recalled all its
over-the-counter drug capsules.
   Mrs. Nickell is charged with two counts of causing death by
product tampering and three of tampering. The death counts carry a
maximum sentence of life in prison; the maximum penalty for
tampering is 10 years.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida charged that Mrs. Nickell
decided to end her marriage and money woes by killing her husband
and collecting as much as $176,000 in life insurance.
   Mrs. Nickell then placed more tainted capsules in stores to give
the appearance of random tampering, the prosecutor said. Ms. Snow
was an innocent stranger caught in the scheme, Ms. Maida said.
</TEXT>
