<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChicagoSlurs 1stLd-Writethru a0890 05-06 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Slurs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0890,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sawyer Fires Cokely For Making Racist Remarks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, `Calls to ...' to UPDATE with comment
from Cokely. DELETES outdated last graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer fired a top aide Thursday for
alleged racist and anti-Semitic remarks, ending a five-day furor.
   ``As mayor, I will not tolerate any racial divisiveness from any
employee,'' Sawyer said in announcing the dismissal of Steve Cokely
from his $35,000-a-year job as special projects coordinator.
   Sawyer said he would call a conference of community and
religious leaders to ``heal our wounds.''
   At issue were statements Cokely made in a series of lectures
from 1985 through 1987. They were tape-recorded and made available
for sale at a store run by followers of Nation of Islam leader
Louis Farrakhan.
   In the lectures, Cokely, who like the mayor is black, had said
doctors, ``especially Jewish ones,'' were infecting blacks with
AIDS and other diseases.
   He called Christopher Columbus a ``Hispanic Jew'' who brought
slaves to America and called Columbus Day a ``white supremacist
holiday.'' Cokely also labeled the Christian cross a ``symbol of
white supremacy.''
   The 35-year-old aide, whose remarks were made public in weekend
newspaper reports, apologized Monday, and Sawyer said then he had a
talk with the aide to ``rehabilitate Steve.''
   Cokely's firing followed mounting pressure on Sawyer from City
Council and community groups, who said they were outraged by the
remarks. The mayor said he acted after consulting with a
``broadly-based, multiracial group.''
   ``I'm sensitive, and I heard from a lot of people, and I took
time to work through the process,'' he said.
   Calls to Cokely's home and office went unanswered. At a rally
Thursday night attended by about 150 cheering supporters, Cokely
said: ``There was a plot to force me to resign. There were some
people who didn't like Steve Cokely. ... Some of them thought I
wanted their jobs.''
   Mayoral aide Monroe Anderson described Cokely as ``a gofer'' for
the mayor who ``goes to groups in the black community, listens,
sometimes talks and then reports to the mayor about the concerns of
those groups.''
   The regional director of the Anti-Defamation League of the B'nai
B'rith issued a statement saying he welcomed the Cokely's dismissal.
   ``There is no place in government for any individual who
promoted such fear-mongering, bigotry-laced attitudes as the
conspiracy-haunted views of Steve Cokely,'' Michael Kotzin said.
   About 50 Cokely supporters demonstrated outside the mayor's
office before the news conference at which the firing was announced.
</TEXT>
