<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugDeaths     05-06 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Deaths,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Say Versed Was Improperly Marketed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new sedative that was touted as a superior
substitute for Valium was marketed in doses that were too strong
and sometimes fatal, doctors told a House panel examining the drug
Versed.
   ``It's a wonderful drug when it works, but the risks are too
great,'' plastic surgeon Dr. Michael Morrisey told the House
Government Operations subcommittee on human resources.
   Morisey, who said a patient of his died after receiving the
drug, said Thursday that doctors are shying away from Versed
because of the risks. ``The drug is basically out of their
control,'' he said.
   Versed, sold in the United States since March 1986, is used
intravenously for both full anesthesia and ``conscious sedation''
for diagnostic procedures often performed in a doctor's office.
   The Food and Drug Administration has received reports of 42
deaths associated with Versed, but doctors and an FDA official said
the actual count is probably higher.
   The maker of the drug, Hoffmann-La Roche Inc., declined to
testify at the hearing. But Dr. Bruce Medd, its vice president and
director of professional services, in a telephone interview
defended Versed.
   ``Fifteen million people have gotten Versed since March 1986,''
Medd said. ``If this was a major problem, we would certainly be
talking about more than 42 fatalities.''
   The doctors at the hearing complained that Versed was marketed
here at doses two to three times as high as in Britain despite
existing studies that showed the lower doses were safe and
effective.
   ``The Europeans were light-years ahead of us'' in understanding
that Versed is much stronger than Valium, said Dr. Robert Julien, a
Portland, Ore. anesthesiologist.
   Dr. Alan Lisbon, an anesthesia professor at Harvard Medical
School, said six studies showing that low doses were effective were
published before the FDA approved Versed. He said the FDA didn't
use them but Britain did in setting its lower dose level.
   Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., chairman of the subcommittee, called the
initial U.S. dose levels ``dangerously excessive'' and criticized
the FDA for failing to review all scientific literature before it
approved the drug.
   He also charged that Hoffmann-La Roche did not promptly report
to the FDA important safety-related information, including deaths
associated with the drug, that could have led to quick revision of
the recommended dose.
   ``Unfortunately, it appears that many of the safety problems
presented by Versed were preventable,'' Weiss said.
   A statement issued by New Jersey-based Hoffmann-LaRoche said all
the allegations against it would prove unfounded, and said it had
complied with all regulations on reporting of information to the
FDA.
   Dr. Carlton Peck, director of the FDA's Center for Drug
Evaluation and Research, said the FDA had responsibly evaluated the
data on Versed and acted promptly in response to reports of adverse
reactions. He said he was not aware of any information withheld by
the manufacturer.
   As for the testimony of the doctors, Peck commented: ``I can't
make any assessment of its credibility. ... There's a lot of
opinion and a sizable amount of hearsay being expressed.''
   Some of the doctors said the drug's packaging and recommended
doses were intended to make it seem comparable to Valium, although
the manufacturer already knew it was up to four times as strong.
   They said revised dosage information was delayed and then buried
in obscure materials. They also complained that the drug had no
margin of safety _ that an extra milligram could send a mildly
sedated patient into a coma.
   Advertising as far back as October 1986 noted the revised
potency level, Medd said. But the FDA did not approve revised
labeling until May 1987 and doctors did not receive a red-flagged
letter about lower dose levels until November 1987.
   ``That got my attention, but it was too late,'' said Dr. Douglas
Walta of Portland, Ore. He said one of his patients died during a
kidney exam last May.
</TEXT>
