<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AmnestyRuling     05-06 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty Ruling,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INS Could Subpoena Growers' Records Under Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm workers living illegally in the United
States could get a boost in their efforts to prove they're eligible
for amnesty under a judge's ruling Thursday.
   U.S. District Judge Lawrence K. Karlton ordered the Immigration
and Naturalization Service to develop regulations for subpoenaing
records from employers of seasonal farmworkers applying for legal
residency.
   A lawsuit filed by the United Farm Workers charged that many
laborers are being unfairly denied a chance for citizenship because
of problems with proving they live and work in this country.
   The INS requires undocumented farm workers to submit documents
such as pay stubs to back up their claims that they picked
perishable crops for at least 90 days in recent years.
   But aliens who previously tried to avoid a paper trail for fear
of deportation are finding farmers aren't always willing to back
them up in writing, said attorneys for the union.
   ``The employers are saying, `Well, you're not working for me
now. I don't owe you anything. I didn't like the way you worked for
me anyway. I don't want to bother. Or I'm going to charge you
$25,''' said Stephen Rosenbaum, an attorney with California Rural
Legal Assistance.
   The UFW is seeking to loosen immigration regulations, allowing
farm workers simply to submit a written statement and putting the
burden on the INS to prove them wrong.
   Karlton held off on ruling on that request, but issued a
preliminary injunction ordering the INS regulations for issuing
subpoenas against reluctant employers.
   On Tuesday, the judge voided a rule that made aliens ineligible
for legalization if they left the United States since November 1986.
   On Thursday he suggested he may narrow the impact of that
ruling. ``I just sort of dropped my teeth and issued an order where
I'm going to have to issue another order and say who I'm talking
about,'' Karlton said.
   He scheduled a June 2 hearing on a motion to compel the INS to
extend the amnesty deadline for those affected.
   Wednesday was the deadline for illegal aliens who have lived in
the United States since Jan. 1, 1982, to apply for amnesty.
Seasonal farm workers who picked perishable crops for at least 90
days in the year ending May 1, 1986, have until Nov. 30.
   Government attorneys said the the impact of the subpoena ruling
was small because INS already uses its subpoena power.
   ``We don't think there's much difference. It's not any different
from what's happening now,'' said Greg Hollows, deputy chief of
civil divisions in the U.S. attorney's office in Sacramento.
   But Rosenbaum said the decision is significant because INS
officials infrequently issue subpoenas to help workers get
documents from growers.
   ``They may still make people jump through hoops in order to get
them,'' he said. ``But I certainly think it is more than an
academic victory.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
