<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EasternAirlines     05-06 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Airlines,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Seeks Wider Federal Probe of Eastern Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation that would further embarrass
Eastern Airlines by prodding the Transportation Department to
expand its investigation of the troubled carrier is on its way to
the House.
   The House Public Works and Transportation Committee approved a
resolution on Thursday urging the department to widen its probe of
Eastern and its parent company, Texas Air Corp.
   The non-binding measure was approved by a voice vote, garnering
support from committee members of both parties. It is not certain
when the measure will be considered by the full House, where 210
lawmakers _ almost half the membership _ are already co-sponsors.
   Management at Texas Air and Eastern is locked in a lengthy
battle with the airline's unions that has spilled into Congress,
the courts and the news media.
   Company executives have sought a number of steps _ including
wage concessions _ to stem a huge tide of red ink, and have said
the congressional resolution is merely a ploy by the unions. But
labor leaders say management's real goal is to destroy the unions,
and that a study of the company's leadership and its operations is
justified.
   ``I don't think we're being led by our nose because of a
labor-management problem,'' said Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., the
resolution's original sponsor. ``We're being driven by safety
considerations.''
   Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt of Arkansas, ranking Republican on
the committee, also supported the measure as a ``statement of
support'' for the Transportation Department probe.
   The Transportation Department announced last month that it had
begun investigating the management, financial status and safety
practices of Texas Air, Eastern and another Texas Air subsidiary,
Continental Airlines. The Federal Aviation Administration is also
inspecting Eastern and Continental planes.
   The non-binding resolution approved Thursday urges the
department to widen its investigation by looking more closely at
how Texas Air and Eastern practices affect the public and company
employees. It also seeks to have the department use its findings in
deciding whether to allow Texas Air to make future operating
changes, such as selling the Eastern air shuttle.
   After the vote, Capt. John Knudson, a spokesman for Eastern's
unionized pilots, said the resolution would ``send a mandate to the
Department of Transportation and the FAA to ensure a full and
public airing of the issues.''
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak, speaking from company
headquarters in Miami, said the measure was ``part of the unions'
campaign to lobby Congress, discredit Eastern and frighten away
customers.''
   A similar resolution in the Senate has 14 co-sponsors.
   Meanwhile, at the U.S. Court of Appeals, Eastern asked a panel
of judges to overturn a lower court's ruling that blocks the
airline from selling its profitable Boston-New York-Washington air
shuttle service. The court reserved judgment.
</TEXT>
