<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     05-06 0943</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Department Drops Use Of Quarantine In Bee Mite Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department quarantine ordered a
month ago in 13 states to stop the spread of destructive bee mites
was canceled today because it proved to be unworkable and too
costly.
   The states are: Florida, Illinois, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi,
Nebraska, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, South
Dakota, Washington and Wisconsin.
   James W. Glosser, administrator of the department's Animal and
Plant Health Inspection Service, said Thursday the restrictions are
being lifted, effective today, on the movement of bees and
equipment from those states.
   Although not known to be harmful to other creatures, the mites
are considered a major threat to the nation's honey and beekeeping
industry.
   The tiny killer mites, Varroa Jacobsoni, were first discovered
in the United States last September in a Wisconsin apiary. They
since have spread to the other states.
   ``Information received from state governments, beekeepers,
growers and researchers has caused us to conclude that the
regulatory program established under the quarantine is not the
appropriate mechanism to contain the interstate spread of Varroa
mites,'' Glosser said.
   The original purpose of the quarantines was to issue permits for
out-of-state movement of only bees and equipment found to be free
of the mites.
   ``However, we've found that the requirements under the
quarantine are not uniformly appropriate or workable because the
role of honeybees in the agricultural economy varies widely from
state to state,'' Glosser said. ``Many beekeepers have found it
impossible to comply with the regulations and still meet their own
deadlines.''
   For example, he said, a beehive might have to be moved out of
its home state several times a year. Treating a hive against mites
requires 21 days, which is longer than most beehives are scheduled
to stay in a state when they are moved for pollination purposes.
   Beekeeping is credited by USDA with the pollination of many
agricultural crops having an estimated annual value of around $20
billion. Those include many fruits, vegetables and hay crops.
   Glosser said other factors weighed on the decision to cancel the
quarantines, including a shortage of treatment materials, and
limited state and federal resources to conduct and coordinate
surveys and inspections.
   ``The movement of hundreds of thousands of hives and other
regulated articles tends to occur during short periods in the
spring and fall, intensifying the demand for inspection services
beyond the limits of current federal and state resources,'' he said.
   The Varroa mite is an external parasite of adult bees and their
developing larvae, or brood. It causes decreased brood, deformed
bees and a weakening of the colony's ability to pollinate plants
and produce honey. Infestation can occur so gradually that the
mites may not be noticed until severe damage is done.
   Glosser said his agency will continue to coordinate the
collection of survey information about the mite.
   ``We feel, however, that state governments, producers and
beekeepers can best tailor Varroa mite detection, control and other
measures to the needs of their particular state,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says record large
supplies of red meat and poultry for the sixth straight year are
expected to chew into the financial returns of livestock producers
in 1988.
   Although that is not good news for producers, the huge supplies
will help hold down meat and poultry prices at the retail level.
   ``Reduced beef supplies are being more than offset by increased
volumes of pork and poultry,'' the department's Economic Research
Service said Thursday. ``Feed costs are rising due to expanding
exports, increased domestic use and reduced production.''
   Poultry output is being led by an expected 5 percent increase in
broiler production, with most of the increase coming in the first
half of the year.
   Commercial pork production rose 7 percent from a year earlier in
the first quarter of 1988, reflecting a gradual increase by hog
producers. Production is expected to be up 10 percent in the second
quarter from a year earlier, 8 percent in the third, and about even
in the fourth.
   ``Returns to (hog) producers may fall to near breakeven before
the third quarter ends,'' the agency reported. ``And negative
returns are possible in the fall.''
   Beef production will likely rise above year-earlier levels in
the second quarter because of more feedlot cattle going to
slaughter at heavier weights.
   ``Returns above cash costs for cow-calf producers are expected
to remain positive in 1988, but returns to Great Plains cattle
feeders may turn negative during the late spring and summer,'' the
report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Russet has beautiful eyes and a lovely
skin, says the Agriculture Department.
   Coastal Russet, is a new, pure white baking potato that will be
on its way this fall to grocery shelves. It's a 6- to 8-inch-long
potato recently released to growers by plant breeders in New York,
Florida, Virginia, New Jersey and Maine.
   Although developed specially for the diverse growing conditions
of the eastern coastal areas from Maine to Florida, researchers
found Coastal Russet can be grown throughout the United States,
officials said Thursday.
   ``Consumers will find this baked potato to be whiter and moister
than Russet Burbank, the nation's leading baking potato,'' said
Robert W. Goth, a plant pathologist in the department's
Agricultural Research Service. ``Many potatoes turn light beige
inside when baked, but not Coastal Russet.''
   The potato was developed over 10 years of research led by
retired plant pathologist Raymon E. Webb at the agency's vegetable
laboratory in Beltsville, Md.
   ``Its shallow eyes and attractive skin pattern look good in a
package, making it pleasing to the producer and the consumer,''
Goth said.
</TEXT>
