<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Transportation-Drugs     05-06 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transportation-Drugs,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOT Proposes Random Railroad Drug Testing, New Alcohol Rules For
Truckers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal for random drug testing of railroad
workers should be sidetracked by the courts, which have already
stopped a program of testing train crews after accidents, the
attorney for railway unions says.
   ``This really smacks of `chutzpah,' '' said Lawrence Mann,
attorney for the Railway Labor Executives' Association, an umbrella
group for 20 unions. Mann said Thursday the group opposes any plan
that puts a burden on workers without ``reasonable suspicion'' of a
violation.
   ``Rail labor will be given its due process by the Federal
Railroad Administration, and then they'll tell us where to go,'' he
said. He predicted the issue would end up in the courts.
   The proposal to compel railroads to begin random drug tests of
workers in positions affecting public safety was announced at a
news conference Thursday by Secretary of Transportation Jim Burnley.
   At the same time, Burnley said the department was moving to
crack down on drunken driving by commercial bus and truck drivers,
with the threat of license losses for first-time offenders.
   Burnley said he grew tried of waiting for Congress to enact
random drug testing, which he said would play ``a major role'' in
ridding the nation's railroads of illegal drugs.
   A rail safety bill that includes a random drug testing provision
has stalled in a House-Senate conference committee.
   Burnley also used the news conference to announce the proposed
crackdown on drunk driving by bus and truck drivers.
   Under the new standard, which states would be expected to adopt
in coming years, first-time violators would be subject to a
one-year loss of their commercial driver's licenses if found to
have an alcohol concentration of 0.04 percent or more. A second
citation would mean a lifetime suspension.
   The strict 0.04 standard ``is significantly below'' the 0.10
figure now set by most states as the level for ``under the
influence'' crimimal penalties, Burnley said.
   While it still would be up to the states to take action against
the drivers, the states could lose some highway aid money beginning
in 1993 if they do not adopt the stricter standard.
   Burnley said the tougher standard was warranted because of the
larger vehicles that commercial operators drive, and the amount of
time they spend behind the wheel.
   The steps announced Thursday follow by two months a DOT plan of
drug testing for all employees in sensitive safety and
security-related positions in the aviation industry.
   Random drug testing of railroad workers would complement the
existing system of testing train crews involved in major accidents.
That program has continued while the Reagan administration appeals
a federal court ruling on Feb. 11 that declared such testing
unconstitutional.
   Burnley said he was confident the Supreme Court would uphold
post-accident testing.
   But even if the high court does side with DOT, Federal Railroad
Administrator John Riley said random drug testing was a necessary
complement to existing rules.
   ``The success of a reasonable-cause drug-testing program is
dependent on the supervisor's ability to detect symptoms,'' Riley
said. ``Unfortunately, many drugs in use today can impair an
engineer's judgment without producing symptoms recognizable to even
a trained layman. Random testing isn't keyed to observable
symptoms, and the users know that.''
   Under the proposal, railroads would have to establish random
urine testing programs for marijuana, cocaine, opiates,
amphetamines and PCP.
   Of 179 train accidents during 1987, tests found at least one
positive drug or alcohol finding in 37.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BYUArtThefts     05-06 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BYU Art Thefts,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brigham Young University Recovers Missing Monet Sketch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVO, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Monet pencil sketch stolen from Brigham
Young University's art collection nearly two decades ago has been
returned, a university spokesman said.
   ``Two Women In A Boat,'' valued at $100,000 to $250,000, was
among more than 1,000 art works worth some $3 million found to be
missing when the school's 12,000-piece collection was inventoried
in 1986.
   University police recovered the sketch, also known as ``The Boat
Ride,'' from an unidentified collector in New York, school
spokesman Brent Harker said Thursday.
   The collector voluntarily relinquished the piece, which had been
purchased from an auction house.
   The Monet and two sketches by Winslow Homer, ``The Shepherdess''
and ``Over The Garden Wall,'' were taken from the university for
authentication in 1969 by Dion O'Wyatt, a New York art dealer,
Harker said.
   O'Wyatt, however, sold the three pieces but had forgeries made
of ``Two Women In A Boat'' and ``The Shepherdess'' and gave them to
Brigham Young, Harker said.
   University officials discovered the forgeries and realized that
``Over The Garden Wall'' was missing during the inventory, Harker
said.
   O'Wyatt pleaded no contest in November to theft by deception in
connection with the three missing sketches and was given a
suspended jail term and fine provided he help return the original
works, Harker said.
   The original ``The Shepherdess'' was recovered in December, but
the owner of ``Over The Garden Wall'' refused to relinquish the
sketch and the university has hired an attorney to try to recover
it, Harker said.
   Harker described the three sketches as the ``crown jewels'' of
the missing art works.
   Wes Burnside, a BYU art professor and curator of the collection
from 1973 until his retirement in 1983, was accused by BYU
officials of involvement in the disappearance of the art works,
most of which are believed to have been stolen, improperly traded
or sold between 1972 and 1978.
   Burnside pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge in exchange for
immunity from prosecution, and in March was named a defendant in a
civil suit aimed at recovering the missing pieces.
   Harker said the sketch brings to about 60 the number of art
works recovered, and that university officials know the whereabouts
of about 140 more and are seeking their return.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
