<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Wallach-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0917 05-06 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wallach-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0917,420</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: inserts new 3rd graf to show that SBA director's real first
name different from that in Wallach memo</NOTE>
<HEAD>Wallach Told Meese the SBA Chief Was the Key to Wedtech Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two weeks before the head of the Small
Business Administration was fired in 1982, Edwin Meese III was told
by Wedtech Corp. consultant E. Robert Wallach that the SBA chief
was the central figure in deciding whether Wedtech got a lucrative
no-bid contract.
   ``Apparently, the key figure at this particular moment is Frank
Cardenas, the director of the SBA,'' Wallach wrote then-White House
counselor Meese in a Jan. 21, 1982 memo released Thursday by a
Senate subcommittee. ``If my information is correct this may be the
last step and Cardenas is the key figure.''
   The SBA administrator at that time was Michael Cardenas.
   A few days earlier, Cardenas and his deputy, David Gonzales, had
decided not to sign off on the Wedtech contract until Army
officials were satisfied with terms and conditions, according to a
report by the Senate subcommittee.
   Cardenas and Gonzales have said that at a Jan. 15, 1982 meeting,
they resisted suggestions by White House aides Pier Talenti and
Henry Zuniga that Wedtech receive the $32 million contract to build
small engines for the Army.
   Cardenas was dismissed by the White House on Feb. 5, 1982 on
grounds of incompetence, and Gonzales was forced out with him.
   The Senate subcommittee reached no conclusions as to whether
Cardenas was fired because of the Wedtech contract or whether
Wallach's memo to Meese alerted the White House counselor to the
situation.
   Cardenas' replacement, James Sanders, later arranged for Wedtech
to get the work. Army officials felt the company's price was too
high, but their concerns were quieted when SBA agreed to make
several million dollars available in advance payments and business
and development expenses.
   Wallach, now under indictment for alleged racketeering in the
Wedtech scandal, has been a friend of Meese's for 30 years.
   Copies of 16 memos by Wallach to Meese, including the one dated
Jan. 21, 1982, were released by the Senate subcommittee on
oversight of government management. On Wednesday, the panel
released a report concluding that Meese and his deputy, James
Jenkins, had violated a White House policy barring participation in
individual contracts, resulting in improper favoritism toward
Wedtech.
   According to Wallach's Jan. 21 memo, Cardenas had the power to
return the contract to the Army for competitive bidding, or to keep
it under an SBA set-aside program for minority-run firms.
</TEXT>
