<HEAD>LaRouche Says `No Case' Against Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political extremist Lyndon LaRouche says a
federal jury in Boston would have acquitted him and his associates
of conspiracy charges if the judge had not declared a mistrial.
   ``There was no case,'' LaRouche said at a news conference
Thursday in Washington. ``The case was a political fraud and a hoax
from the beginning.''
   He cited a story in Thursday's editions of the Boston Herald
that quoted one juror as saying, ``There was too much question of
government misconduct in what was happening'' in the LaRouche
campaign.
   The newspaper reported that the 14 jurors held a ``surprise
vote'' in the jury room after they were excused from the case on
Wednesday and that they voted unanimously to acquit LaRouche and
his aides.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham, who handled the
government's case, could not be reached for comment.
   Prosecutors in the case said Wednesday that they would press for
a new trial of LaRouche, six aides and five affiliated
organizations on charges they raised money for LaRouche's 1984
presidential campaign through credit card and loan fraud.
   LaRouche, a candidate for the 1988 Democratic nomination for
president, and his aides also are charged with conspiring to stymie
a grand jury investigation of the alleged fraud.
   LaRouche defies traditional political labels, espousing views of
global conspiracies and future calamities.
   At his news conference, he predicted that the U.S. economy would
plunge into depression within the next year and that if another
Democrat were elected president, he would turn to LaRouche for
guidance and a possible Cabinet post.
   LaRouche denied that defense attorneys had tried to slow down
the Boston trial, which began on Dec. 17, 1987, and contended that
the U.S. attorney's office in recent weeks had ``tried to delay the
trial to get a mistrial in order to prevent an acquittal.''
   LaRouche contended that defense attorneys had pushed to have a
pretrial hearing into defense allegations of government misconduct
and infiltration of LaRouche groups. But, LaRouche said, government
attorneys balked. Instead, Keeton halted the trial two months ago
for the hearing.
   During the proceedings, the government declassified a memo in
which retired Air Force Maj. Richard Secord told then-National
Security Council aide Oliver North about an associate's effort to
``get info against LaRouche.''
   A search of FBI files based on that disclosure led to the
discovery of another classified document in which three
intelligence operatives said top-level CIA and FBI officials had
asked them to infiltrate LaRouche groups.
</TEXT>
