<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     05-06 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Play Is Oblique Slice of Life</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A screenwriter revisits people and places from
his past in ``No Time Flat,'' a slice-of-life drama in which the
sharpness of the slice is softened by a dream-like quality.
   The play, the seventh by Larry Ketron to be produced by the WPA
Theater, is very well acted, especially by Daniel Ahearn in the
lead role of Calter, the screenwriter whose manner is more Southern
country than Hollywood.
   The story begins with Calter's return to the Carolinas, where
his oldest friend, a policeman, is hospitalized after being shot in
the chest. Calter talks in the hospital waiting room with his
friend's wife, played by Linda Cook, who has appeared on the
television soap operas ``All My Children'' and ``Edge of Night.''
   Calter goes to visit an old girlfriend, and meets her daughter
Carolina (Sandra Bullock), a laid-back teenager who announces
she'll drive to New York with him. There, Calter tries to visit
another old girlfriend, finds she has moved from where she was 25
years ago, but does visit an old Vietnam buddy, played by Paul
Geier.
   The buddies' meandering conversation is the weakest part of the
play. There is the inevitable blaming of the writer for being a
spectator instead of a participant in life.
   But Calter seems content, digging up people and incidents from
his past that he'll probably use in his writing and seeming to find
that, in his case, he can go home again.
   Peter Maloney directed the off-Broadway production which was
seen on its opening night Wednesday.
</TEXT>
