<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NevadaDemocrats     05-06 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nevada Democrats,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Could Pick Up Two-Thirds Of Nevada Delegates This Weekend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nevada Democrats open a three-day state
convention today amid intense jockeying for slots on the 23-member
delegation to the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta this
summer.
   Party veterans say by the time the event winds down on Sunday,
Democratic presidential front-runner Michael Dukakis could hold
official and unofficial commitments from two-thirds of the Nevada
delegation.
   Dukakis had 32 percent of the 980 delegates elected at earlier
county conventions to attend the state convention, while Sen.
Albert Gore Jr., who hs since halted his campaign, had 27 percent.
Jesse Jackson had 25 percent, and the remaining 16 percent was
uncommitted.
   But the delegates are free to change their preferences as they
sign in on Friday and Saturday, and Dukakis could be the big
beneficiary now that Gore, popular in Nevada, is out of the picture.
   However, there is an effort to hold together the Gore delegates
so that they'll have representatives on the national delegation. To
do that, they must maintain 15 percent of the total state
convention delegation.
   But if many of the Gore delegates switch, party officials
predict Dukakis will benefit more than Jackson and could wind up
with eight or nine of the 16 elected delegates.
   Nevada also has seven ``super delegates'' who have a voice at
the convention due to being elected or party officeholders.
   Among those, it was possible that Dukakis would expand his
current count of three to as many as six. However, some of those
delegates will remain officially uncommitted despite their support
for Dukakis.
</TEXT>
