<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-06 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The days of obliging cabbies chasing a missed
train to the next town to get a passenger aboard may be gone, but a
missed riverboat posed only a bit of a problem for a Little Rock
cabdriver Tuesday.
   The cabdriver, Fred Higgins, was hailed by Bruce Robinson of New
Haven, Conn., outside the Excelsior Hotel.
   Robinson had missed a tour bus that was to take a conference
group to Riverfront Park in North Little Rock, where the Spirit, an
excursion boat, embarks on a dinner cruise on the Arkansas River.
   When Higgins and Robinson reached the park, the boat had already
left. ``He was real disappointed, so I said, `Let's try one more
time,''' Higgins said.
   The cabbie headed upriver, hoping to intercept the boat.
Arriving at Murray Lock and Dam, they saw the Spirit heading toward
them in the distance. The question then became how to get Robinson
from the taxi to the boat.
   ``He really wanted to ride it bad,'' said Higgins, who has
worked for the cab company only a month. Spotting two men in a
small pleasure boat, he called them to shore and explained the
situation. The boaters took Robinson aboard.
   Moments later, Dan Burch, captain of the Spirit, spotted the
small boat circling his craft and learned it had a passenger who
wanted to board.
   ``We kind of thought they were kidding,'' Burch said. ``We
slowed the boat and the pleasure craft came to the stern and the
guy got on. He really got a kick out of it.''
   Beverly House of Hospitality Tours, the cruise organizer, said
Robinson made it just in time for dinner. ``We all applauded,'' she
said.
   Higgins got $10 from Robinson for his trouble.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beatrice C. Draper gave Norwalk's mayor a
penny and her thoughts after she was billed for one cent on a
delinquent city automobile tax.
   Draper said she tried to pay the debt in person after she
received the first bill for one cent, but a tax clerk wouldn't take
the payment and said the debt wouldn't affect anything anyway.
   Then Draper got hung up at a state Department of Motor Vehicles
office trying to register a car because computerized records showed
she had a tax debt. And the other day, she received a second bill
from the city for one cent.
   She taped the penny to a letter she mailed to Mayor Frank J.
Esposito.
   ``The point I am trying to make is that the abuse of community
and town funds is ridiculous,'' she wrote. ``The amount of money
spent on time and postage could have been used to better advantage.
... Even though it costs 25 cents, please send me a receipt of my
one-cent payment.''
   Esposito blamed the charge on a new computer that sends the tax
bills. ``This is the first problem we know of, and I am going to
see what we can do to prevent this kind of thing from happening
again,'' the mayor said.
</TEXT>
