<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Aloha-Maintenance     05-06 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aloha-Maintenance,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aloha President Defends Airline's Maintenance Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aloha Airlines' president and chief executive
officer Maurice Myers says Aloha will match its maintenance
inspection record against any carrier in the country.
   According to Federal Aviation Administration documents, an
in-depth inspection of Aloha by the FAA last December found the
airline did not have an adequate system to assure that its aircraft
were properly maintained.
   The inspection included examination of Aloha's compliance with a
special surveillance requirement for aging aircraft, but indicated
no specific concerns about the aging Boeing 737 jet which broke
apart during a flight last week.
   A 20-foot section of the plane's upper fuselage tore away at
24,000 feet, sending a flight attendant to her death and injuring
61 passengers, although the plane limped to a safe landing.
   According to the FAA, the 19-year-old plane, which had 89,000
landings, was one of four Aloha aircraft under a special inspection
program aimed at aging aircraft as well as a special FAA
airworthiness directive warning about possible cracking in the
upper portion of the fuselage.
   The inspectors concluded that the airline did not have ``an
effective internal audit program'' to make certain it was complying
with federal requirements, including emergency FAA airworthiness
directives.
   Myers said Thursday the company had undergone the required
investigation which he described as ``a very thorough inspection
which focuses on procedures and record keeping, not on equipment.''
   ``In our final briefing by the FAA, we were told by the
inspection team that the items found were typical of airlines
across the country and that we run a safe airline,'' Myers said in
a statement. ``We will match our maintenance inspection record
against any carrier in the country.''
   Aloha operates scheduled air service to four islands _ Kauai,
Oahu, Maui and Hawaii _ in the Hawaiian island group as well as
some charter services.
</TEXT>
