<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese     05-06 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asked About Meese, FBI Director Says He'd Resign if Ethics
Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William Sessions responded to
questions about Attorney General Edwin Meese III by saying public
officials have an obligation to maintain the highest legal and
ethical standards.
   An independent counsel investigating Meese since last May 11 is
expected to issue a report raising sharp questions about the
attorney general's ethical behavior, according to sources familiar
with the probe.
   ``Ethical conduct in connection with lawyers particularly is a
very sensitive matter,'' Sessions said Thursday when asked by
reporters about the embattled attorney general.
   ``I think it's even more important when you're dealing with a
person who is, in fact, the attorney general of the United States,
and I think that Mr. Meese would strongly agree with that,'' added
the FBI director.
   Sessions emphasized that he was addressing the principle of
ethical conduct and not the specifics of the Meese case, the
subject of a nearly yearlong investigation by a special prosecutor.
   Sessions said he would resign his own post if the public felt he
had engaged in improprieties.
   ``If it is perceived that the director of the FBI ... is not
properly, legally and ethically carrying out his responsibility, I
always have open the route of resignation for myself,'' Sessions
said when asked, in the context of Meese's legal troubles, what he
would do if he sensed the public thought he were acting improperly.
   But Sessions added that ``I think there's a great deal of
difference between'' a hypothetical situation involving himself and
``the circumstances'' involving allegations against Meese.
   When a reporter asked whether Sessions would be unhappy if his
remarks were interpreted as suggesting that Meese, his boss,
perhaps ought to resign, the FBI director responded:
   ``No, I think you'll have to draw your own conclusions.'' But he
quickly added that ``I'm trying to talk about general principles
that I do believe apply to conduct of public officials. ... I can
speak as to myself, but I am not trying to speak as to those
circumstances that might involve Mr. Meese.''
   After checking with Meese about Sessions' remarks, Justice
Department spokesman Terry Eastland declined to comment.
   Independent counsel James C. McKay has been investigating
Meese's ties to the scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp., a $1 billion
Iraqi pipeline and other matters. Sources familiar with the probe
say McKay is expected to issue a report raising several ethical
questions about the attorney general's ties to longtime friend E.
Robert Wallach, who is under indictment in the Wedtech case.
   A Senate subcommittee on Thursday disclosed that two weeks
before the head of the Small Business Administration was fired in
1982, Meese was told by Wallach that the SBA chief was the central
figure in deciding whether Wedtech got a lucrative no-bid contract.
   ``Apparently, the key figure at this particular moment is Frank
Cardenas, the director of the SBA,'' Wallach wrote then-White House
counselor Meese in a Jan. 21, 1982 memo released by the Senate
subcommittee. ``If my information is correct this may be the last
step and Cardenas is the key figure.''
   The SBA administrator at that time was Michael Cardenas.
   A few days earlier, Cardenas and his deputy, David Gonzales, had
decided not to sign off on the Wedtech contract until the Army was
satisfied with the terms and conditions, according to a report by
the Senate subcommittee.
   But Cardenas was dismissed by the White House on Feb. 5, 1982 on
grounds of incompetence, and Gonzales was forced out with him.
   The Senate subcommittee reached no conclusions about whether
Cardenas was fired because of the Wedtech contract or whether
Wallach's memo to Meese alerted the White House counselor to the
situation.
   Copies of 16 memos by Wallach, then a Wedtech consultant, to
Meese, including the one dated Jan. 21, 1982, were released by the
Senate subcommittee on oversight of government management.
   On Wednesday, the panel released a report concluding that Meese
and his deputy, James Jenkins, had violated a White House policy
barring participation in individual contracts, resulting in
improper favoritism toward Wedtech.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
