<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     05-06 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Goes To Hollywood, Says He's `Hot on the Heels' of Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, campaigning in the state with
the nation's biggest delegate prize, declared he is ``hot on the
heels'' of Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson arrived Thursday afternooon in California and took a
stroll through historic Olvera Street, site of the old Los Angeles
mission church and a center of Hispanic culture.
   Later he hobnobbed with celebrities at a Hollywood fund raiser
where about 200 people paid $100 each to hear him speak.
   Among those attending were Lloyd Bridges, Eileen Brennan, Tony
Franciosa and Dennis Weaver, who said he supports Jackson because
he will bring a ``love ethic'' to Washington.
   Jackson gave a preview on Olvera Street of the issues he will be
emphasizing as he campaigns for California's June 7 primary
election.
   He spoke against the movement to make English the offiical
language of the United States, and discussed immigration, the
strife in Central America, U.S.-Mexico relations and his proposal
to raise the minimum wage.
   In a chaotic crowd that gathered by Jackson's bus on Olvera
Street, a couple of hecklers revived controversy that dogged
Jackson in New York, where Jackson's sometimes shaky relations with
the Jewish community were spotlighted.
   The hecklers shouted ``Lose, Jesse, lose,'' and ``Welcome to
Hymietown,'' a reference to the offensive term Jackson used for New
York in his 1984 presidential campaign.
   But a man nearby shouted, ``Win it for the minorities anyway,
Jesse.''
   Polls have shown Jackson trailing Dukakis badly in California,
but campaign officials said they are looking at the state as a
wide-open contest where Jackson can make inroads among minority
groups, gays and other interest groups.
   Despite Dukakis' increasing delegate lead over him, Jackson told
an impromptu gathering at El Paseo Mexican restaurant on Olvera
Street: ``We are hot on his heels and we're getting stronger as the
days get longer.''
   Former state health chief Mario Obledo, who heads Latinos For
Jackson, said ``California is our best state ever. I feel fairly
confident we're going to win this state.''
   Jackson is expected to have an uphill fight for the Hispanic
vote, with many Hispanics impressed by Dukakis' fluent Spanish.
   Across from where Jackson spoke, a shop on Olvera Street boasted
a Dukakis poster in the window.
   To cast a positive light on his progress, after a string of
losses to Dukakis, Jackson is stressing the popular vote so far,
rather than the delegate race.
   ``Dukakis has 37 percent. We have 29 percent,'' he told the
Hollywood fund raiser.
   ``We're within striking distance. We will win this campaign
because hope has been reborn,'' he said.
   Dukakis' delegate lead is much larger than the popular vote gap,
with Jackson trailing him by more than 500 delegates, out of the
2,081 needed to win the nomination.
   In the past two days, Jackson began to make an issue of the
disparity although party rules allow for states to set up
delegate-selection systems that are not directly proportionate to
the popular vote.
   Jackson on Thursday urged that so-called super delegates and at
large delegates _ those not chosen by voters directly _ show
``fairness'' by committing to candidates who won the popular vote
in their congressional districts.
   Party officials should step in and make sure there is a
reasonable correlation betwen popular vote and delegates, he said.
He urged that super delegates not get on the Dukakis bandwagon
before the primaries are over.
   Jackson warned that his supporters may not vote for a Democrat
in November if they feel ``their vote does not count.''
   ``The most positive consequence of being fair is that people are
inspired ... When people are inspired and diligent, they work
diligently,'' he said. If they don't think they are treated fairly,
however, he said, ``they get discouraged.''
   Jackson said he was not seeking rule changes as he did in 1984,
but that he was instead talking of ``a matter of rule
interpretation.''
</TEXT>
