<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hostages-Kissinger     05-06 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostages-Kissinger,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kissinger Calls French Action On Hostages ``Disgraceful''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger
called it ``disgraceful'' that the French government reportedly
made concessions to Iran to win the release of three hostages in
Lebanon.
   Kissinger said Thursday that France's action ``raises the risk
for all other nationalities ... because now the Iranians will
undoubtedly believe that they can make similar deals with other
nations and it will be a gory extended effort to prove that they
can't.''
   French goverment officials denied they paid ransom for the
hostages' release but others accused the country of dealing with
terrorists while 18 other foreigners remain hostage. Reports said
that in exchange for the three Frenchmen, France agreed to pay the
outstanding balance on a loan originally totaling $1 billion made
by the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
   ``I think the French action today is disgraceful,'' Kissinger
said.
   He added that while it would it wouldn't feasible to engage in
economic reprisals against France, ``I would think that it should
effect those relationships over which we have some discretion.
   ``It certainly disappoints me severely that a French prime
minister, a conservative prime minister, would engage in such
actions,'' Kissinger said, referring to Premier Jacques Chirac.
   Kissinger appeared on ABC-TV's ``Nightline'' program along with
former National Security Adviser Robert McFarlane, who was involved
in the secret Iran-Contra negotiations to win the release of
Americans held in Lebanon, and Peggy Say, sister to American
hostage Terry Anderson. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent
for The Associated Press, is the longest-held hostage in Lebanon.
   McFarlane said there are no moderate officials to deal with in
Iran and that to ``literally deal with the devil for whatever
short-term gain it might get us would only encourage ... the taking
of more hostages.''
   Mrs. Say said that while it is easy to discuss theories of
foreign policy, ``my job has to be the voice for Terry Anderson and
the other hostages whose voices can't be heard.''
   ``These are American lives and it seems to me that there has to
be a better way,'' she said. ``I think there ... are better answers
than doing nothing and just literally turning our backs on these
men and saying, `We're sorry .. if they have to die but we have to
stop terrorism.'''
</TEXT>
