<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     05-06 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Signs From Dukakis Point To Fall Matchup With Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today began a short vacation from
the campaign trail after urging voters in Nebraska and West
Virginia to support him in Tuesday's primaries and his expected
fall campaign against George Bush.
   ``We are not conceding one state to the Republicans this fall,''
Dukakis said at his last campaign stop Thursday in Omaha, Neb.,
repeating a pledge he made earlier in West Virginia and again in
Indiana during a refueling stop.
   ``We have a very, very good chance of winning this election,''
the likely Democratic nominee said in Indiana, which gave him a big
primary victory last week. ``We will contest in every one of the 50
states.''
   The Massachusetts governor returned to Boston late Thursday. He
was to work at the statehouse today before taking the first weekend
off from campaigning since Christmas.
   Dukakis, known for his caution, had until Thursday been careful
to mention his continuing competition from Democrat Jesse Jackson.
But Dukakis began and ended his day Thursday with assaults on the
vice president and mentioned Jackson only as an afterthought.
   He repeatedly attacked Bush's assertion he would be the
``education president'' and also said Bush had sat by as the Reagan
administration allowed corporate raiders to engage in ``merger
mania'' that cost 500,000 jobs.
   After emerging from a tour of a coal mine in ecomomically
depressed West Virginia, Dukakis and United Mine Workers President
Rich Trumka said Reagan and Bush had turned their back on
struggling regions of the country.
   ``I believe very deeply that the president of the United States
has a responsibility to all people in all parts of the country,''
Dukakis told a group of miners. ``We need a president who
understands what economic leadership is.'' West Virginia has the
second-highest unemployment rate in the country.
   Inside the mine, Dukakis operated a huge machine and said he
would suggest building coal-fired power plants near the mines, with
the electricity to be sold to energy-dependent areas of the country.
   ``You don't need an evacuation plan when you build a coal-fired
plant,'' said Dukakis, who has blocked the opening of a nuclear
power plant in New Hampshire by refusing to submit a required
evacuation plan for Massachusetts communities within 10 miles of
the plant.
   Dukakis also said he hopes to receive ``good give-and-take''
from his Cabinet, another dig at Bush, who said Wednesday he
sometimes keeps quiet at White House meetings ``because I don't
want the president to have to be choosing between his vice
president and the other members of the Cabinet.''
   Dukakis scoffed at that stance.
   ``I have a lively Cabinet, and sometimes they get loud and
contentious,'' he said. ``That's the way you get good
give-and-take. ... I hope I'll have a vice president who speaks up
and speak out.''
   Earlier, Dukakis challenged Bush's claim that he would be an
``education president'' and said the White House must always be an
advocate for education _ ``not just during election years.''
   Although Dukakis has said he welcomes competition from Jackson,
he dropped his standard reference to Jackson from a line he
frequently uses to close his speeches.
   In recent weeks, Dukakis has marveled that the two remaining
Democrats are ``the son of Greek immigrants and a black man who
grew up poor in South Carolina.''
   But on Thursday he concluded his speech in Charleston by saying,
``The best America is a nation where, with your help, the son of
Greek immigrants can seek _ and win _ the presidency.''
   He delivered the same line again in Omaha and added: ``I believe
I will.''
   Also Thursday, the Dukakis campaign released federal tax returns
that showed the governor and his wife, Kitty, had joint income of
$108,957 last year and paid $25,892 in federal taxes.
</TEXT>
