<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Strike,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2,000 Strike in Textile Plant For Higher Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One-third of the 6,000-worker force
at a textile plant in the southern Kosovo province went on strike
and were demanding a 50-percent pay increase, the state Tanjug news
agency reported.
   The strikers, spinners and weavers at the plant in the town of
Djakovica, walked off the job Wednesday, the agency reported
Thursday.
   The plant's workers' council and municipal officials decided to
increase wages by 30 percent retroactive to April 1, but the
workers were not satisfied.
   The government lifts a price freeze on May 15, when prices are
expected to increase by up to 70 percent.
   Communist Yugoslavia was plagued by an unprecedented 150,000
strikes last year and the non-aligned nation is plagued by 170
percent inflation.
</TEXT>
