<HEAD>Family Farmer Would Be Dukakis Ag Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis says he would choose a family farmer as his secretary of
Agriculture.
   In an interview before a rally at the National Guard Armory,
Dukakis said the person whom he would choose to take the
Cabinet-level agriculture post would have plenty of hands-on
experience.
   ``I'm talking about somebody who knows what it means to farm and
earn a living,'' said the Massachusetts governor in a brief
campaign appearance Thursday.
   He said he would choose ``someone who understands the importance
of family farming, who could work with me and the Congress to help
shape an agricultural policy that emphasizes the importance of
family farmers.''
   Dukakis said his farm policy would differ from the Reagan
administration's, which he said ``seems to suggest they favor a
totally free economy.''
   ``I don't know anybody who knows anything about farming who
thinks you can do that. We are going to need a combination of
supply management and reasonable price supports in the foreseeable
future.''
