<HEAD>Mexican-American Parade and Jackson Appearance OK</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials say Democratic presidential
candidate Jesse Jackson can be the grand marshal of an annual
Mexican-American parade without threatening public funding of the
event as long as organizers agree in writing by noon today that it
is not a partisan political rally.
   The Mission Economic and Cultural Association, organizers of
Saturday's Cinco de Mayo parade, which celebrates the Mexican
army's defeat of invading French forces in Mexico in 1862, agreed
Wednesday it would make a ``good faith effort'' to keep partisan
politics out of the event.
   ``We agree with it in principle,'' said Roberto Hernandez,
director of the Mission association. ``The fine tuning we'll have
to work out.''
   ``People have a right to come with signs or T-shirts (bearing
Jackson's name or likeness) or whatever, as long as it isn't part
of officially sanctioned activities,'' said Kary Schulman, director
of The City Grants for the Arts program.
   She added that the Mission association must agree that it would
not sanction signs or banners and that no partisan speeches will be
made. If so, about $11,000 in city funds from a local hotel tax
will be available to cover the parade's costs.
