<HEAD>Mrs. Dukakis Works Behind the Scenes to Spruce Up Public Places</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts first lady Kitty Dukakis, wife of
the Democratic presidential front-runner, was paid $20,000 last
year for her part-time position as director of a novel program at
Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
   According to tax documents made public Thursday, Mrs. Dukakis'
earnings accounted for nearly one-fifth of the total 1987 joint
income of $108,957 she and Gov. Michael Dukakis reported.
   Mrs. Dukakis was the founder in 1985 of the Program on Public
Space Partnerships, a department of the Kennedy School that tries
to bring together business, government and neighbors in cooperative
projects to spruce up the appearance of public places. As director,
she draws a half-time salary of $20,000 annually.
   According to Renee Robin, the program's executive director, Mrs.
Dukakis approached Kennedy School Dean Graham Allison in 1985,
expressing her ``long-standing concern over the deteriorating
condition of public spaces in Massachusetts, ranging from downtown
plazas to larger conservation areas.''
   The department was established late in 1986, and Mrs. Dukakis
earned $2,500 from the job in that year.
