<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Obit-Caliguiri 1stLd-Writethru a0475 05-06 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Obit-Caliguiri, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pittsburgh Mayor Dies After Battle With Rare Disease</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates and expands throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard S. Caliguiri, mayor of Pittsburgh
since 1977, died early today at a hospital, according to the
Allegheny County Coroner's Office. He was 56 years old.
   The mayor died at 1:36 a.m. of cardiac amyloidosis, a rare,
incurable disease which deposited dangerous amounts of protein in
his heart and other major organs, according to the coroner's office.
   Caliguiri was taken to Shadyside Hospital around 12:45 a.m. A
paramedic pounded on the mayor's chest and tubes had been inserted
into his mouth, according to the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.
   Paramedics were called to the mayor's home at 12:10 a.m., the
newspaper said. He was carried from his home about a half-hour
later on a stretcher.
   The mayor's wife Jeanne, and one of his sons, followed the city
ambulance carrying Caliguiri to the hospital, the newspaper said.
   Caliguiri stunned Pittsburgh in October when he disclosed that
he suffered from the non-contagious disease whose cause is unknown.
   Caliguiri became aware that something was wrong with him in
March 1987 when he became dizzy while playing golf. After tests,
doctors determined Caliguiri suffered from the disease but nothing
was said publicly until later that year.
   Last summer, friends and political acquantainces began to notice
that Caliguiri, who was short in stature, looked pale and even
thinner than his normal weight of 140 pounds.
   For a while, he dismissed concern by saying it was only an
intestinal ailment, but finally on Oct. 2, he revealed the true
nature of his illness.
   On Dec. 24, 1987, surgeons at Shadyside Hospital inserted a
pacemaker in Caliguiri's chest to regulate his heartbeat.
   Earlier this week, Dr. James O'Toole, Caliguiri's cardiologist,
said he was evalutaing the possibility ofa heart transplant for the
mayor.
   Caliguiri, a Democrat, first became mayor of Pittsburgh in 1977.
   In addition to his wife, Caliguiri is survived by two sons,
Gregg and David.
</TEXT>
