<DOCNO> AP880506-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brown-Courses     05-06 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brown-Courses,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brown Reverses 19-Year-Old Decision, Adds Course Requirements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brown University has added two more
courses to the number required for graduation, partially reversing
a 19-year-old move to make its curriculum more flexible.
   Students in the Ivy League school's class of 1993 will be
required to pass 30 courses to qualify for a bachelor's degree,
Robert Reichley, vice president for university relations, said
Thursday.
   The current system was adopted as part of a wide-ranging
curriculum reform in 1969. The ``New Curriculum'' cut the
graduation requirement from 32 to 28 courses and abolished
distribution requirements and the grade of ``F.''
   A student who fails a course at Brown does not receive credit
for the course, but the failure is not recorded on his or her
transcript.
   The reforms were intended to allow students to experiment by
taking courses in areas outside their major fields of study without
worrying about failure. Students still paid for 32 courses, but
could fail four without penalty.
   Many students were not using the system as intended, according
to a study conducted by Dean Sheila Blumstein.
   Of the class of 1987, 44 percent took 30 or fewer courses, and
two-thirds of the students graduating with fewer than 32 courses
did not even register for 32, Blumstein found.
   Blumstein and Reichley said the change was essentially a
fine-tuning of the system and does not represent a major retreat.
   Reichley said the change has nothing to do with U.S. Education
Secretary William Bennett's well-publicized call for a return to
basics in U.S. higher education.
   Brown still does not require students to take specific classes
outside their majors or fulfill ``distribution requirements'' by
taking classes in several specified fields, Reichley said. Many top
schools do have those requirements.
   Brown officials have cited the 1969 reforms as one reason the
university has become among the nation's most popular and most
competitive.
   Blumstein said she thinks the tougher graduation requirement
will have little effect on Brown's popularity, and said students
seem to support it.
   The change brings Brown more into line with requirements at
other top universities.
   Harvard requires the equivalent of 32 semester-long classes for
graduation, while Yale requires 36. At Princeton, liberal arts
students are required to take 30 courses and complete a senior
thesis _ an option at Brown _ while engineers are required to take
36.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0502EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MethodistConference     05-06 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Methodist Conference,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Methodists Call, Narrowly, For Shell Boycott</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By a slim majority, United Methodist delegates
have called for a boycott of Royal Dutch-Shell petroleum products
until it pulls out of South Africa or apartheid is ended.
   ``Only with the support of international oil corporations can
the apartheid regime survive,'' said the church's governing
conference, asking members to refrain from purchasing Shell
products.
   The narrowly approved action _ by a vote of 475 to 418 _ came
after sharp debate late Thursday in which two Texans strongly
objected, saying Shell actively opposed apartheid and promoted
blacks in jobs, education and housing.
   Others argued for the move, saying ``oil was the fuel of
apartheid,'' and that the company, while verbally opposing
apartheid, did nothing effectively to end it.
   Apartheid is South Africa's system of law and custom which
establishes a racially segregated society in which 5 million whites
deny the nation's 26 million blacks any vote in national affairs.
   In a statement, the U.S. Shell Oil Company expressed
disappointment at the Methodists' action, saying thousands of its
employees who are Methodists ``will find it difficult to
understand.''
   Calling the action a ``discriminatory secondary boycott'' since
the U.S. company itself, a subsidiary, has no investments or
operations in South Africa, the company said:
   The ``individuals who will be hardest hit by a boycott against
Shell are the innocent American service station owners and jobbers
who sell Shell products.''
   As the 11-day conference of the 9.6-million church neared a
close Friday night, it refused to make more strict its rules for
overseeing behavior of clergy.
   It was proposed that the rules be changed to allow a minister to
be put on trial if he refused to cooperate in answering questions,
but this was rejected after opponents said it could lead to
``witch-hunt'' abuses.
   No mention was made in the debate of the case of the Rev. Julian
Rush, a part-time Denver pastor who admits his homosexuality but
refuses to say if he is actively so.
   That, if it were the case, would make him ineligible for the
clergy under church disciplines.
   The conference condemned ``interventions by more powerful
nations against weaker ones,'' declaring:
   ``These actions undermine international law, breed injustice,
frustrate the self-determination of peoples and are responsible for
untold human suffering.''
   Ihstead of military interventions, the church urged regional and
international negotiations and diplomatic efforts such as the
Contadora peace process in Nicaragua to settle disputes.
   Of the South African situation, the church pledged its own
efforts to end apartheid, calling it ``persistent disobedience to
the Word of God.''
   The denomination adopted a national quadrennial budget of $410
million, amounting to $13.50 annually per member. Most of their
contributions totalling $2.5 billion annually go to work of local
congregations and regional units.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0503EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Say-Hostages     05-06 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Say-Hostages,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage Sister: French Government Cares, U.S. Doesn't</HEAD>
<HEAD>With France-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATAVIA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of captive American journalist
Terry Anderson says the U.S. government has decided ``to let these
men die'' rather than to pursue the release of its hostages as the
French did.
   ``It almost appears that the French government places a higher
priority on the lives of their people,'' Peggy Say said Thursday.
   Three French hostages, including one who said he was a cellmate
of Anderson, were released Wednesday by their pro-Iranian captors.
High-ranking officials of the French government apparently
negotiated for their release.
   The U.S. government, however, refuses to negotiate with
terrorists as a matter of principle and joined Great Britain in
expressing hopes that the French did not make a deal for the
hostages.
   ``I find it rather embarrassing that they would call France to
task for making a deal in view of the fact that this government
sold arms to Iran in a poorly conceived initiative that might have
freed the hostages,'' said Mrs. Say, who has spoken out several
times on behalf of her brother and the eight other American
hostages believed held in Lebanon.
   ``I hope they pursue whatever channels the French used, but I
doubt they will,'' Mrs. Say said. ``I'm not a political wizard ...
but it seems to me that their rationale that they won't negotiate
because they want to bring an end to terrorism ... is irrational.
   ``What they are saying is that they know of no other solution to
this situation than to let these men die,'' she said.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, has been held since March 16, 1985, the longest of any
hostage.
   One of the freed French hostages, Marcel Fontaine, said he was
Anderson's cellmate and that he recently played chess and dominoes
with him.
   ``It's good to know Terry is alive, but I'm afraid this doesn't
necessarily mean anything will be forthcoming,'' Mrs. Say said from
her upstate New York home. She said she would fly to Paris this
weekend to meet with Fontaine.
   Earlier, Mrs Say said that the release of the French hostages
was encouraging because she might be able to learn from them about
her brother's condition.
   ``They must have talked and maybe he knows something about what
Terry is thinking,'' she said. ``I'm hoping he can give me some
indication of what I should do next.''
</TEXT>
