<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-06 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Market Down After Three-Day Holiday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost nearly half a yen on profit-taking
in Tokyo today as traders awaited the release of U.S. unemployment
figures, while stock prices also declined following a three-day
market holiday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues finished the day at 27,534.39, down 135.33 points,
or 0.49 percent, from Monday's close.
   The dollar, meanwhile, closed the day at 124.88 yen, down 0.45
yen from Monday's ending figure of 125.33 yen.
   Many participants were taking a wait-and-see stance toward the
dollar in anticipation of U.S. unemployment figures for April,
scheduled to be released later today, traders said. They said
profit-taking had contributed to the dollar's decline during the
day.
   The fall in the Nikkei index, the Tokyo stock market's main
barometer, came after four consecutive days of gains ending in a
record-high closing Monday, the last trading day before the
three-day ``Golden Week'' holiday break.
   ``Activity was slow after the holidays and reflected investor
caution over the earlier gains,'' said an official for a major
brokerage.
   The official, who declined to be named, said the market's
fundamentals nevertheless remained strong.
   Volume in the market's first section was 700 million shares, 200
million less than on Monday.
   ``The market reflected the overnight bearishness on Wall Street,
prompted by concern over U.S. inflation,'' said Masahiro Umemori,
an equity researcher at Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage.
   All banks, financial institutions, markets and most businesses
were closed in Japan Tuesday through Thursday because of national
holidays.
</TEXT>
