<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out in House Speaker's Office; No Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electrical fire that raged unimpeded for 10
minutes caused extensive damage in the Capitol Hill office of House
Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., whose offices are next door to
Wright's, said the fire which broke out shortly after 6 p.m.
Thursday was able to spread because of a lack of fire hoses and
alarms.
   Weldon, who is a former fire chief, said fire hoses which are
supposed to be in emergency cabinets throughout the building were
missing.
   ``We'd have had the fire out. We knew where it was, we were in
there, and we just couldn't get to it,'' he said ``I guarantee you
I'll raise Cain about it the next time we're in session, which I
guess is Monday.''
   Weldon said he had just formed a congressional fire caucus _ a
group of members concerned about fire prevention issues _ three
months ago, ``because America doesn't have a fire policy.''
   Two U.S. Capitol Police officers were treated for smoke
inhalation at the scene and District of Columbia Deputy Fire Chief
Jamelia Jackson estimated the damages to Wright's second-floor
corner office of the Longworth Building at $120,000.
</TEXT>
