<HEAD>Panel Approves Second-Year Funding For Bridges, Border Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a House subcommittee have approved
spending $63 million to reinforce the U.S. Customs Service presence
along the U.S.-Mexico border and improve bridge and border
stations, says Rep. Ron Coleman of El Paso.
   The funding package includes almost $28.7 million for the second
year of the three-year Southwest Border Improvement Program and $35
million to hire 500 new customs agents, Coleman's office said
Thursday.
   ``These projects are essential to improving the flow of trade
and commerce across the border, while at the same time providing
safe and secure facilities for Customs, Drug Enforcement
Administration and other law enforcement personnel at the border,''
Coleman said in a statement released by his office.
   The subcommittee on Treasury, Postal Service and General
Goverment, a part of the House Appropriations Committee, approved
the funding late Wednesday and Coleman said he is confident it will
clear Congress.
