<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Pool 1stLd-Writethru a0474 05-06 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Pool, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Escorts Kuwaiti Convoy In Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, `Iran said in...' with 1 graf to CORRECT
to Tuesday, sted of Wednesday. PICKS up 9th pvs, `Despite the...</NOTE>
<HEAD>EDITOR'S NOTE _ This story was filed by the Pentagon news pool.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS JACK WILLIAMS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new U.S. Navy-escorted
convoy sailed south in the Persian Gulf after Iran reasserted the
right to attack unarmed merchant ships as a tactic in its war with
Iraq.
   The Williams took over escort duty in the northern gulf from the
frigate USS Sides over two Kuwaiti-owned, American-flagged
80,000-ton oil tankers, the Chesapeake City and Ocean City.
   Operating under President Reagan's new orders to extend
protection to non-U.S. flagged ships, the 3,700-ton guided missile
frigate rendezvoused at midday Thursday with the Sides, which
cruised alongside the loaded tankers from Kuwait at the northern
edge of the gulf.
   Led by a Cobra attack helicopter scanning the seas for mines,
the Williams escorted the tankers as they headed for the Strait of
Hormuz at the southern end of the gulf on a two-day trip.
   No tag-alongs were spotted from the deck of the frigate, but the
three-thip convoy may find some. Neutral merchant ships frequently
seek safety in numbers in the gulf.
   Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke told a Pentagon media pool on the
Williams that the new rules will allow the 28 warships Washington
has sent to the region to protect any neutral ship attacked as long
as it was not carrying cargo for use by Iran or Iraq, who have been
at war for 7{ years.
   ``The master has to certify to us by radio that it is not
carrying any belligerent cargo before we can help,'' he said, as
one of several conditions.
   Iran said in a statement Tuesday that it is justified in firing
on unarmed merchant ships. Parliament speaker Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani was quoted in news reports as saying the raids were
conducted only against Iran's accomplices in the war.
   Despite the heated rhetoric, Iran has yet to test the new U.S.
policy afer its April 18 sea battles with U.S. forces that sank or
damaged six Iranian vessels.
   Officers aboard this ship, which played a key role in last
month's fighting, said they are worried most about running into an
underwater mine planted by Iran.
   ``They don't even have to lay them, just threaten to lay them,''
said Williams' captain, Cmdr. Edward Mann. All day Thursday,
crewmen took hourlong mine watch turns, tethered to keep them from
being hurtled overboard. With M-60 automatic weapons at the ready
they peered through high-powered binoculars from the bow of the
ship trying to spot mines ahead.
   Mann and other officers said they were not very concerned about
an NBC News report from Washington that quoted intelligence sources
as saying Iran was massing more than 100 speedboats near Hormuz for
a possible attack. Iran has used speedboats for attacks on ships in
the past.
   ``It could mean anything. Who knows what they are up to,'' said
one officer when asked about the report. Another officer dismissed
it, saying: ``They are likely to do anything, so your guess is as
good as mine.''
   Iran has threatened revenge for the April 18 battle.
   Adm. William J. Crowe, chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of
Staff, told the Pentagon pool earlier this week that Iran's threats
are still taken very seriously.
   No new mines have been found since the April 18 sea battle and
no engagements or harassments have been reported by the Navy.
   An officer said a mine captured last September from the Iran Ajr
warship cost only $500 to make because it was a simple model based
on a 1908 Russian mine.
   ``Five hundred bucks,'' he said. ``Not a bad return on your
investment. Five hundred dollars to blow a $500 million ship.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
