<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     05-06 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Claims Contra Attack Breaks Truce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government charged that
Nicaraguan rebels based in Honduras broke a 6-week-old cease-fire
with a speedboat attack on a military position.
   The Foreign Ministry also alleged Thursday that a CIA operation
based in Costa Rica published false documents to tarnish the image
of the leftist Nicaraguan government.
   Also Thursday, 42 striking workers ended a 10-day fast in
Managua after the government agreed to begin salary negotiations
Monday, union leaders said.
   In Honduras, military spokesman Manuel Suarez Benavides said six
dissident members of the Contras, as the Nicaraguan rebels are
known, detained earlier in the week were expelled from Honduras and
placed on a commercial flight Thursday to Miami. Relatives said
they have disappeared.
   In its first bulletin since Sandinista and U.S.-backed Contra
forces stopped offensive military operations on March 21, the
Defense Ministry said two Contra speedboats based at a Honduran
naval base in the Gulf of Fonseca fired machine guns and rifles at
military position Wednesday ``without obtaining results.''
   Sandinista troops retaliated by firing 57-mm cannon at the
boats, the ministry said. It provided no further details.
   There was no immediate comment from the rebels.
   Government and Contra representatives signed a temporary truce
on March 23, and a 60-day cease-fire began April 1. Two rounds of
negotiations in Managua have yielded no accord to end the
6{-year-old civil war.
   Alejandro Bendanda, secretary-general of the Foreign Ministry,
told a news conference Thursday that a clandestine CIA center in
San Jose, Costa Rica, had circulated at least eight false documents
recently, seeking to discredit the Sandinista government.
   In San Jose, a person answering the phone at the Costa Rican
government's Organization of Judicial Investigation said the agency
had no knowledge of any such activity. The person refused to give a
name.
   On Thursday afternoon, officials of the General Workers
Federation declared the 10-day hunger strike a success. The fast
``restored dignity to workers,'' said Alejandro Solarsano, a
federation leader.
   The 42 construction workers and car mechanics began the fast
April 25 to support a wage strike the union claims has been
supported by 4,500 workers since Feb. 25.
   Solarsano said four of those participating in the fast were
taken to a hospital for treatment.
   Federation director Carlos Salgado told a news conference that
the government had cut off water supplies to the federation
headquarters and prevented relatives of the strikers from bringing
medical supplies inside.
   Rolando Velasquez, secretary of labor relations for the
federation, said the workers would continue the job walkout ``until
the demands of the working class are obtained.''
   Sandinista police have detained more than 70 people since the
hunger strike began.
   In Miami, Marsha Lacayo, the wife of missing Contra adviser
Donald Lacayo, said there ``is no doubt'' that Contra military
commander Enrique Bermudez was responsible for the detainment of
the rebel officials.
   Some of the missing men had accused Bermudez of corruption.
Bermudez has been at the center of a bitter power struggle within
Contra ranks for several weeks.
   Bermudez on Thursday denied having any information about Lacayo,
Enrique Sanchez, Alejandro Montealegre, a rebel pilot identified
only as Waikita, Walter Calderon Lopez, known as Commander Tono, or
Tirzo Ramon Moreno, known as Commander Rigoberto.
   Manuel Suarez Benavides, a Honduran military spokesman, said
Thursday that the rebel officials were put on an Eastern Airlines
flight to Miami because ``the Contras must resolve their internal
affairs outside of our national territory.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0548EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bhopal     05-06 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bhopal,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Carbide Asks Judge To Remove Himself From Hearing Civil Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Union Carbide Corp. today asked
District Court Judge M.W. Deo to remove himself from hearing
India's $3 billion suit against the company for negligence in the
1984 Bhopal gas disaster.
   Lawyers for the Indian government and victims of the leak, the
world's worst industrial accident, criticized the move as a
delaying tactic.
   The request was made by Carbide lawyer Fali Nariman, who
contended in a petition that Deo showed bias by ordering on Dec. 17
that the corporation pay ``interim relief'' to victims before
ruling on the merits of the suit.
   ``The order was not only without jurisdiction but wholly
arbitrary, perverse and displays a complete pre-judgment,'' Nariman
said.
   Deo said the petition was unusual, since such requests normally
are made to a higher court. But he scheduled a hearing for June 16
on the matter.
   The court recesses Saturday for summer vacation and returns June
13.
   Nearly 3,000 people were killed and at least 20,000 seriously
injured when toxic methyl-isocyanate leaked from a pesticide plant
run by a subsidiary of Union Carbide in Bhopal on Dec. 3, 1984.
   Bhopal is the capital of the central Indian state of Madhya
Pradesh.
   Deo is the fourth judge in the case. The first was promoted to
the high court and the second withdrew after a serious auto injury.
The third judge, G.S. Patel, was transferred to another court by
the Indian government after it was disclosed that he had filed a
claim in the case.
   Vepa Sarthy, a lawyer for the Indian government, accused Union
Carbide of filing its petition ``with a view to delay the case.''
   Lawyer Vibhuti Jha, a court-recognized ``intervener'' on behalf
of voluntary relief organizations helping the gas victims, urged
the judge to reject Carbide's request. He described it as stalling.
   Deo's December order that Union Carbide pay interim relief to
the gas victims was upheld by the Madhya Pradesh High Court on
April 4. The High Court set the amount of payment at $192 million.
   Union Carbide earlier this week asked the High Court to review
its decision.
   The multinational company, with headquarters in Danbury, Conn.,
also faces criminal charges in connection with the gas leak.
   India contends the gas leak was caused by negligence. The
company has said it resulted from sabotage by a distruntled
employee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0621EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EverestDescent     05-06 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Everest Descent,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mountaineers Descend after Historic Everest Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Climbers from China, Japan and Nepal who staged a
successful rendezvous on Mount Everest's summit were making
progress today in descending the world's tallest peak, the
expedition's leader said.
   When nine of the climbers met on top of the world Thursday, they
achieved two mountaineering firsts: simultaneously scaling Everest
from two sides and making a live telecast from the summit.
   Three other expedition members later reached the summit.
   Shi Zhanchun, the expedition's leader and president of the
Chinese Mountaineering Association, told a news conference that
eight of the climbers who met on the 29,028-foot summit had reached
a camp at 27,224 feet on the north, or Chinese Tibetan, side of the
mountain this morning.
   He said the ninth had descended to 25,551 feet.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency also reported from Katmandu,
Nepal, that Cering Doje of Tibet, Noboru Yamada of Japan and Ang
Lhakpa Sherpa of Nepal reached a camp at 26,174 feet on the south,
or Nepalese, face of Everest.
   The three, who had climbed from the north side, and three others
who made the ascent from the south and were going down the north
face, are attempting to be the first to complete an
across-the-mountain climb.
   Shi said the climbers who met at the summit will not proclaim
victory until they have reached the 21,320-foot level. The descent
is treacherous and there is still danger of climbers suffering
frostbite, he said.
   The expedition is the largest ever to attempt to climb Everest,
with more than 200 people participating. The teams began their
assaults last month.
   Japan's Nihon Television Corp. engineered the alpine telecasts,
which have been beamed by satellite and televised in China, Japan
and Nepal. NTV has paid most of the cost of the $12.5 million
expedition.
   In Tokyo, an NTV spokeswoman said a nine-member group, including
three network cameramen, were scaling the mountain from the
northern side today, while three others climbed from the southern
side.
   She added that more expedition members planned to reach the
summit of the Himalayan peak that straddles the Nepal-China border.
She did not have further details.
   The expedition was staged to honor the 35th anniversary of the
first successful Everest assault, by Sir Edmund Hillary of New
Zealand and Tenzing Norgay, his sherpa guide, on May 29, 1953.
   The conquering of the mountain the Chinese call Qomolangma was
the top news story on television in Beijing and was the lead story,
with large pictures, on the front page of all major dailies today.
   Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping on Thursday telephoned a television
studio to congratulate the ``great pioneers'' of the three nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
