<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Stowaway-China     05-06 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stowaway-China,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stowaway Spends 15 Hours in Plane's Belly In Bold Freedom Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese man dressed in a ``dapper''
pinstriped suit stepped out of a cramped baggage container after a
15-hour flight to freedom from Beijing, astonishing airport
officials who said he was lucky to survive.
   ``All he wanted was political asylum and freedom,'' Ron Wilson,
community relations officer at San Francisco International Airport,
said Thursday. ``You would expect a guy to be dead when he
arrived.''
   Wilson said that instead of luggage, a baggage handler on
Wednesday found a nattily clad Cheng Guajun in the five-foot-square
storage container in the belly of a Boeing 747 belonging to the
official airline of China.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service district director David
Ilchert would not say whether the man asked for asylum. However, he
did say bilingual officers were interviewing him to find out his
intentions.
   ``He looked pretty dapper as soon as he got some fresh air,''
said Joseph F. Brandon, chief of investigations for the INS in San
Francisco. ``He seemed calm and collected in his thoughts. He
wasn't really emotional.''
   Cheng, 33, who said he ate a candy bar he brought with him for
the trip, told immigration investigators after he arrived Wednesday
that he had watched airport workers in China loading baggage into
the containers for several days before deciding to hide in one.
   Wilson characterized the plan as daring, but foolhardy, since
baggage compartments are not all pressurized and a person inside
one could die from exposure.
   The hold were the container was placed was a temperate 65
degrees. The cargo holds on a Boeing 747 can range from 38 up to 85
degrees, depending on the location in the plane.
   Cheng said he was employed as an accountant by a chemical
company in Tianjin, a major industrial city and port in northeast
China.
   Cheng reportedly told INS investigators he had not been able to
get a student visa to the United States because he could not prove
he had a financial sponsor here. Cheng said he has an uncle in Los
Angeles who would sponsor him.
</TEXT>
