<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FireArrest     05-06 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Arrest,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fighting Tears, Man Pleads Innocent To Fire That Killed 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One by one, the names of the 15 dead were
read aloud in court as a young man tearfully pleaded innocent to
murder and arson charges in a fire that engulfed a crowded rooming
house nearly four years ago.
   James Carver, a 24-year-old former truck driver, pleaded
innocent in an unsteady voice after each count. Once he broke down
in tears, holding up his arraignment Thursday for 15 minutes.
   The Ipswich man was ordered held on bail of $1 million surety or
$100,000 cash by Salem Superior Court Judge Peter Brady.
   Prosecutors allege that Carver set the July 4, 1984, predawn
fire, lighting gasoline-soaked newspapers in a doorway at the
Elliott Chambers boarding house in Beverly in a jealous rage over a
crumbling love affair.
   Jealous over his fiancee dating a tenant at the rooming house,
Carver set the fire that raced through the turn-of-the-century
wooden building, said Essex County District Attorney Kevin Burke.
   The blaze raged out of control for more than two hours. It
trapped six people in their rooms and killed others while they
tried to break down a locked exit. One man jumped from a
third-story window to his death and another man died several days
later in a hospital.
   Burke told reporters after the arraignment Carver's rival died
in the blaze, but he would not identify the man or name Carver's
then-fiancee. Burke said Carver later met his wife MaryJane, 21.
   Carver, indicted last week by an Essex County grand jury, was
arrested Wednesday as he drove from an Ipswich drug store with his
wife and their 6-week-old daughter Kaitlyn, who reportedly has
serious health problems.
   Burke said Carver had been a suspect during the four-year
investigation, but became the principal target last year after a
person revealed Carver had admitted to setting the fire. Burke
would not identify the source.
   Carver, who was identified in an April 21 police lineup ordered
by the grand jury, was reported to be outside the rooming house
around the time of the fire by several witnesses, Burke said.
   Defense attorney Dennis Jackson said Carver's parents have told
police their son was ill and asleep at their Danvers home the
morning of the fire.
   A pre-trial hearing is scheduled for May 23.
   If convicted, Carver faces a mandatory life sentence for each
murder count and up to 20 years for the arson charge.
</TEXT>
