<HEAD>Von Bulow Mansion Up Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oceanfront mansion where Claus von
Bulow allegedly tried to kill his heiress wife, Sunny, is up for
sale, a local real estate agent said.
   No price has been set for Clarendon Court, the 8.3-acre estate
on Newport's ``millionaires' row,'' Jacqueline Throop, manager of
real estate for Gustave J.S. White Real Estate Co., said Thursday.
She did not say whether there were any potential buyers.
   The estate, one of the last privately owned estates on Aquidneck
Island, includes a three-story stone main house, an 18-room
carriage house, three fountains, a swimming pool and a 1.3-acre
undeveloped lot sloping down toward Rhode Island Sound.
   According to tax assessors' records, the estate was assessed at
$1.4 million on Dec. 31, 1986. Tax assessor Allan Booth estimated
the current market value would be about double the assessed value.
   The estate is owned by Martha ``Sunny'' von Bulow, who purchased
it in 1970 for a reported $250,000 and spent another $600,000 to
renovate the mansion.
   Mrs. von Bulow has been in a coma since 1980. Her husband, Claus
von Bulow, was acquitted in 1985 of charges that he induced the
coma while trying to murder his wife with an insulin injection.
   Von Bulow agreed late last year to renounce all claims to his
wife's fortune, including the estate and the New York cooperataive
apartment where he had been living, in order to settle a lawsuit
filed against him by his stepchildren. He has announced plans to
move to Europe.
