<HEAD>Report: Prominent Chinese Dissident To Travel To U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fang Lizhi, China's most prominent dissident,
will be allowed to make his first trip to the United States to
attend a scholarly conference in December, a pro-Beijing newspaper
reported today.
   Fang was notified Thursday that officials approved his taking
part in an international symposium on the theory of relativity to
be held in Texas, the Chinese-language Wen Wei Po reported. The
dissident is a renowned astrophysicist who works at the Beijing
Observatory.
   The notice came a day after Fang made an electrifying public
appearance at Beijing University during which he advocated greater
democracy. He spoke to several hundred students at an informal
gathering.
   The scientist, an outspoken critic of China's socialist system,
said Wednesday that ``I never change my opinion'' on China's
politics or economy.
   Fang was forced to resign in early 1987 as vice president of the
Science and Technology University in Hefei, Anhui province.
Authorities claimed he incited pro-democracy student protests that
swept the country.
   Fang has been denied repeated requests to conduct research in
the United States. He has said he received invitations from several
American universities, including Harvard.
   The three-sentence dispatch in Wen Wei Po gave no other details
about Fang's possible U.S. trip. It said he would travel to
Australia in August.
