<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Rebels Believed Behind Two Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels killed a deputy
police commander and a retired sergeant today, police said. More
than 20 people have died in guerrilla clashes in the past three
days.
   Police said two assailants shot and killed retired police Sgt.
Feliciano Belandrez and Capt. Teofilo Tan, a deputy station
commander, in attacks three hours apart in Manila.
   Police said Belandrez was killed as he was leaving his home. Tan
had just returned from the night shift and was seated in front of
his house when two assailants approached.
   ``One guy even greeted him (Tan). He shouted `Captain!.' When
the captain replied, the man pulled out a .45 (caliber pistol) from
his waist and shot him twice in the head,'' said police Cpl. Johnny
Aguirre. ``The two walked casually after shooting him.''
   Police said they believed the assailants were members of the
communist New People's Army, which has been fighting the government
since March 1969.
   The guerrillas have killed more than 100 police and soldiers in
the capital since early 1987, police said.
   Military officials said nine soldiers were killed and eight
wounded Wednesday and Thursday after a military patrol stumbled on
a guerrilla training camp and fought about 400 rebels in the
mountain village of Umas in Negros Island, 350 miles southeast of
Manila.
   No rebel casualty figures were immediately available.
   Military reports said two other soldiers, eight rebels and a
military informant were also killed in clashes Wednesday on the
main island of Luzon, on the central Samar island and on Mindanao
in the south.
   The deputy chief of staff for intelligence told a civic group
that 1,291 people were killed in more than 1,200 ``insurgency
related'' incidents throughout the country this year.
   Brig. Gen. Galileo Kintanar said the dead included 584 rebels,
346 soldiers and 361 civilians.
