<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NewCaledonia     05-06 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Caledonia,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises To 21 in Cave Assault, Military on State of Alert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL DONNET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three more bodies were found around
an island cave where French soldiers rescued 23 hostages held by
Melanesian separatists in this French Pacific territory, officials
said today.
   The presumed chief of the captors, Alphonse Dianou, died of
wounds inflicted during Thursday's assault, the gendarmerie said.
His death and the discovery of the bodies of the three Melanesians
brought the death toll to 21.
   France's minister for overseas territories, Bernard Pons, said
the 7,000 army and gendarmerie personnel in New Caledonia were on a
state of ``absolute alert'' following the bloody rescue mission
that freed 22 gendarmes, police under military orders, and one
assistant prosecutor.
   The situation appeared calm today, but the Kanak Socialist
National Liberation Front, the main separatist group, called for a
24-hour mobilization Saturday to protest the attack on Ouvea, an
island in the Loyalty group northeast of Noumea, the capital.
   A front statement promised strikes in a ``day of active mourning
of the same level as the massacre on Ouvea.''
   Fifteen 15 separatists and two members of the assault team were
initially reported killed in the assault. Five other people were
injured.
   The front statement said the death toll showed the attack was
``premeditated butchery.''
   Pons, announcing the state of alert, said ``terrorists ... will
find themselves in front of entirely determined men.'' He did not
elaborate.
   Both Pons and conservative Premier Jacques Chirac have referred
to the front as a ``terrorist group.'' Pons has asked that the
front be outlawed, a position supported by Chirac. However,
President Francois Mitterrand, a Socialist, who would have to
approve such a decree, has expressed his disapproval.
   Chirac and Mitterrand are vying for the presidency in elections
on Sunday.
   Sources in the front's political bureau said that disrupting the
elections was not a question.
   The hostage-taking on Ouvea was in part to protest regional
elections held here April 24, the same day as first-round
presidential voting. The front boycotted the regional balloting.
   The front is seeking independence from France, which has ruled
New Caledonia since 1853.
</TEXT>
