<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-GasLeak     05-06 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Gas Leak,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ural Mountain Villagers Hospitalized With Gas Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A purification system failed at a gas refinery in
the Ural Mountains and released a cloud of hydrogen sulphide that
poisoned 52 people and contaminated a village beyond remedy, a
newspaper reported.
   Nine of the injured required hospitalization, the Sovietskaya
Rossiya daily said in its report Thursday.
   The leak occurred in Muzhichya Pavlovka, near Orenburg, and the
paper said the village's 844 residents would have to be resettled.
   The problem began with the failure in early March of a gas
purification unit, the article said. Then, on April 25, the duty
engineer noticed a compressor malfunction.
   ``The only right decision in that case was to stop pumping gas
to the refinery,'' the newspaper said. ``The refinery released gas
to burn instead, which, according to the local population, has been
the regular practice here.''
   K.I. Akulov, the Soviet health official, told the newspaper the
refinery near Orenburg and another in Astrakhan on the Caspian Sea
are dangerous to the public health and urged that corrective
measures be taken.
   ``Still, today, none of the sulfur purification systems are
operating at either refinery, nor do automatic control systems to
detect poisonous releases exist. The three-mile protective belt,
ordered in 1975, never was maintained around the refinery.''
   To make matters worse, the newspaper said, the ministry
responsible for relocating the villagers does not plan to do it
until 1990 or 1991.
</TEXT>
