<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0746EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Hayter 1stLd-Writethru a0518 05-06 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Hayter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famed Engraver and Painter Dies at 86</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT `Pollock' sted `Pollack'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Stanley Hayter, an English-born painter
sought by artists such as Pablo Picasso and Salvador Dali for his
innovative printmaking techniques, died of cardiac arrest at age
86, it was reported today.
   Hayter, who died Wednesday in Paris, was a leading figure in the
Paris art scene for more than half a century.
   The Paris-based International Herald Tribune said in today's
editions that Hayter was credited with turning engraving into a
lively and experimental form that brought many famous artists to
work alongside him in his studio in Montparnasse.
   Among those artists who visited him at his studio, known as
Atelier 17, were Alexander Calder, Marc Chagall, Jackson Pollock,
Dali and Picasso.
   Hayter was born in London in 1901 and graduated from Kings
College, London, with honor degrees in art and chemistry. He worked
in Iran from 1922 to 1925 for the Anglo-Iranian oil company but his
first interest was art.
   ``My father was a painter and a lot of people in my family
before, so I was messing about with painting fairly seriously when
I was a child. I was painting all the time when I was in the
(Middle) East,'' Hayter once said. ``I didn't do much with prints
till I came to Paris.''
   He quickly discovered and revolutionized the vanishing art of
original printmaking, bringing new techniques to the medium
including a method of color printing from a single plate instead of
having a separate plate for each tone.
   Hayter wrote two books that are essential reading for
printmakers, ``New Ways of Gravure'' (1949) and ``About Prints''
(1962).
   He lived in Paris from 1926 to 1939, then went to New York,
where he established his studio at the New School and gave an
impetus to American printmaking. He returned to Paris in 1950.
</TEXT>
