<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf of last item to CORRECT `Pollock' sted
`Pollack'; PM separates moved on Caliguiri as a0508, Rose as a0466,
and Hayter as a0531.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Richard Caliguiri</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Richard S. Caliguiri, who helped
transform Pittsburgh from a sickly steel town to a vital corporate
center, died early Friday of a rare heart disease after more than a
decade in office. He was 56.
   The mayor died of cardiac amyloidosis, according to the
Allegheny County Coroner's Office and a hospital spokesman. The
incurable disease deposits dangerous amounts of protein in the
heart and other major organs.
   As City Council president in 1977, he took over as interim mayor
when then-Mayor Pete Flaherty joined the Carter adminstration, then
ran as an independent and narrowly beat the popular Democratic
candidate for the office.
   Caliguiri was sworn in April 10, 1977, as the 53rd mayor of
Pittsburgh. He won re-election twice by landslides during a period
in which the region lost more than 75,000 jobs and had unemployment
rates as high as 19 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>George Rose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUERTO PLATA, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British actor George
Rose, who won Broadway's Tony award for ``My Fair Lady'' and
``Drood,'' died when his car swerved into a ditch and flipped over
in this Caribbean resort, police said. He was 68.
   Rose made his Broadway debut in 1946 in a production of ``Henry
IV,'' but first drew national attention in ``A Man for All
Seasons'' in 1961.
   His later roles included ``The Royal Hunt of the Sun'' (1965);
the 1968 and 1972 revivals of ``My Fair Lady''; ``My Fat Friend''
(1974); ``The Kingfisher'' (1978); ``Peter Pan,'' ``The Pirates of
Penzance'' and ``The Mystery of Edwin Drood.''
   Rose's first movie appearance was in the British-made film
version of Charles Dickens' ``The Pickwick Papers'' in 1952. He
went on to play character role in more than 30 films, including ``A
Night To Remember'' (1958); ``Hawaii'' (1966); and ``A New Leaf''
(1971).
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Wladimir Zarotschenzeff</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wladimir Zarotschenzeff, a Russian emigre
whose caviar and gourmet food distributorship is the largest on the
West Coast, died Thursday. He was 84.
   Zarotschenzeff, who was known to longtime clients as Mr. Zee,
began his distributorship in his garage and parlayed it into the a
business that supplied hotels and restaurants with caviar.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Sterling Powell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sterling Powell, the New Jersey
welterweight boxing champion in 1934, died Wednesday. He was 78.
   Powell fought throughout the 1930s and 1940s under the name
``Six Second'' Powell, a nickname he got by knocking out his first
professional opponent six seconds into the fight.
   Powell never fought for a national crown during a career in
which he said he lost about 30 of his 118 professional bouts. He
sparred with boxing champions Sugar Ray Robinson and Rocky
Graziano. Powell also played for several years with the Colored
Stars, a traveling baseball team.
   After his fighting career ended, Powell worked in the
construction industry and was a member of the Labor Industrial
Union of North Amercia.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Hayter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Stanley Hayter, an English-born painter
sought by artists such as Pablo Picasso and Salvador Dali for his
innovative printmaking techniques, died Wednesday of cardiac arrest
at age 86.
   Hayter was a leading figure in the Paris art scene for more than
half a century. The Paris-based International Herald Tribune said
Hayter was credited with turning engraving into a lively and
experimental form that brought many famous artists to work
alongside him in his studio in Montparnasse.
   Among those artists who visited him at his studio were Alexander
Calder, Marc Chagall, Jackson Pollock, Dali and Picasso.
   Hayter was born in London in 1901 and graduated from Kings
College, London, with honor degrees in art and chemistry. He worked
in Iran from 1922 to 1925 for the Anglo-Iranian oil company but his
first interest was art.
   Hayter wrote two books that are essential reading for
printmakers, ``New Ways of Gravure'' (1949) and ``About Prints''
(1962).
</TEXT>
