<HEAD>Tass Reports Breakup Of Polish Strike, Soviets `Regret' Polish
Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio Moscow reported today that work had resumed
at the steel mill in southern Poland where state-run media had
reported that police broke up a strike.
   On Thursday, a government spokesman said the Kremlin regrets the
labor unrest confronting its ally.
   Later Thursday, the official Tass news agency reported that
plainclothes Polish agents entered the Lenin steelworks in the
Krakow suburb of Nowa Huta before dawn ``to restore order, to
enable the majority of the labor collectives to resume work and to
prevent further damage to the national economy.''
   It said the strike was broken up without ``incidents,'' and that
strike committee members were detained. The agency did not mention
the lockout at the Lenin shipyard in Poland's Baltic port of Gdansk.
   Today's editions of the Communist Party daily Pravda carried the
Tass report on page seven.
   Radio Moscow, without mentioning the situation in Gdansk or Nowa
Huta, reported at noon Thursday that 61 percent of the people
surveyed in Poland thought a strike wave that broke out there April
25 would damage the economy.
   At a regular news briefing Thursday, Foreign Ministry spokesman
Gennady I. Gerasimov was asked about the unrest and said: ``We
regret that such events take place in Poland.''
   He declined to say whether Soviet officials had offered advice
or suggestions to the Polish government about the situation.
   Polish workers are seeking pay increases of up to 60 percent to
offset prices that have gone up 42 percent so far this year.
   The strikers in Gdansk and Nowa Huta also demand reinstatement
of free trade unions and fired union activists and the release of
political prisoners.
   Poland's communist authorities have said the price increases are
necessary to straighten out Poland's economic problems and the
strikes damage the reform effort.
   Pravda on Wednesday accused ``anti-Polish centers'' in the West
and domestic dissidents of trying to exploit the unrest in Poland.
   Before Polish authorities stifled the Solidarity free trade
union movement with the December 1981 imposition of martial law,
Soviet troops had massed on Poland's border and there was
speculation they might intervene.
</TEXT>
