<HEAD>12 Dead, 30 wounded in Palestinian Clashes, Shiite Shooting,
Cinema Bombing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more casualties, four Shiites
killed in separate attacks. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Palestinian factions battled with
mortars, rockets and machine guns in west Beirut's devastated
Chatilla refugee camp today. Police said six people were killed and
30 wounded.
   In a separate attack, four Shiite militiamen of Justice Minister
Nabih Berri's Syrian-backed Amal movement were killed in Beirut's
southern slums by unidentified gunmen in a speeding car. Amal
blamed a rival Shiite faction.
   Two other people died and five were wounded when a bomb exploded
Thursday night in a movie theater in Beirut's Syrian-policed Moslem
sector, police reported.
   It was the third cinema bombing in west Beirut in two weeks. Two
people were wounded in the earlier blasts.
   A police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
fundamentalist Moslem factions were believed to be behind the
bombings to force amusement centers to close during the Moslem
fasting month of Ramadan.
   The fighting in Chatilla between guerrillas of Palestine
Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction and a
rival Syrian-backed group known as Fatah-Uprising began shortly
after dusk Thursday and still was raging today.
   Each side pounded the other's positions with 82-mm mortars,
106-mm recoilless cannon, heavy machine guns and rocket-propelled
grenades, police said.
   It was not known what touched off the fighting, the second
outbreak of violence in Chatilla this week.
   At least eight fighters were killed and 43 wounded Monday in the
first major clash between the two factions since Arafat's
reconciliation meeting with Syrian President Hafez Assad in
Damascus two weeks ago.
   Fatah, the main group within the PLO, overran most of the rival
faction's positions in Chatilla in that clash and seized control of
the camp.
   In the south Beirut violence, Amal accused the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God, of killing the four militiamen.
   Police said Amal militiamen besieged the main Hezbollah barracks
in Beirut shortly after the shooting, but there were no immediate
reports of any more violence.
   Amal crushed Hezbollah in Shiite-dominated south Lebanon in
April. Sixty-two people were killed and 150 wounded in four days of
fighting.
   That was a major setback for the fundamentalist Hezbollah's aim
of setting up an Iranian-style Islamic republic in Lebanon.
   Hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella group for Shiite
factions holding 18 foreign hostages in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
