<HEAD>Workers Expand Area Of Search For Remains Of U.S. Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Laotian team has expanded its
search on a remote Laotian hillside for the remains of two American
fliers shot down in 1966, U.S. officials said today.
   The 14-man U.S. military team is cooperating with Laotian
government officials in the third joint excavation of a U.S.
warplane crash site. The searchers are trying to account for 555
Americans who didn't return home from Laos during the Indochina war.
   The team flew to Laos Tuesday to search the brush- and
bamboo-covered area of southern Savannakhet province, where an
OV-1A Mohawk was downed by heavy ground fire on March 15, 1966.
   The U.S. Embassy in Bangkok said it received an undated message
from the team saying the search site had been expanded from 4-by-11
yards to 40-by-60 yards.
   ``No explanation was given, but it is assumed that the team
discovered material from the plane ... outside the presumed
original 4-by-11-yard primary impact area,'' the statement said.
   ``The joint U.S.-Laotian team has removed brush from the lower
half of the search area and has begun to examine it for material
and remains from the plane,'' it said.
   The excavation is expected to be completed early next week.
   The American team is from the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution
Center and the Army Central Identification Laboratory,
Honolulu-based agencies entrusted with resolving the fates of
Americans missing in foreign wars. It is led by Lt. Col. Joe Harvey.
   Maj. Tim Pfister, a spokesman for the U.S. Pacific Command, said
the Mohawk was involved in a mission to block the western portion
of the Ho Chi Minh Trail, which North Vietnam used to infiltrate
men into U.S.-backed South Vietnam.
