<HEAD>Fired Mayoral Aide Says Others Plotted Against Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer says he'll call a conference
of community and religious leaders to ``heal our wounds'' after a
five-day controversy that led to an aide's firing because of
racist, anti-Semitic remarks.
   Sawyer dismissed Steve Cokely on Thursday under mounting
pressure from the City Council and community groups. The mayor said
he acted after consulting with a ``broadly-based, multiracial
group.''
   ``As mayor, I will not tolerate any racial divisiveness from any
employee,'' Sawyer said. ``I'm sensitive, and I heard from a lot of
people, and I took time to work through the process.''
   At issue in the controversy were statements Cokely made in a
series of lectures from 1985 through 1987. They were tape-recorded
and made available for sale at a store run by followers of Nation
of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan.
   Cokely, the mayor's special projects coordinator, said in the
lectures that doctors, ``especially Jewish ones,'' were infecting
blacks with AIDS and other diseases. Cokely, like Sawyer, is black.
   He also called Christopher Columbus a ``Hispanic Jew'' who
brought slaves to America and said Columbus Day was a ``white
supremacist holiday.'' Cokely also labeled the Christian cross a
``symbol of white supremacy.''
   The 35-year-old aide, whose remarks were made public in weekend
newspaper reports, apologized Monday, and Sawyer said then he had a
talk with the aide to ``rehabilitate Steve.''
   However, the mayor, who had been told by Jewish leaders weeks
ago about Cokely's remarks, came under fire for his delay in taking
action.
   ``It was my thought that Steve Cokely should have been
terminated immediately,'' said Alderman Timothy Evans, one of the
mayor's political opponents. ``It was not done ... and it was a
mistake.''
   At a rally Thursday night after his firing, Cokely told about
150 cheering supporters that he was dismissed from the
$35,000-a-year job because he was getting too powerful.
   ``There was a plot to force me to resign,'' Cokely said.
   Mayoral aide Monroe Anderson described Cokely as ``a gofer'' who
``goes to groups in the black community, listens, sometimes talks
and then reports to the mayor about the concerns of those groups.''
