<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0914EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ColdWomen     05-06 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cold Women,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iron Deficiency May Explain Why Some Women Often Feel Cold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers who put swimsuit-clad women
in drafty rooms and dunked them in cool water say women who often
complain of the cold may be consuming too little iron.
   ``If you are cold a lot of the time or cold when other people
aren't, then you might have a physician check your blood iron
levels,'' said Pennsylvania State University nutritionist John L.
Beard.
   Physiologist Henry Lukaski, who conducted another study linking
iron deficiency to feelings of chilliness among women, said women
should ask their doctors to test blood levels of an iron-carrying
protein called ferritin, a more accurate indicator of mild iron
deficiency than measurement of hemoglobin, the iron-containing
protein that makes blood red.
   Beard and Lukaski, of the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Human
Nutrition Research Center in Grand Forks, N.D., presented their
studies Thursday at the annual meeting of the Federation of
American Societies for Experimental Biology.
   Lukaski said men also can feel cold due to iron deficiency, but
far fewer do so than women. Men tend to get more iron because they
eat more, while women lose iron through menstruation, he said.
   He said women who suffer mild iron deficiency should eat more
lean red meat and other high-iron foods, including fish, poultry,
beans, beets and leafy green vegetables, and should drink orange
juice to enhance iron uptake.
   Iron-rich foods are preferable to iron supplements because
organic iron is more readily absorbed by the body than inorganic
iron supplements, Lukaski said. However, Beard said, iron
supplements are practical and adequate if taken over a long time.
   Beard's study compared eight women who were very iron-deficient
with 10 women who had normal iron levels. Both groups had equal
percentages of body fat, and the experiment was designed to
eliminate bias caused by differences in diet and menstrual cycle.
The women were submerged up to their necks for 100 minutes in
82-degree water, 16.6 degrees below normal body temperature.
   Beard found the iron-deficient women's body temperatures dropped
an average of 1.25 degrees Fahrenheit compared with a drop of
three-fourths of a degree in the normal women.
   Thyroid hormone, which increases body metabolism to produce
heat, didn't increase as much in the iron-deficient women as in the
others. Iron-deficient women also used 13 percent less oxygen,
indicating they generated less body heat.
   But after the anemic women took iron tablets for 12 weeks to
reverse their condition, all the differences vanished.
   Lukaski and USDA scientist Clint Hall had six women wear
two-piece bathing suits and sit in a room with a cool draft on two
occasions.
   The first time, after eating an low-iron diet for 80 days, the
women started to shiver after an average of 84 minutes.
   Then the women ate a diet with almost the recommended daily
amount of iron for 84 days, followed by iron supplements for 16
days. The women shivered after an average of 92 minutes.
   Lukaski also found that when the women were iron-deficient,
their body temperatures fell about 1.1 degrees, compared with
one-half a degree after they ate the diet with more iron.
   In addition, the women produced more thyroid hormone and two to
three times more norepineprine when they had adequate iron.
Norepinephrine is a stress hormone that tells the body to produce
heat, Lukaski said.
   He said previous studies found about 30 percent of American
women don't get enough iron. The recommended daily amount is 18
milligrams for women who menstruate, and 15 milligrams for men and
for older women.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0916EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Webster 1stLd-Writethru a0467 05-06 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Webster, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CIA Chief Questions Indictments of Foreign Leaders</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 4-5, Meanwhile the Wall, with Reagan ordering
CIA to use clandestine means against Noriega.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CIA Director William Webster says he questions
the wisdom of indicting foreign leaders such as military strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega of Panama on drug charges, according to an
interview published today.
   ``There has to be some advance thinking about where these
actions take us and whether they do in fact help the drug
enforcement counter-narcotics program or create some confusion,''
the former FBI chief and federal judge told The Washington Times.
   ``What do we intend to do with these indictments?'' he asked.
``Do we intend to pursue extradition? Are we going to seek to
overthrow by whatever means we have _ economic, military, political
_ as a result of the indictment?''
   Meanwhile, The Wall Street Journal reported today that President
Reagan has ordered the CIA to begin using clandestine radio
broadcasts, leaflets and rumormongering against Noriega.
   The CIA agreed to undertake the propaganda campaign after the
agency rejected State Department propopals for financial or
paramilitary aid to anti-Noriega forces, the newspaper said. Even
before the new program gets going, it said, its launching is being
complicated by the Pentagon's refusal to let the CIA use U.S.
military bases to broadcast anti-Noriega messages.
   Noriega faces federal drug charges in Florida, but negotiations
aimed at getting him to step down include arrangements not to seek
his extradition.
   Still, Webster said he has confidence that Noriega ``can be
persuaded _ if that's the nice word for it _ induced to step down
if the current pressures are not significantly relaxed and other
pressures are considered.''
   When asked if U.S. policy had failed in Panama, he said: ``I
don't think it's lost. The only thing that's going to get lost is
maybe some `face' of those who made wild predictions that he would
roll over and play dead the first time we barked at him.''
</TEXT>
