<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0918EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AtlantaArchbishop     05-06 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Atlanta Archbishop,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta's New Archbishop's Installation Draws Eminent Clergy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new leader of northern Georgia's Roman
Catholics promised them his status as the nation's first black
archbishop would not hamper his relationship with his mostly white
parishioners.
   ``There can be no escaping the fact that I am the first black
bishop to serve in Atlanta and the first black archbishop in the
nation,'' Archbishop Eugene A. Marino told the thousands of people
attending his installation Mass Thursday.
   ``Having noted that, I hasten my deep personal conviction that
it need not affect the quality of my ministry among you nor the
nature of our relationship with each other,'' he said, prompting
prolonged applause.
   The Archdiocese of Atlanta covers 69 counties in north Georgia,
with a Catholic population of about 156,000, including about 10,000
blacks. Only two of the approximately 200 priests in the
archdiocese are black; about five of the 65 parishes are
predominantly black.
   Many of the nation's highest ranking Roman Catholic leaders
attended Thursday's Mass, including Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of
Chicago, Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston and retired Cardinal John
Krol of Philadelphia.
   In addition, more than 800 clergy, including nearly 100 Roman
Catholic bishops, were present, prompting Archbishop Pio Laghi,
Pope John Paul II's representative in the United States, to say the
support showed ``that the selection made by the Holy Father has
been the right one.''
   The overflow crowd at the Atlanta Civic Center warmly received
Marino, a native of Biloxi, Miss., applauding as he entered the
hall and interrupting his homily several times with more applause.
   ``I come to you today with neither pretense nor apology,''
Marino said.
   ``Like so many of you, I am a Southerner. My roots go deep into
the rich, brown soil of Mississippi and back to Puerto Rico and
Africa. I was born and raised in the Deep South, the old South with
its curious mixture of aristocratic gentility and gracious
hospitality on the one hand and racial segregation on the other,''
Marino said.
   ``Although at times embarrassed, today I am unashamed from
whence I have come. The experience of the old South has profoundly
influenced all of us, black and white. Suffering through that
experience has laid the foundation of the New South so beautifully
and dramatically typified by this city. Today I happy to be a
citizen of Atlanta.''
   Among the local leaders attending the Mass were Coretta Scott
King and Martin Luther King III along with other relatives of the
late Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.; and Mayor Andrew Young, himself a
Congregationalist minister.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
