<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   05-06 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0486,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Party Overtake Thatcher's Conservatives In Local Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with later results; CORRECT
number of centrist councils to six, sted eight. Pick up 9th pvs:
`Critics charge...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The socialist Labor Party made strong gains in
local balloting and overtook Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservatives in the first electoral test of her third-term
program, returns indicated today.
   The election Thursday was fought on the national issues of a
Thatcher-inspired shakeup of the welfare system this spring and
plans for a new property tax. Property taxes, together with central
government grants, fund local governments.
   ``The results are a major rebuff to the government's policies.
The country has said, enough is enough,'' said Labor Party general
secretary Larry Whitty after the day-long balloting Thursday.
   The Labor Party kept major prizes including Birmingham,
Britain's second-largest city, and the Scottish capital, Edinburgh.
It also took control of the university city of Cambridge.
   With results declared from 207 of the 211 local governments
contested in the day-long ballot, Labor had net gains of 107 seats.
The Conservatives had lost three and the centrists lost 74, the
British domestic news agency Press Association calculated.
   The Conservatives had control of 48 of the contested cities and
towns, up seven; Labor had 97, up six; and the centrist Social
Democratic and Liberal Party had six, unchanged.
   The rest were controlled by independents, Scottish natonalists
or had no party with overall control.
   Despite the apparent edge to Labor, the Conservatives posted
gains in the prosperous south and captured seven city councils no
one party had controlled previously.
   The big loser was the third-place Social and Liberal Democratic
Party. It was formed in March to merge the centrists, but a
breakaway faction remains a separate party.
   Critics charge that Mrs. Thatcher is going too far with
right-wing policies and the latest moves on welfare and taxes are
unfair to the poor.
   A British Broadcasting Corp. computer analysis showed that Labor
took 39 percent of the vote, a nine-point jump since the June
general election, while the Conservatives had 37 percent, five
points down, and the centrists with 18 percent suffered a
four-point drop.
   Environment Secretary Nicholas Ridley said that, considering the
controversy over the welfare and property tax changes, the Tories
did ``rather well.''
   David Steel, Social and Liberal Democratic Party co-leader,
said: ``I'm not pretending we've done well. But it has been an
awfully difficult year for us.''
   The election, in which about 20 million Britons were eligible to
vote, involved about 4,000 seats that were last contested in 1984.
   One-third of seats on the local authorities in England and Wales
and the entire councils in the 53 Scottish districts were at stake.
There were no elections this year in London and Northern Ireland.
   The Conservatives, humiliated in Scotland in the June general
election, again failed to make headway there. They remained in
control of just a handful of small councils in Scotland, while
Labor added the major city of Aberdeen to its collection of
Scottish victories.
   The welfare changes are part of an ambitious program by Mrs.
Thatcher to end what the Conservatives term Britain's ``dependency
culture'' nutured by the welfare state.
   Under the new property tax, now having a rough ride through
Parliament, taxes would be levied on each individual adult in a
household.
   Under the old system, the tax was levied only on each individual
property, regardless of how many people lived there. The new
flat-rate system, dubbed a poll tax by critics, will treble the
bill for some households.
   Mrs. Thatcher believes that making everyone pay will bring home
the cost of electing left-wing local authorities, the big spenders.
</TEXT>
