<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Bing     05-06 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Bing,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Held to Determine Whether Bing Marriage Should Be Annulled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ailing opera impresario Rudolf Bing was abused
and prevented from getting proper care by his wife, according to
witnesses at a hearing to determine whether she should be thrown
out of his home.
   Bing's lawyer has asked a judge to annul the Bings' January 1987
marriage, claiming the 86-year-old former Metropolitan Opera
leader, who has Alzheimer's disease, didn't know what he was doing
when he married her.
   But first, at Thursday's hearing, the lawyer, Paul Goldhamer,
asked judge Carmen Ciparick to remove 48-year-old Carroll Bing from
the couple's apartment because she is a danger to her husband.
   Mrs. Bing frequently disrupted the hearing by trying to take
Bing from the courtroom and yelling that witnesses were lying. A
court in Washington has declared her mentally incompetent to handle
her affairs.
   A restaurant captain, Enrico Caruso, said Mrs. Bing once threw a
glass of water at Bing because he wanted to dine with longtime
friend Margaret Gilbert.
   Annette Maggio, guest relations manager at the Essex House, said
she saw Mrs. Bing shake her husband roughly by his shoulders when
his court-appointed conservator, Paul Guth, tried to speak to him.
   ``Don't you know they're trying to separate us?'' Ms. Maggio
quoted Mrs. Bing as screaming.
   Bing's night nurse, Alice Brennan, said the elderly man has had
only two baths in the past two months, because Mrs. Bing did not
allow nurses near him.
   ``Carroll was constantly saying that we (the nurses) were trying
to take her man,'' Mrs. Brennan said.
</TEXT>
