<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CookieMisfortune     05-06 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cookie Misfortune,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Scout Cookies Don't Clear Japanese Customs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Brownie troop's hopes of shipping
more than 400 boxes of Girl Scout cookies to sailors aboard a U.S.
aircraft carrier are crumbling after Japanese customs officials
blocked the delivery.
   ``I don't think it's fair,'' 8-year-old Nickelle Clark said
Thursday. ``I'm mad.''
   She sold more than 500 boxes of cookies this year, including
some to a sailor aboard the USS Midway who had written to say he
missed the annual treat.
   Troop 807 leader Manchetta White said a $2,000 duty tax
prevented the cookies from clearing customs and going to 35
servicemen who ordered them.
   American Airlines officials are trying to figure out what to do
with 402 boxes of Girl Scout cookies piled up in the back of their
ticket office here.
   The airline offered free passage for the cookies to the crew of
the carrier, which is based in Atsugi, Japan. They were shipped
April 26 but were returned after four days in a Japanese customs
warehouse.
   Jean Titus, American Airlines' general manager in Corpus
Christi, said she's working with American Airlines officials in
Tokyo regarding alternative methods of delivery.
   Although Japanese officials at the embassies in Washington and
Houston were not available Thursday because of a national holiday,
a representative in the honorary consulate's office in Dallas said
a $2,000 duty fee seemed high.
</TEXT>
