<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brawley     05-06 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharpton: TV Reporter Paid Teen-Agers for Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television reporter has denied charges that he
paid two teen-agers to say Tawana Brawley was at a birthday party
during the time the young black woman claims she was kidnapped and
assaulted by a gang of whites.
   ``We offered no money, and we specifically told them we do not
pay for stories,'' WCBS-TV reporter Mike Taibbi said Thursday in
response to charges by the Rev. Al Sharpton, who has been acting as
spokesman Tawana Brawley's family.
   At a news conference called by Sharpton, a man who said he was
the father of one of the teens said his son never knew Miss Brawley
and had lied when he said he saw her at the party.
   His son and another boy received between $10 and $100 for the TV
interview, said the man, Gregory Fleming Sr.
   Taibbi, appearing on the air later Thursday, said he had given
one of the two unidentified teens $10 for gas. Earlier, Taibbi
acknowledged paying for sodas at a fast-food restaurant, but said
no money ever changed hands.
   Sharpton labeled the Wednesday night report ``a media hoax built
on the whims of young kids and the paranoia of some crack addicts
in Newburgh,'' an upstate city near Miss Brawley's hometown of
Wappingers Falls.
   In a statement Thursday afternoon, WCBS-TV said it stood behind
the report.
   Miss Brawley, 16, was found Nov. 28 inside a trash bag with
racial slurs scrawled on her torso and feces smeared on her body.
She claimed to be the victim of a sexual and racial assault
involving up to a half-dozen white men, including one with a police
badge.
   Sharpton and two attorneys, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox,
have refused to allow Miss Brawley to appear before a state grand
jury investigating the case and have charged prosecutors with a
cover-up.
   During the WCBS-TV broadcast, an unidentified witness who
appeared with his face concealed said he saw Miss Brawley at a
birthday party in Newburgh during the four-day period when she
claimed she was held captive. He also said she spent time with a
former boyfriend during that period.
   Attorney General Robert Abrams, who is the special prosecutor
for the Brawley case, issued a statement saying: ``All aspects of
this case, including reports that Tawana Brawley may have been seen
in Newburgh, are under continuing investigation.''
   In a separate development, Sharpton and other civil rights
activists arrested during a protest against racism last December
walked out of a court appearance Thursday after a judge refused to
move the proceeding into a larger courtroom. Criminal Court Judge
Albert Koch issued bench warrants for 18 defendants.
</TEXT>
