<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-China     05-06 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-China,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Paper Praises Chinese Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party daily Pravda today heaped
praise on Chinese reforms that have attracted foreign investment,
and it called for a rebirth of the work ethic to bring similar
prosperity to the Soviet Union.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev has made favorable references to
recent Chinese economic experiments, but Pravda's article was the
most complimentary report yet on reform in the neighboring
communist state.
   Today's article on China's Tianjin region, one of 14 open
economic zones, set forth a list of accomplishments and credited an
inspired workforce for the success of ``Chinese perestroika.''
   ``Perestroika'' is the name of Gorbachev's reform program that
aims to rebuild the Soviet economy and society. Soviet proponents
of perestroika, which means ``rebuilding,'' have encouraged broader
use of joint ventures to draw foreign investment to Soviet industry.
   But an array of problems faces the foreign businessman in the
Soviet Union. They include low worker productivity, unreliable
delivery of supplies, poor storage and transportation facilities,
and a lack of convenient and comfortable accommodations.
   China's open economic zones contain only 8 percent of the
nation's population but account for more than a quarter of its
industrial production and 40 percent of all exports, Pravda said.
The zones were created four years ago.
   The authoritative newspaper said the special economic zones had
been successful in attracting foreign capital and joint ventures
because the Chinese built support facilities needed for
international trade.
   In the Tianjin region, architecturally unique buildings
``literally pop up like a mirage in the desert,'' Pravda said. It
reported that the region's developers built luxury hotels, a golf
course, sports clubs and other services that make Western
businessmen feel comfortable.
   Transport problems also were worked out ahead of time to ensure
enough shipping capacity to foreign customers, and a lenient tax
system has drawn more foreign investment each year, the newspaper
said.
   Pravda said the Tianjin region alone had 80 contracts for
joint-venture enterprises and that capital investment in the region
last year exceeded $100 million.
</TEXT>
