<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ETVideo     05-06 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ET Video,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`E.T.' Video Gets Big Fall Promotion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``E.T.'' is coming home. Maybe to your home.
   The endearing little alien of ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial''
will be invading the home video market this fall with a hoopla
worthy of the most popular movie of all time.
   MCA Home Video and the Pepsi Cola Co. announced plans for the
mammoth publicity campaign at a news conference Thursday on a
Universal Studios sound stage decorated to look like a wooded scene
from the 1982 movie.
   The videocassette will be released on Oct. 27 at a retail price
of $24.95, said Gene F. Giaquinto, president of MCA Home
Entertainment Group.
   The Pepsi Cola Co. will support the release with the greatest
advertising campaign in its history, said Roger Enrico, president
of Pepsi Cola World Wide Beverages. Pepsi has commissioned a series
of television commercials featuring ``E.T.'' and will offer a $5
rebate on purchase of the video.
   Enrico said Pepsi will also support ``E.T.'' with displays in
more than 60,000 retail stores and will sponsor a sweepstakes
giving away more than 100,000 free copies of the video.
   Giaquinto said the two companies would spend $25 million
promoting the release.
   The movie, produced by Steven Spielberg, tells the story of an
endearing little alien from another world who became marooned on
earth and was befriended by a group of small children. The children
protect him from government agents and help him return to his own
world.
   ``E.T.'' has taken in more than $228 million in film rentals,
with the worldwide box office estimated at nearly $500 million.
   MCA, Pepsi and Spielberg's company will make a contribution from
the proceeds of the video sale to the Special Olympics. The group
supports activities for mentally retarded athletes.
</TEXT>
