<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrayingMantis     05-06 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Praying Mantis,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Carolina House Adopts Praying Mantis As State Insect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Carolina may soon get a new symbol
because some elementary school students bugged the General Assembly.
   The House on Thursday overwhelmingly passed a bill to make the
praying mantis the state insect; the Senate had taken similar
action in March. Gov. Carroll Campbell also supports the proposal,
spokesman Tucker Eskew said.
   Rep. Woody Aydlette, whose lighthearted promotion of the
cockroach was rejected, did succeed in adding an amendment that
would require a three-fourths vote instead of a majority vote in
the General Assembly to adopt state symbols.
   Aydlette said it's a waste of legislators' time and taxpayers'
money to add to the already long list of state symbols.
   The students in the Dacusville-Crosswell Enrichment Program in
Perkins County initiated the legislation as part of a class project
to learn how the legislative process works, Dacusville Elementary
School Assistant Principal Tammy Hamlin said Thursday.
   ``They realized the state didn't have an insect and went to
work,'' she said.
   The students did research to determine the proper insect to
represent the state and voted for the praying mantis.
   The students got their state senator, Nell Smith, to propose the
bill, came to Columbia to testify, wrote letters to legislators and
crafted praying mantis brochures, bumper stickers and buttons.
   ``The lobbying was extensive,'' said state Rep. Larry Martin, a
Dacusville Elementary School alumnus.
   When the bill hit a snag in the House, the children wrote and
called the legislators who opposed it and convinced all of them but
Aydlette to remove their objections, Martin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
