<2ND_LINE>PM-Double Trouble,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teller, Alleged Bank Robber Meet Again In Hold-Up Rerun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of robbing a BayBank
branch here earlier this year escaped from jail and, 90 minutes
later, held up the same bank and the same teller, police say.
   The teller recognized Steven W. Bergeron during the stick-up as
the same man who staged a hold-up at her window on March 25, said
Detective Sgt. Gilbert Larson. The suspect also apparently
recognized the teller.
   ``He said. `I want you to help me again.' She said, `No.' He
said, `I have a gun. Don't make me use it,''' Larson said.
   The teller handed over the money. Police would not disclose how
much was taken but Larson said it wasn't much. Police were
searching for Bergeron.
   Bristol County Sheriff David Nelson said Bergeron, 31, had
scaled a wall at the county jail earlier Wednesday, climbed over a
roof and slid down a drain pipe to escape.
   Bergeron, arrested at gunpoint at a motel March 31, had been
serving several jail terms and was awaiting trial on three bank
heists, including the one at the BayBank in March.
   The day before his escape Bergeron was sentenced to two
concurrent two-year sentences on charges of breaking and entering
in the daytime with intent to commit a felony, and larceny.
