<HEAD>Mom Dismayed When Son Adopts Wandering 5-Foot Lizard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a 5-foot-long Nile monitor lizard
in Gilda Centro's shower, and she isn't happy about it.
   Her son, Patrick, spotted the lizard wandering near a busy
street earlier this week, chased it down and brought it home. Mrs.
Centro, a Broward Sheriff's Office dispacher, believes the reptile
is a runaway and has been searching in vain for missing lizard
reports.
   ``I'd like to find his rightful owner,'' said Mrs. Centro.
   ``I'd keep him as a pet, but my mom's not keen on it,'' said
Patrick, 18. ``He's tame and he likes people. He's really cool.''
   Bill Zeigler, general curator of Miami's Metrozoo, said he would
gladly adopt the large, flesh-eating lizard, which is not native to
the United States.
