<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Dennis     05-06 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dennis,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Attorney Leading Contender for Weld's Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward S.G. Dennis Jr., the U.S. attorney in
Philadelphia, is the leading candidate to take over the Justice
Department's criminal division, a White House spokesman said today.
   ``There are others, but he's the leading candidate,'' said
Deputy Press Secretary B.J. Cooper. ``We're still doing background
checks.''
   Dennis, 43, a career prosecutor, would succeed William F. Weld,
who resigned March 29 in protest against Attorney General Edwin
Meese's continued leadership of the department. Meese has been
under investigation by independent counsel James McKay for more
than a year.
   Dennis was appointed U.S. attorney for the eastern district of
Pennsylvania by President Reagan in 1983 after three years as head
of the narcotics section in the Justice Department criminal
division. Before that he was an assistant U.S. attorney in
Philadelphia.
   If nominated by Reagan to the Justice Department post, Dennis
would be subject to confirmation by the Senate. If confirmed, he
would be the Justice Department's only ranking black official. He
is one of two blacks among the nation's 93 U.S. attorneys.
   Dennis has built a reputation as a vigorous prosecutor of
political corruption.
</TEXT>
