<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DogDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0556 05-06 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dog Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0556,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disabled Veteran Is Disturbed by Police Attack on Dogs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th, `But several ...,' with comments
from mayor at news conference this morning.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKSHEAR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For as long as most residents can
remember, Elliott Trueluck has walked downtown to a coffee shop
each morning, singing and talking to a pack of dog yelping at his
heels.
   Last week, however, a police officer opened fire on Trueluck's
canine followers, killing at least two of them. Now, the disabled
veteran says he's afraid to go out into the streets of this small
southeastern Georgia town.
   ``It scared the I-don't-know-what out of me,'' recalled
Trueluck, 61, who is described by his wife as a ``shell-shock''
victim of World War II. ``I did what that (police officer) told me
to do and got out of there. What if he had turned the gun on me,
instead of the dogs?''
   Harriett Dixon, director of the Okefenokee Humane Society in
nearby Waycross, said police Sgt. James Mock killed several dogs on
April 29 with shotgun blasts and then used a billy club to beat
wounded dogs to death.
   Warrants obtained by the Humane Society and a witness charge
Mock with cruelty to animals for allegedly shooting and clubbing
the dogs. He is free on $500 bond.
   Mayor Harry Adams said Mock shot the dogs on orders from City
Hall after Trueluck had laughed off warnings to keep the animals
off city streets. An ordinance requires that dogs be leashed when
out of their owners' yards.
   But several people who work at a neaby shopping center said
unleashed dogs belonging to prominent white citizens roam the
center, ignored by police, while their owners are inside. Trueluck
is black.
   ``The actions taken by the policeman in this case are considered
just and proper,'' the mayor said at a news conference today. ``He
was performing his duty in accordance with prescribed procedures.''
   Adams said the dogs killed by Mock were considered mean, vicious
and a threat to the community. He said the city has decided to buy
a tranquilizer gun as a result of the incident.
   Witnesses disputed the mayor's contention that the dogs were
dangerous.
   ``I've walked right by them on the sidewalk and all they did was
wag their tails,'' said Judy Thompson, who witnessed the shooting.
``It's bad to think you live in a town where the cops just pull up
and go to shooting.''
   ``We watched him every day,'' said another witness, Rebecca
Jacobson. ``He had different dogs with him every day. He'd walk and
they would follow him. If one of them strayed, he'd sing.''
   The attack occurred as Trueluck was returning home with at least
eight dogs from his favorite coffee shop in this timber and farming
community about 100 miles southwest of Savannah. Ms. Jacobson said
she was working in a drug store at the shopping center when she
heard the shots.
   ``I ran out. ... He was out there beating them with a stick.
There was one injured dog that was trying to get away. He'd run a
little and sit down. We could tell he'd been shot in the back.''
   City officials said Mock killed two dogs. But Mrs. Dixon
contends that as many as six others may have been hauled off by
city sanitation workers before she arrived at the scene.
   Police Chief Dennis Martin said he has asked the Georgia Bureau
of Investigation to conduct an independent probe to determine if
any of the state's anti-cruelty statutes had been violated.
   ``My officers haven't done anything wrong,'' the chief added.
   Trueluck's wife, Myrtice, said he receives a small disability
check every month because he has never recovered from being ``shell
shocked'' while serving as a Marine in the Pacific during World War
II. A symptom of his condition is that he laughs at almost
everything.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
