<DOCNO> AP880506-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 3rdLd-Writethru a0551 05-06 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0551,0875</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Standoff At Gdansk Shipyard, Government Proposes Punishment For
Strikers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UDPATE with draft legislation on
punishing strikers, edits to trim. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of police carrying clubs ringed
the strikebound Lenin shipyard today, and workers inside said they
expected an assault. Workers at a huge southern steel mill said a
raid by riot troops had not ended their strike.
   The Roman Catholic Church criticized the police raid at Nowa
Huta steel plant outside Krakow and said authorities apparently was
planning similar action against the shipyard workers.
   The the government moved in draft legislation to punish
organizers of strikes and any forms of protest with up to one
year's imprisonment. The draft also suspends the already limited
right to strike by officially recognized trade unions.
   The Nowa Huta strike began April 26 after a successful one-day
stoppage by transit workers in the northwestern city of Bydgoszcz
touched off Poland's worst wave of labor unrest since the 1981
military crackdown on the independent Solidarity union federation.
   The state-run radio said today work had resumed, but workers
said the strike was still on.
   The church statement, issued in Warsaw, came as three
church-appointed mediators told reporters they felt betrayed by the
police attack Thursday because an agreement had been within reach
to end the 10-day strike.
   State-run media reports said the Gdansk shipyard's director
warned strikers in a message broadcast over loudspeakers during the
night to leave or he would resort to ``other means.''
   A Pole who spent the night in the yard said about 2,000 strikers
were inside and ``it's very tense. You can see they are all under
great stress.''
   The workers began to worry about their low food supplies, with
supporters outside no longer allowed to bring gifts of bread.
   ``It seems they are going to use a different scenario than in
Nowa Huta,'' said senior Polish dissident Adam Michnik. ``They
probably want to take the shipyard by hunger.''
   During the night, police convoys periodically moved about this
Baltic port in a show of force. Inside the shipyard, Solidarity
lead Lech Walesa circulated among young strikers and vowed to be
``the last to leave'' the yard, where Solidarity was born.
   A note from strikers smuggled out of the shipyard Thursday
evening said: ``As far as we know, they (the authorities) are
preparing for a police raid.'' The strike at the 12,000-worker
shipyard began Monday.
   The government proposal to punish strikers was contained in a
previously announced bill to give the state special powers to speed
up its economic reform program. The draft was obtained by Western
news agencies in Warsaw.
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski said in March that the
government might require special powers to speed up its plans to
reform the ailing economy.
   Solidarity says it generally favors the direction of the reforms.
   But a statement by Walesa received today from inside the
shipyard said that, ``Society must be the co-author and partner in
the solutions.''
   Wage demands fueled by rapid inflation this year have threatened
to ``derail'' the economic reform program, the government said this
week, announcing that it would ask for the special powers.
   In the draft, which has yet to be presented to parliament, the
government would be empowered to change management structures,
order layoffs of workers, order liquidations, break-ups or mergers
of companies and fire managers.
   It also would allow for a freeze of wages and prices.
   Opposition activists said at least 32 strikers, including a man
whose legs were broken, had to be treated for beatings suffered
when security forces stormed the steelworks Thursday.
   The government denied anyone was injured in the pre-dawn raid.
   The Rev. Tadeusz Zaleski, who was with the strikers during the
raid, said riot police were beating people with ``very long heavy
sticks.'' He said they destroyed the altar where he said Mass for
workers.
   In its statement, the church said: ``We express deep sorrow that
an attempt of dialogue and social conciliation did not bring the
expected results.'
   On Wednesday, the church had sent mediators to both trouble
spots with the approval of authorities, the statement said.
   ``We feel shocked that in the course of the talks, which in
parts were very encouraging, the talks were brutally stopped,''
said one of the mediators, Andrzej Stelmachowski.
   A combine official said on state-run radio today that the plant
was quiet and ``strenuous work'' was going on. The radio also said
plant workers would this month receive 25 percent raises, half of
what the strikers had demanded.
   The Bydgoszcz strike and a two-day stoppage at another steel
mill ended with promises of pay raises to offset 42 percent price
increases.
   In addition to higher pay, the Nowa Huta and Gdansk strikers
demand reinstatement of free trade unions and fired Solidarity
activists and the release of political prisoners.
   Solidarity was born after a wave of strikes in August 1980 and
was banned two years later.
   Three times in postwar Poland, labor unrest that followed price
increases has toppled governments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
