<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0537,0861</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Give Deportation Order To Arab-American Resistance Leader</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with report of arrest of Jewish settler, SUB 2nd
graf, `A Jewish...' with two grafs and INSERT graf after 21st pvs,
`Rizik Abu...' Pick up 22nd pvs, `On Thursday...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested an Arab-American leader of the
Palestinian civil disobedience movement and ordered him deported,
Israeli officials said today. A government spokesman accused him of
advocating violence.
   Police arrested a Jewish settler in the shooting death of a
Palestinian shepherd. Another shepherd was wounded in the eye in
the incident.
   Israel radio reported that troops shot and wounded a 15-year-old
Arab boy in anti-occupation unrest today in the Gaza Strip town of
Khan Yunis.
   Sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said U.S. Ambassador
Thomas Pickering would protest the ordered deportation of Mubarak
Awad, who was arrested at his Jerusalem home at midnight (6 p.m.
EDT Thursday). U.S. Embassy officials said they had no information
on such a protest.
   In 1985 Awad established the Center for Non-Violent Studies in
Jerusalem, which calls on Palestinians to peacefully resist the
Israeli occupation of Arab lands captured during the 1967 Middle
East war.
   Leaders of the 5-month-old Palestinian uprising have adopted
many elements of Awad's non-violence strategy. Awad also provided
tours and information to foreign journalists covering the unrest.
   Avi Pazner, spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said
Awad was ordered deported because he had gone beyond his calls for
non-violent protest and was responsible for leaflets that urged
Palestinians to throw gasoline bombs and stones.
   ``This is preaching violence,'' Pazner said, adding that Awad
had also called for a Palestinian state that would include all of
Israel.
   Awad said today he supported the establishment of a Palestinian
state alongside Israel, his lawyer, Jonathan Kuttab, told The
Associated Press.
   Kuttab met Awad today in jail and was preparing an appeal
against his deportation.
   Awad said the deportation order came because the Palestinians
were showing restraint and using civil disobedience, Kuttab said.
   The move to expel Awad followed a crackdown on leaders of the
uprising, 20 of whom have been deported to Lebanon.
   Israel has also jailed 21 Arab journalists, including one
Thursday, in an effort to stifle news coverage of the proests.
   Benjamin Yaari, deputy legal adviser of the Interior Ministry,
said Awad was given the deportation order Thursday and that he has
three days to appeal to Israel's supreme court.
   Awad, 44, who also has a home in Wapakoneta, Ohio, was in Israel
under a tourist visa that expired last November, and he refused an
order to leave the country. Awad was allowed to remain following
strong U.S. pressure against the previous expulsion order.
   Authorities on Thursday arrested Elias M. Zananiri, managing
editor of the Arab weekly Al Awdah and of the Palestine Press
Service. The authorities have closed the Arab-run press service and
Al Awdah, which also has an English edition.
   Police spokesman Rafi Levy said Zananiri would be held for at
least 48 hours for investigation on charges of incitement to riot.
   The Palestinian death toll in the uprising that began Dec. 8
rose to 184 Thursday after a confrontation near the West Bank
village of Turmus Aiya, 17 miles northeast of Jerusalem.
   Israel radio said the clash started when a Jewish woman spotted
several Palestinian shepherds in a field. The woman panicked and
called for help, and armed settlers as well as Arab villagers
rushed to the scene.
   It said the Arabs began to throw stones and a settler ``opened
fire, apparently at the stonethrowers, killing one and wounding
another.''
   An Arab reporter from east Jerusalem's Al Quds newspaper said
Jude Abdallah Awad, 28, was shot in the head and killed when the
settlers tried to drive away Palestinians working in their fields.
   Rizik Abu Naim, 29, was wounded in the right eye when he tried
to rescue Awad, said the reporter, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Police today arrested a settler in connection with the shooting,
said Israel Medad, spokesman for the nearby Shilo settlement.
Israel radio identified the suspect as Yisrael Zeev, a U.S.
immigrant. Police had no immediate comment.
   On Thursday, the army ordered that shops in the occupied lands
close for three days or be welded shut. The order promises to be a
major test of wills Saturday, when underground leaders of the
uprising said shops should remain open.
   Near the West Bank village of Beita, about 1,000 settlers, some
carrying rifles, marched and waved Israeli flags Thursday where
Jewish settler Tirza Porat, 15, and two Palestinians were killed in
a clash April 6.
   They retraced the route followed by Miss Porat and teen-age
hikers until the clash. An army investigation concluded that she
was accidentally shot by an armed escort of the hikers. Jewish
settlers have alleged the Arabs caused her death by stoning the
teen-agers.
   Several Jews from ``Stop the Occupation'' movement demonstrated
in Beita to support the creation of an independent Palestinian
state.
</TEXT>
