<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolMom     05-06 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Mom,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mom Goes To School To Keep Son Off Suspension</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOONSBORO, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Her son thought it was a terrible idea,
but Debbie Crampton says she's glad she went to high school with
him so he could avoid a three-day suspension.
   ``I would suggest it to any parent who is trying to understand a
problem at school or worried about why their kid's grade dropped,''
said Ms. Crampton, whose son, Allen, was suspended for acting up in
class.
   When Boonsboro High School officials decided to suspend the
sophomore, Ms. Crampton decided it was more important to keep him
in school. She proposed to join him, and the school took her offer
up.
   ``They get zeros for all the work they miss and that brings
their grade down and he couldn't afford to have his grades go
down,'' Ms. Crampton said Thursday after her third and final day of
classes.
   Her son was less than enthusiastic.
   ``It's terrible,'' he said. He didn't elaborate.
   Ms. Crampton, a 1972 graduate of Boonsboro High, said her first
day back in school was a little stressful. She's a smoker, but
could not light up.
   ``In fact, I got caught chewing gum in English class. I had to
spit it out,'' she said.
   She also got homework in math and science.
   ``I think he'll be more careful now and listen a bit now,'' Ms.
Crampton said. ``I didn't think he minded at first, but when we
were coming home, he asked me if it was my last day. He was glad to
have it over with.''
   Boonsboro Principal Joseph Robeson said letting parents attend
was a good idea.
   ``I think first of all it gives the youngster the clear
impression (that) they (the parents) would go above and beyond what
they normally do to improve a situation,'' Robeson said.
</TEXT>
