<2ND_LINE>PM-Najib-India, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0571,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib Renews Vow to Continue Fighting Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after graf 10 `Soviet troops...and Pakistan'
to UPDATE with Tass reporting returning refugees, PICKS UP graf 11
pvs `He was...'
^Eds: One name for Najib is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib of Afghanistan said
today he stood ready to bring Moslem rebels into his government but
that his army would fight them if necessary.
   The Soviet Union, which has been backing his socialist
government, is scheduled to withdraw its estimated 115,000 troops
from Afghanistan starting May 15. Some diplomats have said the
departure of Soviet soldiers will leave Najib's forces unable to
repel the U.S.-supplied guerrillas, who already control much of the
country.
   But Najib said today after a three-day visit to India that his
army would deal ``a heavy and severe blow'' to the Pakistan-based
guerrillas if they continue to fight.
   The rebels have refused to participate in any government headed
by Najib.
   Asked today at his news conference if he would step aside as
president to facilitate what he calls ``national reconciliation,''
Najib replied: ``I would like to tell you that the Afghan Loya
Jirga (national assembly) was convened last November and endorsed
the new constitution of the republic and elected the president for
a seven-year term.'' Najib's mandate would end November 1994.
   Najib said the Mujahedeen ``are actually doing a political
suicide'' by refusing to talk with his government.
   Meanwhile, a Mujahedeen statement issued today in New Delhi
attacked what it called ``India's misconceived policy of taking
(the) side of (the) criminal regime of Kabul.''
   The Afghan president met Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and several
top government officials during his stay in New Delhi. Both the
Afghans and Indians have talked of warm relations between the two
countries, who share a common enemy in Pakistan.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to prop up
the socialist government against attacks by Islamic guerrillas. The
Soviet withdrawal is scheduled to begin under an agreement signed
last month by the Soviet Union, the United States, Afghanistan and
Pakistan.
   The Soviet news agency Tass said today that more than 10,000
refugees were returning to Afghanistan each day. It gave no details
and did not say when the number rose to that level.
   A week earlier, officials in the Afghan capital of Kabul said
130,000 refugees had returned since January 1986.
   At least 3 million Afghans have fled their country during the
decade-long civil war. They are mostly housed in refugee camps in
Pakistan and Iran, and the Kabul leadership is attempting to draw
them back to Afghanistan as Soviet troops begin to withdraw.
   Najib said today the deposed Afghan king, Zahir Shah, was also
free to return home to participate in politics.
   He was overthrown in 1973 by a cousin, who was assassinated in
1978. Afghan refugees and some Western officials have suggested
that the deposed king's return might pave the way for a transition
of government.
   An Indian official, speaking after Najib's news conference, said
India had played an informal role in talking with the ousted king,
as well as the United States, the Soviet Union and Pakistan.
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, he added, ``The impression
we gathered from the Afghans (is that) they are trying to broaden
the base of their government.''
   Najib also said he had rejected a petition by foreign reporters
to free an Italian journalist and a French photographer jailed on
espionage charges. He said the two men, who were captured after
entering Afghanistan with the Mujahedeen, had engaged in
``subversive activities.''
</TEXT>
