<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DisasterRdp     05-06 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Disaster Rdp,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises in Nation's Industrial Disasters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from this week's industrial disasters rose to six
today with the discovery of two more bodies at the still-burning
Shell Oil Co. refinery at Norco, La., as investigators began
looking into a Los Angeles skyscraper fire and explosions at a
Nevada rocket fuel plant.
   The string of accidents began Wednesday afternoon when
earthquake-force explosions destroyed the Pacific Engineering
Production Co. building and 11 others at a Henderson, Nev.,
industrial park, killing two people and injuring more than 255
people.
   That night, fire broke out at the 62-story First Interstate Bank
tower, California's tallest building, incinerating four floors and
causing $450 million damage. One worker was killed when he became
trapped in an elevator and 40 other people were injured.
   A few hours later, explosions that broke windows 20 miles away
in New Orleans set off fires at the Shell refinery. Three people
were found dead, and four more were still missing this morning,
said Wendy Jacobs, a Shell spokeswoman. Four-two people were
injured as windows shattered and doors and roofs were torn off
throughout Norco.
   Small, stubborn fires continued to burn today at the refinery
complex, fueled by residual gasoline and oil in tangled lines and
equipment, but the towering blaze that sent black smoke over the
area was out. A specially trained crew of 25 plant workers poked
through the wreckage today, looking for the missing men, said Sarah
Colletti, a plant spokeswoman.
   The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration and
the Environmental Protection Agency sent investigators to the
refinery today to assist Shell in determining the cause of the
accident.
   Investigators hadn't determined the cause of the skyscraper
inferno yet either, and Los Angeles fire officials said they were
calling on the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to
help because of the severity and scale of the blaze.
   The request doesn't necessarily mean arson is suspected, but
rather that there is a need for the ATF's technical expertise, said
Fire Department spokesman Greg Acevedo.
   Fire officials cited a ``flashover effect,'' a phenomenon in
which materials become superheated, causing a firestorm, in
explaining the blaze's rapid spread.
   In Nevada, union and plant officials debated about safety at the
Pacific Engineering building, where ammonium perchlorate, a key
fuel component for the space shuttle and U.S. military rockets was
produced.
   Union officials said they had complained about safety at the
plant, but company officials denied there was a problem.
   ``This plant is, in my opinion, one of the worst I have ever
been into,'' John Molovich, safety and heath technician with the
international Steelworkers Union, said in a letter following a
September 1982 tour of the plant. The letter was released Thursday.
   ``I cannot understand how this plant has not been blown off the
face of the earth, given the product it manufactures,'' Molovich
wrote.
   But Fred Gibson, the company chairman, responded: ``It is a safe
plant and I am stating there have been no fires there. We had
inspections from OSHA and we had no continuing problems with
anything.''
   Laury Lewis, general manager of the State Industrial Insurance
System, said his records indicate Pacific Engineering ``has always
been a pretty good risk.'' His records, he said, indicated no
previous multiple injury problems or explosions.
   Pacific Engineering was one of two plants in the United States
that made ammonium perchlorate. The other is Kerr-McGee, whose
plant is just a mile away from the site of Wednesday's destruction.
Ammonium perchlorate production there was halted until the cause of
the accident was determined, and officials at rocket manufacturer
Morton Thiokol Inc. said there could be an effect on the nation's
space program.
</TEXT>
