<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Suit, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0585,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Sues Unions, Charges They Tried To Destroy Airline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS five grafs at end, other background; Version moved on
financial circuits</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines today sued its pilots and
machinists unions for $1.5 billion, accusing them of trying to
destroy the financially embattled carrier so they can buy it at a
``bargain basement price.''
   The lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in Miami by Eastern and
its parent, Texas Air Corp., accuses the Air Line Pilots
Association and the International Association of Machinists with
racketeering, extortion, fraud and defamation.
   The suit marked a new salvo in the airline's rancorous relations
with its unions. Since it was bought by Texas Air, management has
pressed the machinists to accept deep wage cuts it deems necessary
to return Eastern to profitability.
   The suit's accusations against the unions include charges they
conducted a public ``smearing'' of the carrier's reputation, staged
illegal work slowdowns and tried to undermine worker loyalty,
Eastern said in a press statement.
   ``We can't provide any (further) comment on it,'' said Eastern
spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
   Charles Bryant, president of the machinists local, was returning
to Miami from a convention in Atlanta and could not be reached for
comment. ALPA spokesmen in Washington also could not immediately be
reached.
   The Eastern-Texas Air complaint alleges the unions were
``attempting to obtain ownership and control of Eastern through an
extortionate scheme to smear the company's reputation.''
   If the unions failed in their attempt to drive down Eastern's
price, they were willing to ruin the company ``to maintain the
excessive wages and bring back the high fares prevalent until
deregulation changed the industry 10 years ago,'' Eastern contended
in a news release.
   Named in the complaint were ALPA and its Eastern Master
Executive Council, the IAM and its District 100, and respective
local union leaders, including Bryant and John J. Bavis Jr. of ALPA.
   Eastern, whose losses of some $900 million in the past 10 years
include a $181.6 million loss last year, was bought by Texas Air in
1986 for $676 million. The Miami-based carrier's unions had tried
to halt the sale, making their own offer for Eastern.
   The Federal Aviation Administration last month announced it was
seeking $823,000 in penalties from Eastern for past safety
violations and then began a plane-by-plane inspection of the
carrier.
   Last year, Eastern paid $9.5 million in FAA fines levied for
safety violations.
   On Thursday, the House Public Works and Transportation Committee
approved a non-binding resolution on Thursday urging the U.S.
Transportation Department, parent of the FAA, to widen the probe of
Eastern and Texas Air.
   The resolution urges the department to look more closely at how
Texas Air and Eastern practices might affect the public and company
employees.
   It also seeks to have the department use its findings in
deciding whether to allow Texas Air to make operating changes, such
as selling its Boston-New York-Washington air-shuttle service.
   A federal judge has blocked Eastern from selling the profitable
shuttle service; Eastern is appealing the order.
   The Transportation Department announced last month that it had
begun investigating the management, financial status and safety
practices of Texas Air, Eastern and another Texas Air subsidiary,
Continental Airlines.
</TEXT>
