<1ST_LINE>u a PM-RefineryBlast 2ndLd-Writethru a0527 05-06 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Refinery Blast, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0527,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Helpless To Search For Six Missing As Refinery
Smolders</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with fires continuing to burn
this morning, more details on search, EPA, OSHA investigators being
sent to assist, picking up 5th graf pvs, ``It went ....'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORCO, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emergency crews searching the smoldering
wreckage of a refinery discovered two bodies today, raising the
death toll to three and leaving four men missing in the blast that
shattered plate glass windows 30 miles away.
   Wendy Jacobs, a Shell spokeswoman, said the two were among six
employees who had been missing since the explosion.
   Police today patrolled virtually windowless Norco to protect the
town's bank, furniture store and other businesses. The local co-op
lost most of a wall facing the plant when the devastating explosion
cut loose.
   At least three Shell Oil Co. employees died and 42 other people
were injured in the blast in a catalytic cracker Thursday morning.
   This morning small, stubborn fires continued to burn, fueled by
residual gasoline and oil in tangled lines and equipment, but the
towering blaze that sent up clouds of black smoke had died out.
   Twenty-five members of the plant emergency crew went into the
maze of hot, twisted metal searching for the missing, said plant
spokeswoman Sarah Colletti. Tight security prevented anyone else
from entering the plant.
   The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration and
the Environmental Protection Agency sent investigators to the
refinery today to assist Shell in trying to determine what caused
the explosion.
   ``It went `Boom!' and then `Boom!' again,'' said Adam Mashia,
65, who lives less than a mile from the plant. ``It knocked me to
the floor and as I was getting up, it knocked me down again.''
   The force of the explosion broke windows in New Orleans's Garden
District, 30 miles down the Mississippi River.
   People in Slidell, 45 miles distant, said they also felt the
blast. The fire that broke out in the refinery forced the
evacuation of about 2,500 residents until it was brought under
control about 5{ hours later.
   Gasoline futures prices went up because of the damage to the
plant, which will create a squeeze on gasoline supplies in the Gulf
Coast, according to Greg Dreis, an analyst at Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures.
   Authorities waited for the plant's remains to cool down today
before searching for the missing men, also Shell employees.
   Fred Foster, manager of Shell's Norco complex, said Shell has
established a claims center for victims.
   He also said a team of company investigators, joined by state
and federal authorities would begin looking for the cause of the
blast once the plant cooled down.
   Alan Migliore, who lives about three blocks from the refinery
complex, said: ``I was sleeping in the kitchen and it knocked me to
the floor. From there, I looked up and could see that the whole
area to the Shell was on fire. ... It blew both of the front doors
in, and the deadbolts took the frames out.''
   Damage at the refinery complex alone was expected to run into
the millions of dollars, said Shell spokesman Phil Schwin. The
accident ruptured the catalytic cracker, which converts crude oil
to gasoline, and seriously damaged control rooms and other
facilities.
   Residents of this town on the heavily industrialized, 75-mile
petrochemical corridor said they are fed up over recurring
emergencies that have forced them to evacuate their homes eight
times in 12 years.
   ``People were literally frightened out of their minds,'' said
New Orleans attorney J.T. Hill, who filed a $25 billion lawsuit
within hours of the explosion.
   ``I didn't know what happened,'' said another resident, Paul
Dauzat, 55. ``I went to look out the window and my wife said, `Why
are you looking out the window? The door is off.'''
   Damage was sustained on both sides of the mile-wide Mississippi
River, and Shell Oil said people needing repair materials could
charge them to the company's account at lumber yards on the river's
east and west banks.
   In Baton Rouge, Gov. Buddy Roemer said he didn't plan to ask for
federal disaster assistance because of Shell's willingness to
accept responsibility for damages.
   Just inside the gates of the Shell complex was a sign with the
familiar Shell logo, saying ``Complex Safe Days 616.'' As the fire
continued, workers took the sign down.
</TEXT>
