<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StreetPreachers     05-06 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Street Preachers,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Street Preaching Children Suspended For Third Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school principal suspended a
5-year-old student and his 6-year-old sister for the third time in
the last three weeks for ``preaching'' outside the school.
   Principal Jim Gorst listened to Matthew Strode for 15 minutes
Thursday morning before suspending the boy for 10 days. He also
suspended Matthew's sister, Pepper, for refusing to enter the
school building.
   The Eastfield Elementary School principal had already given
their 10-year-old brother, Duffey, his third suspension last week.
   The incident Thursday was the latest round of a monthlong fight
between school officials and David and Robin Strode, the children's
parents. The Strodes say school officials are violating the
children's First Amendment rights to freedom of speech and religion.
   The three Strode children have insisted on preaching outside the
school, while school officials say they must enter the building and
go to class if they're on the grounds.
   David Strode, a machinist, has been a street preacher since 1981.
   ``It's not the preaching, the issue is the disruptive noise, the
screaming,'' Gorst said. ``It's stressful to our teachers and it's
stressful to our students.''
   From 7:30 to 7:45 a.m., Pepper stood quietly with Matthew behind
the school's rear entrance as he and Duffey alternately shouted
Bible verses. Duffey stood in the road outside the school gate, 100
yards away.
   ``You're in violation of school rules by being out here,'' Gorst
told Matthew and Pepper. After two more warnings, Gorst approached
Robin Strode's car, parked near the gate. Matthew and Pepper
followed.
   ``Come in the office, please, with your children. I think you
realize your children are in violation of school rules,'' Gorst
said.
   As Robin Strode left the school with Matthew and Pepper, after
meeting with Gorst, she said: ``I hope the Lord takes every last
one of them and does something to them. They ain't nothing but a
bunch of hypocrites.''
   The children are honor roll students and their mother has been
picking up their homework during their suspensions. If they're
suspended again, Matthew, Pepper and Duffey may not be promoted to
the next grade, however.
</TEXT>
