<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Pledges To Keep Farm Subsidies In Place</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Bush today; pick up 3rd graf pvs bgng
``The vice...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TWIN FALLS, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said today
that efforts to hurt him politically with the Iran-Contra affair
were ``tested and tried in the primary'' and failed.
   ``I'm not worried at all,'' Bush said. ``I'm not vulnerable.''
   Bush has been dogged by questions about his role in the
arms-for-hostages affair throughout his candidacy. Although
Republican primary voters apparently cared little about the issue,
his Democratic opponents have indicated they will try to make
Iran-Contra an issue in the fall campaign.
   ``I'm not worried. It's been tested and tried in the primary,''
Bush said.
   Bush also shook off the published comments of two top aides
quoted as saying embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese III was a
liability to Bush's Republican presidential campaign.
   ``I haven't authorized anything. Now I have to get on the phone
and find out what they said,'' Bush said.
   On Thursday, Bush called for retaining federal supports on sugar
and other crops even though he favors eventual elimination of farm
subsidies.
   The vice president is ending a three-day swing through the West
with campaign stops today here and in Montana. He was to visit a
local family farm and inspect an irrigation system before flying to
Billings, Mont., for a rally.
   Agriculture issues have been a main focus of his Idaho visit.
   ``Under a Bush administration, the (sugar) program would
continue even though I would try very hard to expand markets abroad
by breaking down barriers to American products,'' Bush said.
   Asked by reporters on Thursday in Boise if he advocates a
lifting of sugar import quotas, important in this region where
sugar beets are a major crop, Bush said he would not _ despite
Reagan advocacy of a global easing of farm subsidies.
   ``I know every administration gives lip service to eliminating
the sugar program and other programs, but it's not going to happen
unilaterally, believe me,'' he said.
   At last year's seven-nation economic summit in Venice, President
Reagan called upon U.S. trading partners to end all agricultural
trade subsidies, including quotas, by the year 2000.
   Reducing such trade barriers is currently on the agenda in a new
round of global trade talks under way in Geneva.
   Bush, who has the Republican presidential nomination in the bag
but is continuing to campaign anyway with an eye on the fall
election, said, ``I'd have a pro-Western policy.''
   ``There's room for a lot of economic growth and energy growth in
the West,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Bush said Reagan is withholding his formal
endorsement of his candidacy so it can be done with a degree of
fanfare.
   ``We're waiting for a dramatic moment to capture the applause of
the waiting political crowds,'' Bush said in an interview with the
local CBS affiliate in Boise.
   ``There's no question where Ronald Reagan's sentiments lie. He
told me this as recently as two days ago. We're waiting to do it so
it has a little flair to it.''
   To date, the White House has been mum on when the endorsement
will come, although presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater has
indicated it will be soon.
   ``There's a lot of thinking going on on it, what would be best.
But the issue is not in doubt,'' Bush said. ``I don't think there's
a person in the United States, Democrat or Republican, who wonders
who President Reagan is going to support for president.''
   On another subject, Bush said that he would not pay money for
the release of hostages under any circumstances.
   Responding to a question centering on news reports of possible
French payments to seek the release of recently released French
hostages, Bush said:
   ``No, because I just think that will make others be taken
hostage.''
   On the sale of U.S. arms to seek the release of U.S. hostages
held in Lebanon, Bush conceded, ``to the degree that it turned out
to be arms for hostages, it was diametrically opposed to U.S.
policy. Our policy is not to do that.''
   ``Mistakes were made, yes, mistakes were made. But the genesis,
the creation of that was not arms for hostages.''
   Bush said he expected Democrats to use the Iran-Contra affair
against him as an issue ``because they're devoid of other national
issues.''
   The vice president was asked by local reporters if Sen. James
McClure, R-Idaho, a longtime friend, was under consideration as a
possible running made.
   Bush, who has been bombarded with similar questions about other
regional favorites wherever he goes, praised McClure highly but
once again stressed he has not yet begun the selection process _
preferring to wait until after the Democrats pick their full team
at their convention in July.
</TEXT>
