<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LoudParty     05-06 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Loud Party,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Escalates Into Near Riot Near Iowa State University Campus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spring party near Iowa State University
escalated into huge melee early today as party-goers threw beer
bottles at cars and used furniture to build a bonfire in the
street, and two people were arrested, police said.
   ``I was out there, and it was very, very close to being a tragic
situation. It was ugly,'' said Police Chief Dennis Ballantine.
   Police arrested Scott Thompson of Ames and Andrew Schoenewe of
Sioux City, both 21, on charges of simple assault after the
two-hour melee, and Ballantine said more arrests were expected.
   Police officer Dick Webb said authorities weren't immediately
sure if Thompson and Schoenewe are students at the 26,000-student
public university.
   One police officer was assaulted but didn't require treatment,
Ballantine said.
   Ballantine said neighbors complained about the private party
about a half-block north of a residence hall, and a police officer
issued a noise citation shortly before 2 a.m.
   More people joined the party until it swelled to about 1,000
people _ mostly students _ who started a bonfire in the middle of
the street, using furniture as fuel, the chief said.
   There were reports of vandalism, mostly to garden fences and
flower gardens, as well as incidents of people throwing beer
bottles at parked and moving vehicles, Ballantine said.
   Most of the crowd left when they saw officers arriving,
Ballantine said, and 200 to 300 people were left when about 30
police officers, Story County sheriff's deputies and campus
security officers moved in shortly after 3 a.m.
   He said the authorities finally cleared the area at about 3:40
a.m. City crews and campus workers spent were cleaning up the area
today.
   ``The party host lost control of his party,'' said Ballantine.
</TEXT>
