<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF-AppleSale     05-06 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-Apple Sale,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students, Teachers Sell Apples To Support School; Lose Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students and teachers in southern China's Hunan
province stopped classes and sold apples on the street to help
support their school but ended up losing $568 in the project, a
newspaper said Friday.
   The Guangming Daily said local education officials in Pingjiang
ordered the Chengguan Middle School to earn $3,378, or about $6.75
per student, as part of a work-study program encouraged by Beijing.
   The government, strapped for education funding, has urged
schools to bolster revenues by doing outside work.
   The school sent two teachers to neighboring Henan province to
buy 10,340 pounds of apples. Classes were suspended for two days
and the school ordered its 36 teachers to set up stalls on the
street and sell 55 pounds of apples each, the report said. The 452
students were required to sell 11 pounds each, the report said.
