<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO-Syria     05-06 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Syria,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Hints At Plans To Turn Up Heat In Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO's executive committee gave strong
indications that it will seek to intensify the uprising in the
Israeli-occupied territories following Israel's raid on Arab
guerrillas in Lebanon.
   The 15-member committee ended six days of closed-door talks
Thursday night, its first session since Palestine Liberation
Organization Chairman Yasser Arafat met Syrian President Hafez
Assad in Damascus on April 25.
   The Arafat-Hassad meeting ended a 5-year-old feud.
   The committee, which rarely announces in detail what decisions
it reaches, vowed in a communique issued late Thursday to
``redouble revolutionary effort by all ways and means and in all
fields.''
   It did not elaborate, but it was widely interpreted as meaning
an intensification of the 5-month-old uprising in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip against 20 years of Israeli occupation.
   It was also seen as an indication that the PLO plans to step up
guerrilla attacks on Israel.
   An Israeli force pushed into south Lebanon on Monday in a
two-day raid against Palestinian guerrillas and their Moslem allies
who have carried out several raids into Israel in recent weeks.
   The Israelis reported killing 40 pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
militiamen during the sweep. Three Israeli soldiers also died.
   The communique said the PLO leadership has ``taken all necessary
measures to maintain the uprising in the occupied territories and
to enhance the steadfastness of our people under occupation.''
   Arafat's reconciliation with Assad in the wake of the April 16
assassination of PLO military commander Khalil Wazir _ believed to
be the PLO's main strategist in the Israeli uprising _ could be a
plus for the PLO.
   The reconciliation would strengthen the PLO's guerrilla campaign
against the Israelis. The Syrians control north and east Lebanon,
where they have about 25,000 troops, and could provide valuable
logistical assistance for cross-border raids.
