<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0430 05-06 0987</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Disowns Aides' Quotes on Meese</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush on aides' Meese comments in top 8 grafs,
picking up in 4th graf pvs, Jackson was; cuts last 4 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush sought to distance himself today from
aides' comments that his campaign is being hampered by Attorney
General Edwin Meese III's legal problems and refusal to resign.
   Jesse Jackson, meanwhile, kept up a heavy pre-primary schedule
in California, but Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis began a
long weeekend away from the campaign trail.
   Bush, in the face of Democrats' demands that Meese resign or be
fired, has consistently said he does not want to prejudge the
independent counsel's investigation of the attorney general.
   However, in a story in today's Detroit News, Peter Teeley,
Bush's communications director, and Robert Teeter, a senior
campaign adviser, were quoted as saying Meese's situation is a
problem for Bush. ``Meese is a liability,'' Teeley said.
   Bush, asked about it while campaigning on a farm near Twin
Falls, Idaho, said he was unaware of the aides' comments, hadn't
authorized them and would ``get on the phone and find out what they
said.''
   One day earlier, Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis, in a slap at Bush, his likely November opponent, said he
wouldn't accept a vice president too timid to speak out on tough
issues.
   Bush, on Thursday, was asked about the release of three French
hostages and said he would never agree to payments to secure the
release of Americans in captivity.
   Jackson, Dukakis' Democratic rival, was chafing at what he
called the premature ``coronation'' of Dukakis. Jackson stepped up
his criticism of party delegate-selection rules on Thursday, but
Dukakis virtually ignored him, training his fire instead on Bush.
   Jackson was campaigning today in California, whose primary on
June 7 will be the biggest _ and last _ of the season. Dukakis was
home in Boston, with no campaign events scheduled for the next few
days.
   Bush was hustling through a series of stops today in Idaho,
Montana and Nebraska. All three states have primaries in the next
month, but as Bush already has a numerical lock on the Republican
nomination, aides say he is aiming to build Western backing for the
general election.
   The vice president's comments about hostages came amid reports
that France had arranged Thursday's release of three French
hostages by agreeing to pay the outstanding balance on a loan
originally totaling $1 billion made by the late Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi of Iran. France has denied paying a ransom for the trio's
release.
   Bush said he would never agree to such an arrangement ``because
I just think that will make others be taken hostage.''
   The vice president's role in the Reagan administration's
arms-for-hostages deal with Iran has been questioned by Republican
and Democratic opponents alike. ``To the degree that it turned out
to be arms for hostages, it was diametrically opposed to U.S.
policy,'' Bush said Thursday of the deal.
   He conceded that the Democrats are making the Republican
arms-for-hostages plan a campaign issue, but claimed they are
``devoid of other national issues.''
   Bush's campaign was engaged in damage control after the vice
president's comments a day earlier that he sometimes refrains from
speaking up at Cabinet meetings because he is concerned about
leaks, and because he doesn't want President Reagan to be forced to
choose between him and other officials.
   Dukakis, campaigning in West Virginia on Thursday, seized on
that, saying that in Massachusetts he has a ``lively Cabinet, and
sometimes they get loud and contentious.''
   ``That's the way you get good give and take,'' the governor
said. ``I hope I'll have a vice president who speaks up and speaks
out.''
   Attempting to blunt the criticism, Bush spokesman Stephen Hart
said Bush's comments about keeping quiet at Cabinet meetings didn't
mean Bush avoids giving the president his opinions. Hart said Bush
has ample opportunity to do that privately.
   ``He reserves his advice for the president,'' the spokesman said
Thursday as Bush spent a day focusing on education issues.
   The vice president visited James A. Garfield High School in
predominantly Hispanic East Los Angeles. He sat in on a calculus
class taught by Jaime Escalante, whose teaching of advanced math to
disadvantaged students is the subject of a movie, ``Stand and
Deliver.''
   Bush said if he is elected, there will be a ``changing of
priorities to some degree'' to reflect more emphasis on education.
However, he cautioned; ``There has to be a limitation to what the
federal government can do.''
   That stance, too, drew a dig from Dukakis, who discounted Bush's
pledge to be an ``education president.'' The White House, he said,
must always be a supporter of education _ ``not just during
election years.''
   Jackson, for the second day in a row, attacked the Democratic
delegate-selection process, saying Dukakis' big lead in the
delegate race was ``inflated.'' By the latest AP delegate count,
Dukakis has 1,500 to Jackson's 927.
   Campaigning in Kearney, Neb., Jackson said he did not intend to
challenge party rules formally, but that he believed the support of
``super delegates'' should be roughly in line with the popular vote
in contests to date. Super delegates have a voice at the Democratic
National Convention by virtue of their elective or party offices.
   Jackson has won 28 percent of the votes in primaries so far but
is publicly supported by just 46 super delegates. Dukakis, who has
won 37 percent of the primary votes, is supported by 166 super
delegates.
   ``We'll be making appeals for fairness and we certainly hope
people will respond,'' Jackson said. ``What the people are saying
must not be covered up by all the ... talk of the coronation and
`the race is over.' The race is on.''
   Asked about Jackson's complaints, Dukakis campaign spokesman
Mark Gearan said only: ``These rules have been in place for some
time.''
</TEXT>
