<DOCNO> AP880506-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Kurds     05-06 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Kurds,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq's Kurdish Groups Form Front</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Kurdish political parties have formed
a united front to campaign for an autonomous homeland in northern
Iraq, the coalition announced Friday.
   The front consists of all Kurdish parties that have been
battling the government of Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, and it
seeks recognition of ``Kurdish national rights based on a voluntary
union,'' the newly formed front announced.
   A spokesman in Damascus, Syria, telephoned the announcement to
The Associated Press office in Nicosia. It was signed by Massoud
Barzani, leader of the Kurdish Democratic Party, the largest group
in the new front.
   The new coalition is meant ``to strengthen the unity of our
struggle and escalate resistance in Iraqi Kurdistan in the face of
the war of genocide that the Iraqi regime is waging against the
Kurdish population,'' the announcement said.
   The Kurds' fight for autonomy, backed by Iran, has created a
second front in the northern mountains of Iraq in the 7 {-year-old
war between Iran and Iraq.
   The Kurdish struggle has forced the Baghdad government to divert
tens of thousands of troops from the main battlefields.
   There are an estimated 3.5 million Kurds in Iraq. They have been
fighting off and on for 50 years to gain autonomy in the northern
provinces that border Iran, Turkey and Syria.
   The main members of the new union are the Kurdish Democratic
Party and the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, led by Jalal Talebani,
another veteran Kurdish fighter.
   It also includes four smaller parties, the Socialist Party of
Kurdistan, the Popular Democratic Party of Kurdistan, the Kurdish
Socialist Party and the Iraq Communist Party which is dominated by
Kurds.
   The announcement said that a joint committee of leaders of
member parties will lead the front.
   The Kurdish Democratic Party, the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan
and some of the smaller parties in the front joined forces, under
Iranian tutelage, in 1986 to fight the Iraqis.
   Separate Kurdish nationalist groups are agitating for a degree
of autonomy in Turkey, where there are about 10 million Kurds, and
Iran, which has 5.5 million Kurds. They are not connected with the
Iraqi Kurdish front.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
