<HEAD>India Says Border Firing Interfering With Harvest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers in the border town of Poonch
have accused Pakistani soldiers of firing at them and interfering
with the harvest of wheat and other grains along the frontier, the
United News of India reported Friday.
   The news agency said the deputy commissioner in the town
appealed to the Kashmir state government to intervene.
   Both India and Pakistan have troops stationed along their
disputed border in Kashmir.
   UNI said that during a meeting between Indian and Pakistani
military commanders on April 17, Pakistan assured India there would
be no firing on local civilians.
   But UNI said nine shooting incidents have been reported since
then. It quoted the deputy commissioner's report as saying 13
civilians have been killed and more than 24 injured in unprovoked
firing by the Pakistanis in the past year.
