<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Stately     05-06 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Stately,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIM Co-Founder Dead of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE EARTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elaine M. Stately, an Indian activist
and co-founder of the American Indian Movement, has died of cancer.
She was 57.
   Stately died April 27 at her Minneapolis home and was buried
April 30 on the White Earth Indian Reservation in northwestern
Minnesota, where she was born.
   ``We feel it was a very tremendous loss to us. She was very
actively involved in everything involved with Indians. She was very
involved with the youth and mothers, particularly young mothers,''
Clyde Bellecourt, AIM's first chairman, said today.
   Stately was chairwoman of the Minneapolis American Indian Center
for several years and worked for the city of Minneapolis as a
liaison with the Indian community.
   Stately had preached the value of education even as she
struggled to raise a family by herself on welfare.
   While four of her children were still at home, she received her
high school equivalency degree. She attended the University of
Minnesota before leaving to work for the city as an Indian liaison.
   Rebecca Stately said she remembers tagging along as a little
girl with her mother to the first gathering of the Concerned Indian
Americans, an Indian activist group that later changed its name to
the American Indian Movement.
   AIM was founded in Minneapolis in July 1968, said Bellecourt.
   ``She was very active in the efforts to develop the American
Indian Movement,'' Bellecourt said. ``She was one of the founders.''
   Stately is survived by six daughters, three sons, her mother, a
brother, a sister and 13 grandchildren.
</TEXT>
