<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Tax-Mail     05-06 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax-Mail,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sneaky Mailing of Late Taxes May Not Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legal quirk may still allow late taxpayers
to get their forms postmarked before the April 15 filing deadline,
but officials caution against relying on the technicality to avoid
paying penalties.
   The backdated postmarks are available because of a special
Postal Service program for stamp collectors who want to get
examples of stamps postmarked on the first day they are issued.
   Theoretically, the remaining taxpayers who haven't filed could
also use the system to dodge the fact that they missed the deadline
last month, Linn's Stamp News, a newspaper for collectors, suggests
in its May 9 editions.
   But officials of the Postal Service and Internal Revenue Service
said such an action would be questionable.
   Only about 3 million tax returns of the nearly 100 million due
have yet to be filed, the IRS estimates, and most of them are from
Americans overseas, who still have time to file.
   The backdated postmark service is designed to help collectors
who cannot travel from city to city to be present for first day of
issue ceremonies for each new postage stamp.
   New stamps are sold only in the city of issue on the first day,
going on sale elsewhere the next day.
   With the special service, collectors can go to post offices in
their home towns and buy the stamps, place them on envelopes and
mail the envelopes in bulk to the first-day post office for special
cancellations.
   This service is usually offered for about a month after a stamp
is issued, to give collectors time to take advantage of it and to
ease first day pressure on the issuing post office.
   For the new ``E'' stamps, the time has been extended to May 21,
since they were released on rather short notice March 22, in
anticipation of the new postage rates that took effect April 3.
   Thus, in theory at least, a collector could put the new ``E''
stamps on an envelope containing tax forms, send it to Washington
for the first day cancellation, and it would then be delivered with
the date March 22 on the envelope, Linn's reports.
   Technically, then, the taxpayer could still send in the forms
``on time,'' under court decisions that have held a postmark is
evidence of filing.
   But IRS and Postal Service raised questions.
   The first-day-of-issue cancellations look different and are
treated differently from regular date cancellations affixed to
mail, said Dick Rustin, manager of the Postal Service's stamp
information branch.
   Regular cancellations do confirm the date something was mailed,
he said. But, for those which state ``first day of issue,'' he
said, ``we would not verify that the mail entered the system on
that day.''
   Tax forms arriving a month late with a March 22 cancellation
might also raise questions at the IRS, said spokeswoman Johnell
Hunter. She said the tax agency might check to see if the person
sending in the form had a history of being late.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MideastMediation     05-06 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mideast Mediation,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Mediating Between Syria and Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the sidelines of its Middle East diplomacy,
the United States is trying to mediate between the leaders of Syria
and Lebanon who haven't been on speaking terms for more than a year.
   The U.S. diplomatic shuttle was begun nearly five months ago by
April Glaspie, the U.S. ambassador-designate to Iraq, Reagan
administration officials said. Glaspie is focusing on attempts to
negotiate a more equitable power-sharing agreement between
Lebanon's Christians and Moslems.
   Her mission is particularly urgent in the face of a Sept. 23
constitutional deadline for presidential elections in Lebanon, the
officials said. No date has been set for the balloting.
   Syria, which controls parts of Lebanon with more than 30,000
troops, has proposed a formula granting increased power to
Lebanon's Moslem majority. The Christians, led by President Amin
Gemayel, have so far rejected the change, according to Lebanese
Christian groups in Washington.
   Ms. Glaspie, who has good ties with the Syrian leadership from
her days as a political officer in the U.S. Embassy in Damascus,
also has enlisted the help of the Vatican and the French government
to influence the Christians, one U.S. official said.
   Like other State Department officials he spoke on condition of
anonymity so as not to jeopardize Ms. Glaspie's diplomatic effort.
   But the United States does not appear to have much hope of
success.
   ``There are very difficult issues involved so that it's going to
continue to take effort, but we're committed to seeing what we can
do,'' State Department spokesman Charles Redman said this week.
   Another official said that as time for negotiations runs out,
Ms. Glaspie is focusing on getting agreement from both sides to set
an election date and to curb violence by their forces.
   The United States is concerned that if elections are not held,
the ensuing power vacuum would plunge the country into anarchy and
leave it in the hands of the dozens of militias which virtually run
it now, he said.
   ``And of course there's the question of nurturing Syrian good
will,'' the official added.
   Syria is Moscow's main ally in the Middle East and a radical in
the Arab camp. Following a thaw in relations with Washington last
fall, Syrian President Hafez Assad promised to help obtain freedom
for American hostages believed held in Syrian-run sections of
Beirut.
   Under an unwritten 1943 agreement, the presidency in Lebanon is
reserved for a Christian and the posts of prime minister and
parliament speaker for Moslems. This year, however, some leading
Moslems have begun laying claim to the presidency too.
   Gemayel was elected in 1982 when his brother was assassinated
nine days before he was due to take office. He is not running for
another term and the only candidate who has officially declared is
Dany Chamoun, a former Christian militia leader.
   The change in presidents is seen by the Reagan administration as
a good opportunity to seek political reform. The need to stem the
factional violence is particularly urgent for the United States in
view of the collapse of the country's economy, which has all but
wiped out its middle class.
   The Lebanese pound, once the Mideast's most stable currency, has
nosedived to an all-time low of 700 to the dollar. Until 1985 it
was 2.5 to the dollar.
   But a Lebanese Christian official suggested there is more to the
U.S. and Syrian efforts than just a desire for calm in Lebanon.
   ``Lebanon is not the main thrust,'' said Robert Farah, executive
director of the Lebanese Information and Research Center in
Washington which represents a coalition of Christian forces.
   Farah said the United States is hoping it can parlay its help
with Syria's Lebanese problem into Syrian support for U.S. efforts
to start Israeli-Arab peace talks. Syria has so far rejected the
plan.
   The United States also is hoping Syria can use its influence
with the Palestine Liberation Organization to quell a five-month
uprising by Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip against
Israel's occupation, the U.S. official said.
   Syria hopes better relations with the United States may ease
some of its economic problems and ensure its role in future U.S.
diplomacy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
