<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis-NationalGuard     05-06 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-National Guard,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules Against Dukakis In National Guard Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today rejected a lawsuit filed by
Gov. Michael Dukakis aimed at preventing Massachusetts National
Guard troops from training in Central America.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Keeton, in a lengthy opinion, said
federal authorities have the power to give orders to National Guard
troops even when a governor objects.
   Keeton explicitly upheld the constitutionality of the Montgomery
Amendment, a 1986 act of Congress that strips governors of the
power to decline such assignments unless their states are facing an
emergency that requires the Guard.
   Lawyers for the Justice Department had argued that the
Constitution gives Congress final authority over the nation's
entire military apparatus.
   Attorneys for Dukakis had claimed that governors reserve
authority over training the militia.
   At issue in the case was the legality of a Pentagon order
directing 13 public information officers to take part in training
in Panama and Honduras for two weeks in late May and early June.
   Dukakis, a Democratic presidential candidate who has been a
vocal critic of the Reagan administration's Central American
policy, had opposed the directive.
   Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich, joined by Massachusetts and nine
other states, challenged the law last year in U.S. District Court
in St. Paul and lost. That case is now on appeal.
</TEXT>
