<2ND_LINE>AM-Arson Hero,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighter Charged With Setting Fires To Enhance Career</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANOR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A volunteer firefighter who authorities said
started blazes so he could look like a hero by battling them has
been accused of setting six fires since December.
   Michael DeWayne Perkins, 20, was charged after he admitted
setting the fires, Police Chief Albert Olguin said.
   ``He'd always be out there battling the fires,'' Olguin said.
``He was in a way trying to paint a picture of a hero. All the
firefighters thought of him as being a good firefighter.''
   Perkins was charged Thursday with one count of arson and jailed
in lieu of $10,000 bond. Olguin said the other arson cases would be
presented to a grand jury.
   Five of the fires were set in vacant buildings in Manor, east of
Austin, and one grass fire was set, Olguin said. No one was injured.
   Perkins reported the February grass fire just after it was set,
Olguin said.
   Manor Volunteer Fire Chief Hiawatha Nash declined to comment.
   Perkins had been a Manor volunteer firefighter since November
1986, said Dona Pope, assistant city secretary and fire department
secretary.
