<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MeeseIntentions     05-06 0925</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese Intentions,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Quietly Making Plans To Stay at Least Until September</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edwin Meese III is quietly making plans to
remain as attorney general at least until September.
   Despite widespread speculation that the heat generated by
Meese's legal problems will soon drive him from his post, there is
in his latest flap a largely overlooked clue from Meese himself
about his determination to stay on.
   Amid a stream of public disclosures about his assorted legal
problems, Meese last month privately and quickly accepted an
invitation to make an official visit to Japan as attorney general
Aug. 29-Sept. 1. Even though the trip itself has engendered
controversy, he gives every indication of planning to go.
   At Mel Krupin's restaurant, frequented by lawyers and lobbyists,
political operatives and pundits, Krupin says, ``They talk about
Meese but they don't make any comments'' about the propriety of
Meese's actions. ``Nobody knows if he's going to stay or go. They
just talk about how long he'll stay.''
   Independent counsel James McKay is not expected to indict Meese
in any of the handful of cases he has investigated, but McKay's
public report is expected late this month.
   McKay is expected to excoriate Meese for tolerating the
appearance of conflicts of interest even where they may not in fact
exist. Actions creating such appearances are forbidden by
presidential order.
   McKay then is likely to refer his evidence to Justice Department
internal ethics officers for recommendations on whether
administrative discipline by President Reagan is required.
   Most observers predict one of two outcomes: Either Meese will
seize the lack of an indictment as vindication and quickly step
down or McKay's move will allow him to continue for a decent
interval before departing voluntarily.
   A less widely held view is that Meese will not leave unless
Reagan forces him out.
   This debate has emerged from months of seemingly non-stop Meese
revelations.
   On Jan. 29, the Los Angeles Times disclosed a 1986 memo from his
confidant E. Robert Wallach to Meese that, to some, seemed to
suggest illegal bribes to Israeli officials to clear the way for an
oil pipeline.
   On Feb. 11, Meese's former White House colleague Lyn Nofziger
was convicted of lobbying for Wedtech _ a reminder that Meese
remains under investigation for his role on behalf of that Bronx,
N.Y., defense contractor.
   Unseen by the public until this week, an invitation for Meese
arrived March 15 from Japanese Justice Minister Yukio Hayashida to
visit Japan beginning Aug. 29. Meese's official visit would
coincide with a private conference on U.S-Japanese legal issues
running through Sept. 1.
   A day after the invitation arrived, independent counsel Lawrence
Walsh returned an indictment in the Iran-Contra case. Although
Meese was not among Walsh's targets, the charges were a reminder of
Meese's oft-criticized role in investigating that scandal.
   Sometime before the end of March, McKay privately told Meese's
attorneys he did not have enough evidence for indictments in the
pipeline case or in another matter in which Meese approved a major
reversal of Justice Department telephone antitrust policy while
owning stock in regional telephone companies that could benefit
from the reversal.
   On March 29, Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns and Assistant
Attorney William Weld, head of the criminal division, quit on short
notice. They made it clear that they doubted Meese could run the
department effectively, and Weld told Meese that if he were the
independent counsel he would indict the attorney general.
   On April 1, McKay publicly announced his interim decision about
the pipeline and telephone cases, but added that his grand jury had
other matters to investigate.
   On April 4, Meese privately wrote Hayashida he was ``most
pleased to accept your gracious invitation to visit Japan at the
end of this summer.'' Justice Department political appointees this
week described this response as extraordinarily quick compared with
other matters they say have languished in Meese's office for months
and even years, such as whether to challenge two major Supreme
Court rulings on criminal law.
   On April 13, The Associated Press reported that a wealthy
Washington real estate family arranged to pay a $40,000 annual
salary to Meese's wife, Ursula, then won renewal of a $50 million
lease to provide offices for the Justice Department and quickly
sold the building for a $28 million profit. McKay is investigating
the matter.
   On April 20, Burns and Weld met Reagan and told him face-to-face
of their concerns. The president promptly summoned Meese, heard his
side and _ as Reagan has always done before _ reaffirmed support
for his longtime friend.
   On April 21, in his first mention of leaving, Meese told USA
Today, ``If an attorney general was indicted, I think that would be
a basis for stepping aside.'' But he added, ``I don't know of any
factor right now that would cause me to resign.''
   On April 26, the co-sponsor of the Japan conference mailed
30,000 copies of a letter from Meese to lawyers and businessmen
asking them to pay more than $3,000 apiece to join him at the Japan
conference.
   On May 3, Meese's solicitation letter and Japan trip plans were
disclosed in news reports. The Office of Government Ethics opened
an investigation of the arrangements.
   On May 4, William Barraclough, chief executive of the private
group planning the Japan conference, said, ``There are no
indications whatever that Ed Meese is going to back out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Michael J. Sniffen has covered the Justice
Department for The Associated Press since 1980.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
