<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ChicagoMayoral 1stLd-Writethru a0613 05-06 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Mayoral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0613,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules For Special Election in 1989</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 9 grafs detail and background, adds byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cook County judge today ruled that a special
mayoral election should be held in 1989 so that voters can pick a
successor to the late Mayor Harold Washington.
   Circuit Judge Eugene Wachowski issued the ruling after listening
to arguments by a half dozen attorneys representing two groups that
had filed opposing lawsuits over the issue.
   Alderman Timothy Evans, considered a potential candidate and an
opponent of interim Mayor Eugene Sawyer, called the ruling a
``marvelous, marvelous victory'' for the citizens of Chicago.
   A spokesman for a group that favored allowing Sawyer to complete
Washington's term, which would have ended in 1991, said today's
ruling would be appealed.
   Wachowski said it was clearly up to the city Board of Elections
whether to call a special election in 1989, as it in fact did
earlier this week.
   Loud cheers and applause erupted as Wachowski announced his
decision, and he had to call for order.
   Russ Stewart, representing a group called United Citizens of
Chicago and Illinois, had argued against holding a special
election, saying that Sawyer was rightfully elected by the City
Council in December.
   As a result, Stewart told the judge that Sawyer should be
allowed to serve until the next regularly scheduled election in
1991.
   ``We do not believe there has been any disruption in government
from having the vacancy caused by the death of Harold Washington,
and the filling of that vacancy by Mr. Sawyer,'' Stewart said.
   But Tom Johnson, an attorney for a group called The Coalition To
Let The People Decide in 1989, contended that state law clearly
says a special election must be held if more than 28 months remain
in the unexpired term of a vacant municipal office.
   The question is ``whether the voters, the people in the
neighborhoods, will have a chance to participate in deciding who
will govern the city of Chicago for the remainder of (Washington's)
48-month term,'' Johnson told the judge.
   Washington died Nov. 25 of a heart attack and Sawyer was elected
by the city council a week later. Hundreds of Washington and Evans
supporters demonstrated against what they said were ``back-room
deals'' that unfairly left the citizens out of deciding who should
be mayor.
   Evans declined to comment on whether he would run in the special
election, saying, ``You'll have to tune in to see.''
   Kenneth Hurst, president of the United Citizens group and a
former GOP candidate for mayor, said he would appeal the decision.
   He described the group as a non-partisan watchdog organization
seeking fair government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SoldierofFortune     05-06 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soldier of Fortune,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Would-be Hit Man Gets 20 Years in Foiled Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who pleaded guilty in a bungled
murder-for-hire plot was sentenced to 20 years in prison by a judge
who also ordered that he submit to a psychiatric examination.
   Chief U.S. District Judge James DeAnda imposed the maximum
sentence Thursday to William Clayton Buckley of Knoxville, Tenn.,
rejecting prosecutors' recommendation of a 10-year term.
   DeAnda ordered that Buckley, 36, serve the sentence consecutive
to terms totaling 29 years imposed in three other states in cases
involvng assaults.
   The judge said he would resentence Buckley after he was examined
by a psychiatrist.
   Buckley pleaded guilty in a botched attempt to kill a man whose
former girlfriend had answered a ``gun for hire'' advertisement in
Soldier of Fortune magazine.
   Richard Michael Savage, who placed the ad, was convicted last
month in Brownsville of masterminding the attempted murder of Dana
Free. Savage has not been sentenced.
   Savage hired Buckley and Sherry Lynn Breeden, also of Knoxville,
to kill Free, whose ex-girlfriend was angry over losing her life
savings in a business deal with him, testimony showed.
   Buckley and Ms. Breeden botched the job when they threw grenades
into a Pasadena house shortly after Free had left.
   Free's ex-girlfriend, Alive V. Brado, died of emphysema in
October in Kentucky, where she was serving a five-year term
stemming from the plot against Free.
   Buckley and Ms. Breeden pleaded guilty in the Pasadena attack.
   Ward C. Lambeth, of Denver, pleaded guilty to conspiracy for
delivering $15,000 of the $20,000 Ms. Brado agreed to pay for
Free's murder. He was sentenced to five years in prison.
</TEXT>
