<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraLawsuit 1stLd-Writethru a0632 05-06 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys For Honey, Avirgan Say Case Stalled To Protect Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, ``In the hearing xxx, to CORRECT attorney's
first name, Daniel sted Michael</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for two journalists who accuse U.S. and
Contra officials of running an illegal drug and arms smuggling ring
said today their case is being thwarted by federal officials trying
to protect Vice President George Bush.
   The comments came during a hearing on the $24 million damage
suit that was filed in federal court here by journalists Tony
Avirgan and Martha Honey. They are represented by The Christic
Institute, a liberal policy group.
   Avirgan was injured in a May 1984 bombing which the two blame on
a group that includes Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim, two
businessmen who were charged with conspiracy and theft in the
Iran-Contra case.
   The lawsuit does not cite any U.S. government officials among
its 29 defendants. Central to the lawsuit is the claim that the
defendants conspired to traffic in drugs and plot assassinations in
Central America and elsewhere. The defendants have denied the
charges.
   The lawsuit, filed in May 1986, several months before the
Iran-Contra affair was exposed publicly, names some of the people
in the private network that Lt. Col. Oliver L. North formed to help
the Nicaraguan Contras, who oppose Nicaragua's leftist government.
   The allegations in the civil lawsuit _ set for trial June 26 in
federal court in Miami _ are broader than the issues raised by
Lawrence Walsh, the independent counsel in the Iran-Contra case.
   In the hearing today before U.S. District Judge James King,
Christic attorney Daniel Sheehan said part of their case involved
Bush's directorship of the Central Intelligence Agency in 1976 when
he allegedly allowed covert operations to ``go off the books'' to
prevent them from being ended by the incoming administration of
President Jimmy Carter.
   During a recess, Sheehan told The Associated Press that some of
the defendants in the case ``were running the covert operations for
George Bush.''
   Sheehan said the case was being held up to protect Bush, who is
virtually certain to be the Republican nominee for president this
year.
   Attorneys for some of the defendants were to speak later in the
day.
   The Honey-Avirgan lawsuit claims that ``a secret team'' headed
by former CIA official Theodore Shackley worked over two decades to
manage a covert, shadow government funded with drug profits. There
has never been independent confirmation of the charge.
   Today's hearing involved a series of pretrial motions, including
one by Sheehan to have the judge grant immunity to potential
witnesses who refused to testify for fear of prosecution.
   Attorneys for Avirgan and Honey said they have been unable to
investigate the case because important witnesses, including Jesus
Garcia and Jack Terrell, have been threatened with indictment if
they speak to investigators for Honey and Avirgan.
   Sheehan's assistant Lewis Pitts said a grand jury investigation
in Miami ``was used to silence these little people to interfere
with the investigation.''
</TEXT>
