<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NewCaledonia     05-06 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Caledonia,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Separatists Vow Vengeance; Police On Alert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL DONNET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Melanesian separatists on Friday
vowed to avenge the ``premeditated butchery'' of 19 kidnappers
killed during a dramatic rescue of 23 French lawmen. Police and
army personnel were put on full alert.
   The Kanak Socialist National Liberation Front, the main
Melanesian separatist group, called for Saturday to be a ``day of
active mourning of the same level as the massacre on Ouvea'' and
urged work stoppages and barricades to be set up in the streets.
   French police said the bodies of three more kidnappers were
found on the island of Ouvea. They also said the presumed chief of
the captors, Alphonse Dianou, died of wounds inflicted during
Thursday's assault.
   His death and the discovery of the three bodies brought the
death toll among the kidnappers to 19. Two members of a French
assault team also died. Five people were injured.
   This French Pacific territory appeared calm Friday after troops
stormed the secluded cave on Ouvea and freed the hostages.
   Bernard Pons, France's minister for overseas territories, said
the 7,000 army and gendarmerie personnel on New Caledonia were
placed on a state of ``absolute alert.''
   Pons said ``terrorists ... will find themselves in front of
entirely determined men.'' He did not elaborate.
   The rescue team pelted the cave with tear gas canisters during
the nearly seven-hour battle on Ouvea, which is in the Loyalty
island group. The hostages freed themselves from their manacles
with a key that had been smuggled in by a hostage who was being
used as a go-between with French authorties.
   Melanesians make up 36 percent of the territory's 145,000
people, while European settlers comprise about 43 percent. The rest
are Asian or Polynesian.
   The Melanesian front is seeking independence from France, which
has ruled New Caledonia since 1853.
   The kidnappings began on April 22 during a wave of violence by
Melanesians protesting the first phase of the French presidential
elections on April 24. A group of separatists stormed a police
station, killed four gendarmes and seized several others.
   On April 27, eight other lawmen were seized when they tried to
negotiate the release of the other hostages.
   Both Pons and conservative Premier Jacques Chirac have referred
to the main separatist organization as a ``terrorist group.'' Pons
has asked that it be outlawed, a position Chirac supports.
   In an interview published Friday in several French newspapers,
Chirac said that ``after the failure of the terrorists ... it is
possible to build a fraternal Caledonia ... where no one feels
excluded.''
   Chirac and Socialist President Francois Mitterrand are vying for
the presidency in elections on Sunday, and their positions on New
Caledonia differ.
   Chirac takes a hard line, while Mitterrand favors mediation
between the European settlers and the native Melanesians, who have
become a minority in their own land since France colonized it in
1853.
</TEXT>
