<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Fitzwater     05-06 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Fitzwater,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Cabinet Silence ``Courageous,'' Fitzwater Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Friday it is ``admirable and courageous'' of his old boss, Vice
President George Bush, to refrain from making recommendations to
President Reagan during Cabinet meetings.
   Fitzwater, who was Bush's press secretary before becoming the
chief White House spokesman last year, was asked about statements
the vice president made during a presidential campaign swing
through Western states.
   Bush, speaking to reporters during a campaign stop in Sacramento
on Wednesday, said ``kiss and tell'' books about the administration
are partly to blame for his reluctance to speak up more in meetings.
   The vice president also said, ``I hold back speaking in meetings
because I don't want the president to have to be choosing between
his vice president and the other members of the Cabinet.''
   Fitzwater said, ``The vice president has taken that position
since day one, that he is a private adviser to the president. He
reserves his recommendations and confidence for the president and
often doesn't voice his feelings in meetings for that very reason,
that they will be leaked or go to the press, or that various people
will try to use his (positions) to take sides to the president.''
   ``He has defined an appropriate position for the vice president
that I find admirable and courageous in view of the heavy pressures
that are continually put on him to talk,'' Fitzwater said. ``He has
for the first time in history defined the vice presidency in a way
that is meaningful to the president and has made it the
confidential adviser that I think is very important; and I suspect
future vice presidents will want to follow that mold.''
   Fitzwater also said that the president will soon endorse Bush,
who has amassed more than the number of delegates needed for the
Republican presidential nomination, ``at an appropriate ceremony
and function ... probably with very high visibility.''
   He said the White House was not ready to announce when this will
be. The president will speak at a fund-raising dinner for
Republican congressional candidates on Wednesday. Fitzwater said
Bush was expected to attend.
</TEXT>
