<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Najib     05-06 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Najib,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib Says He'll Deal With Guerrillas Militarily or Politically</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib of Afghanistan said
Friday his army would deal ``a heavy and severe blow'' to Moslem
guerrillas if they keep fighting his government but said his offer
of a political role for the guerrillas stands.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas, whose headquarters are in Pakistan,
have refused to participate in any government headed by Najib. In a
statement issued Friday in New Delhi, they attacked ``India's
misconceived policy of taking (the) side of (the) criminal regime
of Kabul.''
   The Afghan president met Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and several
top government officials during his three-day stay in New Delhi and
then held a press conference.
   Najib said India and Afghanistan, whose mutual antagonist is
Pakistan, achieved new levels of cooperation during his visit.
   The Indian government announced that India has agreed to supply
Afghanistan with 2,000 tons of tea over a four-year period. Joint
ventures and an Indian role in reconstruction projects were also
discussed, but no details were given.
   Najib also told reporters he had rejected a petition by foreign
journalists to free an Italian journalist and a French photographer
jailed in Afghanistan on espionage charges.
   When asked about the fate of the two journalists, Najib, former
head of Afghanistan's KBG-style secret police, said, ``Both
participated in the war conflicts and illegally entered
Afghanistan. They resorted to subversive activities.''
   Fausto Biloslavo, an Italian who worked for the small Albatross
News Agency, was captured in July 1987, convicted in March of
spying and sentenced to seven years in prison.
   Alain Guillo, a French free-lancer who often worked for the
Sygma photo agency, was captured in March 1987, convicted Jan. 4 of
spying and sentenced to 10 years in prison.
   Both men were captured after entering the country with the
guerrillas, who have been fighting nearly 10 years to oust Najib's
Soviet-backed government.
   Friday's news conference was a reflection of Najib's increased
availability to non-Soviet bloc reporters and coincides with
Moscow's preparations to start withdrawing its estimated 115,000
soldiers from Afghanistan.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to prop up a
socialist government against attacks by Islamic guerrillas. The
Soviet withdrawal is scheduled to begin May 15 under an agreement
signed in Geneva on May 14 by the Soviet Union, the United States,
Afghanistan and Pakistan.
   Najib said the guerrillas ``are actually doing a political
suicide'' by refusing to talk with his government.
   He reiterated that the deposed Afghan king, Zahir Shah, was free
to return home to participate in politics.
   Zahir Shah was overthrown in 1973 by a cousin who in turn was
assassinated in 1978. Afghan refugees and some Western officials
have suggested that Zahir Shah's return from his exile in Rome
might pave the way for a transition of government.
   An Indian official, speaking after Najib's news conference, said
India had played an informal role in discussing the Afghan problems
with the deposed king, as well as with the United States, the
Soviet Union and Pakistan. The official spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Najib flew home to Afghanistan shortly after the news conference.
</TEXT>
