<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua-Quake 2ndLd-Writethru   05-06 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Quake, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0624,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tremors Felt in Nicaragua, Costa Rica</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with reports of damage in
southern Nicaragua. Pick up 7th pvs, `Managua was...' Adds byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake sent frightened
residents into the streets today, and state-run radio said some
buildings were damaged in the southern town of Rivas.
   Radio broadcasts called on the public to remain calm.
   The quake at 8:46 a.m. (10:46 a.m. EDT) measured 5.7 on the
Richter scale, said John Minsch, a geophysicist with the U.S.
Geological Survey's National Earthquake Information Center at
Golden, Colo.
   The quake was centered near the west coast of Nicaragua about 80
miles south of Managua, he said.
   Most workers and residents returned to their jobs or daily
routines within minutes of the tremor. Some Managua residents said
they felt two tremors, but there were no immediate reports of
damage or injury in the capital.
   Radio Sandino said some homes suffered damages in Rivas, 70
miles south of Managua.
   Managua was devastated by an earthquake in December 1972 that
killed at least 10,000 people.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage in
populated areas, and a quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage
in populated areas.
</TEXT>
