<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WVaGovernor     05-06 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WVa Governor,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Democrats, Two Republicans Fighting For Governorship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Gov. Arch Moore has battled
back into the lead against a millionaire primary challenger who
seeks to deny him a shot at a fourth term as leader of this
financially troubled state.
   Seven Democrats are seeking their party's nomination for
governor in Tuesday's election, with polls showing the two
front-runners too close to call in an increasingly strident race.
   Moore's opponent is Morgantown businessman John Raese, a coal,
steel and media company owner who narrowly lost to then-Gov. Jay
Rockefeller in the 1984 U.S. Senate election.
   He has accused Moore of waging a ``rose garden'' campaign,
refusing to debate him and relying on his status as governor to
carry him through the election.
   Moore, 65, claims to have cut taxes by $311 million in the past
four years, although he fought most of the cuts when they were
imposed by the Legislature.
   He also cites his accomplishments at bringing news businesses
and bringing 30,000 jobs to the state, although the total number of
employed West Virginians has increased by just 5,700 since Moore
took office in 1985.
   Moore insists that the state is making an economic recovery, but
Raese and the Democrats say otherwise. Mario Palumbo, a state
senator from Charleston, says the state will face a $400 million
deficit when the fiscal year ends June 30 and should declare
bankruptcy. Raese says Moore has made just 10 percent of $385
million in budget cuts recommended by the Governor's Task Force on
Waste Management.
   The 38-year-old Raese, who inherited much of his wealth, has
gained a reputation of a ``rich kid'' who loves fast boats and hard
living. At a Dallas hotel in 1984, while attending the Republican
National Convention, Raese grabbed a newspaper reporter by the
lapels and proclaimed ``I buy and sell reporters like you every
day.''
   Earlier this week, Raese's wife, Liz, called her husband ``a
man's man'' and said he is not the ``party animal'' many people
believe him to be.
   ``Sure, John loves fast cars and fast boats. When he gets
stressed out, that's his release,'' she said. ``In fact, we have
our best love affairs in the middle of the ocean. There is solitude
out there. You're alone.''
   When Republicans were surveyed April 13-18 for the West Virginia
Poll, Raese had a 54 percent to 30 percent lead. But Moore had not
yet begun his television and newspaper advertising, and in the past
two weeks he has been on the road campaigning almost constantly,
promising state money for various projects and announcing plant
openings in Elkins and South Charleston.
   In a new poll conducted Monday through Wednesday, Moore was
favored 48 percent to 35 percent. The copyright poll, conducted for
The Associated Press, Charleston Daily Mail and WSAZ-TV by
Ryan-Samples Research Inc., is based on telephone interviews
conducted with 306 registered Democrats and 275 registered
Republicans and independents selected at random. It had a margin of
error of 5.6 percent.
   On the Democratic side, Clyde See, 46, and Gaston Caperton, 48,
have waged an expensive battle of television commercials accusing
each other of various misdeeds.
   See, a former House of Delegates speaker and the party's 1984
nominee for governor, has ridiculed Caperton's business practices
and his refusal to sign a voluntary campaign spending limit.
   See's ads point out that a study found a 25 percent error rate
in state claims processed by Caperton's insurance company,
McDonough Caperton Insurance Group of Charleston. The company
handles the state employee insurance system.
   Caperton has responded by saying he built the nation's 18th
largest insurance company and accused See of engaging in
``old-style politics'' and a dirty campaign full of ``distortion.''
   In the latest West Virginia Poll, among Democrats surveyed,
Caperton was named by 30 percent, while See was picked by 29
percent, with the rest divided among the five other candidates or
undecided.
   Caperton has also come under fire for his heavy spending. In a
statement filed with the secretary of state on Wednesday, he listed
$1.8 million in campaign expenses _ more than three times that of
any other candidate.
   ``I have had to use TV because I came into the race relatively
unknown,'' said Caperton, making his first try for public office.
``The criticism from the other candidates is nothing more than a
show of frustration and desperation.''
</TEXT>
