<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatherSerra     05-06 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Father Serra,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Franciscan Missionary Step Closer To Sainthood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The beatification of Father Junipero Serra
means the Roman Catholic church is finally coming to appreciate
U.S. history, says a diocesan spokesman, but his detractors blame
the founder of the mission system for helping destroy Indian
culture.
   The Vatican will beatify Serra, an 18th-century priest and one
of the first Europeans in California, on Sept. 25. Beatification is
one step from sainthood, and many in the church here hope it will
lead to sainthood for Serra.
   A contingent of Roman Catholic bishops from California plans to
travel to Rome for the ceremony.
   ``The church has finally caught up to U.S. history,'' said Ted
Elisee, spokesman for the Diocese of Monterey, where Serra is
buried at the Carmel Mission Basilica.
   ``He has been called California's first citizen. He was a great
historical figure in the U.S., and the church is catching up with
him,'' said Elisee. ``For those who are devoted to him, this is an
affirmation and a confirmation of their belief. For them, this is a
great moment.''
   Serra, a Franciscan born on the island of Majorca, established
the first of nine missions in San Diego in 1769. Altogether, 21
missions were created by his order from San Diego to Sonoma.
   When the pope visited the United States last year, he stopped at
Serra's grave and lauded his work.
   Serra's remains were exhumed in 1943 for archaeological and
canonical purposes, then reburied in the middle vault in a copper
coffin with an air-tight glass inner lid. The coffin was sealed
with brass wire, then marked with images of the Virgin Mary and
with crosses.
   In May 1985, Serra was declared venerable by the church. Once
Roman Catholic authorities agreed that Serra had accomplished one
miracle, beatification was in line. If a second miracle can be
confirmed, Serra can be declared a saint.
   The first miracle involved the recovery of Franciscan Sister
Boniface Dyrda, now 71 and living in St. Louis, who was diagnosed
as fatally ill in 1960. She recovered from what was found to be
lupus, tuberculosis of the skin, after she and her order prayed to
Serra, Elisee said.
   Indian groups have opposed honors for Serra, who they say
subjected Indian converts to corporal punishment and forcibly kept
them inside the missions, where they were separated by sex and
required to do farming and construction tasks.
   His actions, including stealing Indian lands and exposing
Indians to European diseases for which they had no resistance,
helped destroy Indian culture, the critics say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1434EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mother'sDay     05-06 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mother's Day,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother's Shrine Celebrates 80th Anniversary Of First Mother's Day
Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAFTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carnations, roses and memories will fill a
chapel when sons and daughters gather to honor their mothers
Sunday, 80 years after the nation's first Mother's Day service was
celebrated here.
   ``We expect to have a full house. We usually do,'' said Lenore
Shafer, a tour guide at the Mother's Day Shrine. ``I think
everybody has a feeling for their mother.
   ``Everybody doesn't have children, but everybody has a mother.''
   Tourists from all 50 states, England, Canada and even Japan have
visited the shrine, located in a former Methodist church built in
1872, Shafer said.
   ``Some like the hard-carved pews, others come to see our stained
glass windows and murals,'' said Betty Hayhurst, chairwoman of the
committee that oversees the shrine. ``A lot of young people come
here too. It's not just old people.''
   Anna Jarvis, the founder of national Mother's Day, spelled out
its purpose in a letter to organizers 80 years ago: ``To revive the
dormant love and filial gratitude we owe to those who gave us
birth. ... To brighten the lives of good mothers. To have them know
we appreciate them, though we do not often show it as we might.''
   The first Mother's Day celebration on May 10, 1908, at Andrews
Methodist Church in Grafton, and another at Wanamaker's Auditorium
in Philadelphia that afternoon, marked the death of Miss Jarvis'
mother, Anna Maria Jarvis, three years earlier.
   Back in the 1850s, when the area around Grafton was still part
of Virginia, Mrs. Jarvis had been spurred to work against
unsanitary living conditions in the region by the deaths of eight
of her 12 children before they reached adulthood.
   Her ``Mother's Day Work Clubs'' in Grafton and nearby towns were
so successful that doctors urged others to follow her example. The
clubs also won praise for easing hostility among neighbors during
the Civil War, when the slavery issue divided families and
ultimately divided Virginia itself.
   Throughout the last years of her life, Mrs. Jarvis shared her
dream of a day set aside for the mothers of the world _ living and
dead _ with Anna.
   But she did not live long enough to see her dream come true.
   According to the book ``Mother's Day and the Mother's Day
Church,'' Anna, then a 41-year-old spinster, vowed to herself to
establish Mother's Day as her mother's casket was being lowered
into her grave at West Chester, Pa.
   The idea soon became an obsession as Miss Jarvis worked to
promote the day with personal appearances and letter-writing
campaigns.
   She finally persuaded John Wanamaker, a Philadelphia merchant
and philanthropist, to support her in her quest. Wanamaker later
became part of a committee, along with food manufacturer H.J.
Heinz, that mapped out a program to extend Mother's Day around the
world.
   After the first celebration in 1908, the idea caught on quickly,
and by the following year Mother's Day was observed in at least one
town in nearly all the states, as well as Puerto Rico, Canada and
Mexico.
   A year later, Gov. William E. Glasscock proclaimed the second
Sunday in May as Mother's Day in West Virginia, and in 1914,
President Woodrow Wilson did the same for the whole country.
   Flowers have been part of Mother's Day since Miss Jarvis sent
500 white carnations, chosen to represent purity, to Grafton for
the first celebration. Participants were urged to wear a red
carnation if their mother was living, and white if their mother was
dead.
   ``It is definitely the biggest holiday of the year for us,''
said Rocky Pollitz, vice president of industry relations for
Teleflora, the nation's largest independently owned floral company.
   ``People may not think of sending flowers all year, but on
Mother's Day, everybody thinks of flowers.''
   Many, whose mothers have died, send flowers to the shrine,
Hayhurst said. The flowers are taken to nursing homes and hospitals
following the Mother's Day service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Alice'sRestaurant     05-06 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Alice's Restaurant,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restaurant Of Hippie Fame Reopens As Fancy Deli</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oh no! Has Alice's Restaurant gone
yuppie?
   Well, the restaurant Arlo Guthrie made famous in his talking
anti-war song ``Alice's Restaurant'' has been reborn as a fancy
delicatessen, and it does feature such fare as red potatoes stuffed
with caviar.
   But Joey Wheaton and Bernie Mallon bristled Friday at the
suggestion that their restaurant seemed to be a yuppie version of
the eating spot that had been a symbol of the hippie days of the
1960s.
   ``We haven't made that much money yet,'' said Wheaton. ``We're
still driving a secondhand station wagon.''
   They said that since they opened La Fete Chez Vous last month
there have been only a few visits by people in search of the folksy
spot Alice Brock ran in the 1960s.
   ``Some people will ask `Didn't Alice's Restaurant used to be in
Stockbridge,' and we'll tell them, `You're sitting in it,''' said
Wheaton.
   Guthrie's song chronicled a 1965 arrest that kept the narrator
out of the Vietnam War-era draft after his conviction for littering
after he dumped the remains of a Thanksgiving dinner he had eaten
at Ms. Brock's home.
   Mallon worked for Ms. Brock before she left the restaurant. She
now works in a restaurant in Provincetown, on Cape Cod.
</TEXT>
