<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DogDeaths     05-06 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dog Deaths,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Defends Dog Killings, Says Town Has Serious Stray Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKSHEAR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Harry Adams on Friday defended a
police officer who used a shotgun and nightstick to kill two dogs,
saying the city has a serious problem with stray dogs.
   The town, Adams said, has received angry phone calls and hate
mail over the incident. ``People have looked at one side of the
story.''
   The dogs, frequent companions to a disabled veteran, were shot
by Sgt. James Mock. A witness and the Ofekenofee Humane Society in
nearby Waycross obtained warrants from a probate judge charging
Mock with cruelty to animals. He is free on $500 bond.
   Adams said the Georgia Bureau of Investigation, asked to
investigate, had decided no crime was committed.
   The town, he said, has bought a tranquilizer gun, and police
will be taught to use it.
   ``We love animals as much as anyone else,'' the mayor said.
``We're not out to kill dogs ... only eliminate dogs that we
consider dangerous to human life.''
   Adams also disputed claims by Harriett Dixon, director of the
humane society, that up to eight dogs may have died in the April 29
incident.
   ``To set the record straight, only two dogs were killed,'' he
said. ``Three shots were fired, one or more of which killed one dog
and critically wounded the other. The officer took his baton and
finished killing the second dog.''
   Since the humane society became involved, Ms. Dixon said, she
has received telephone threats to stay out of Blackshear.
   ``This is not the first time this has happened,'' she said.
``Dogs have been shot in front of people's homes. The people
telling me these things are afraid to identify themselves.''
   Adams said 61-year-old Elliott Trueluck had been warned
repeatedly to keep the dogs outside the city, which has a leash
law. Trueluck is well-known in Blackshear because he strolls to a
restaurant just about every morning, followed by a pack of dogs.
   Adams cited an ordinance that gives police the authority to kill
vicious animals; police, he said, had received numerous complaints
about Trueluck's dogs.
   Police Chief Dennis Martin said one of the dogs once tried to
attack a waitress at the restaurant and others had almost caused an
auto accident while fighting in a street in the south Georgia town
of 3,500 people.
   City officials have said Trueluck laughed off the warnings.
   Trueluck said he has been afraid to walk to town since the
shooting.
   ``It scared the I-don't-know-what out of me,'' he said.
   His wife, Myrtice, said he receives a small disability check
every month because he has never recovered from being ``shell
shocked'' in the Pacific during World War II.
</TEXT>
