<1ST_LINE>r i AM-People-JuanCarlos     05-06 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Juan Carlos,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spanish King Made Honorary Citizen Of Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Juan Carlos of Spain became an honorary citizen
of the Eternal City during a majestic ceremony Friday at the city
council chamber overlooking Michelangelo's Capitoline Square.
   President Francesco Cossiga, members of Spanish royalty and
Italian aristocracy, top government officials, diplomats and red
and purple-robed cardinals and prelates attended the ceremony.
   Nicola Signorello, mayor of Rome, enlarged on the personal ties
that link the city with Juan Carlos, who was born here on Jan. 5,
1938. His grandfather, King Alfonso XIII, had been exiled from
Spain in 1931.
   Signorello said that, among other things, Juan Carlos was being
honored for ``guiding with firmness and far-sightedness the re-born
Spanish democracy towards a future of peace, liberty, prosperity
and social advances.''
   ``Rome gave us the spiritual texture of our society _ law,
language, political and administrative organization and art,'' the
monarch replied in Italian.
   Later, in the courtyard of the Capitoline Museums, the king was
given an award by the Italian Solidarity Center, which works to
rehabilitate drug addicts. The group wanted to spotlight the king's
interest in fighting drug addiction, which Juan Carlos has called a
``de-humanizing culture.''
</TEXT>
