<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1752EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Awad-Profile     05-06 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Awad-Profile,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advocate of Non-Violence But Fighter For Palestine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As an advocate of non-violence, Mubarak Awad
would seem to be the type of Palestinian leader the Israeli
government could accept.
   But Israel declared the Jerusalem-born American a danger to the
state and ordered him deported. Protests by the United States
halted earlier efforts to deport Awad, who lived 15 years in the
Midwest and holds U.S. citizenship.
   Awad has called for his fellow Arabs to use non-violent means,
rather than stone-throwing or gunfire, to express their longing for
a homeland.
   But Awad's strategy of strikes, boycotts and non-cooperation has
helped fuel the current Palestinian uprising in the occupied
territories. He also has made clear that, like armed PLO
guerrillas, he wants an independent Palestine.
   Awad, 44, is founder of the Palestinian Center for the Study of
Non-violence and says his ideas come from the passive resistance of
Mohandas K. Gandhi, the Indian leader known as the Mahatma, or
``great soul.''
   His gentle manner adds to the impression that he is an advocate
of peace. One friend commented that the soft-spoken Awad must have
been very good at what he did for years: counseling juvenile
delinquents in Ohio.
   Awad, for all his advocacy of non-violence, also has not
condemned Palestinian guerrillas. Asked recently about his thoughts
on Palestinian fighters, he replied:
   ``They have the right. If they think they can achieve things
with guns, that is up to them. I cannot achieve things with guns. I
don't think it achieves anything.''
   An Israeli statement accuses Awad of encouraging civil
disobedience, which he has advocated, but also of helping prepare
leaflets that call for violence against Israel.
   Awad's wife, Nancy Nye from Wilmington, Ohio, denies her husband
authored such leaflets and insists he does not want to destroy
Israel. But she added: ``No matter where he is, he will be working
for Palestinian independence.''
   Awad was born in Jerusalem in 1943, before the creation of
Israel.
   Ms. Nye said Awad's father was shot and killed in the 1948
Arab-Israeli war when he left the family home to help a wounded
man. Awad was brought up by his mother, a nurse.
   A year after Israel captured Arab east Jerusalem in the 1967
Middle East War, Awad went to the United States to study and
received a master's degree from Saint Francis College in Fort
Wayne, Ind.
   He settled in Wapakoneta, Ohio, became a youth counselor and
founded a string of counseling services. He has two children by a
previous marriage, who live in Bluffton, Ohio.
   Awad began returning to Jerusalem on visits in 1983 and two
years later came back for good. His calls for strikes and boycotts
of Israeli goods have caused him regular trouble with authorities.
   He has been arrested at least four times. Last November, Israel
refused to renew his tourist visa and tried to deport him then.
   But after five months of a sustained Arab uprising, Israel
seemed to have no hesitation about expelling the man who says
non-violence is the way to Palestinian independence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
