<DOCNO> AP880506-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1754EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Widow'sMinistry     05-06 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Widow's Ministry,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Department Orders Widow to Stop Feeding Homeless in Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A widow says she'll find another way to help
others now that health officials have told her she has to stop
taking homemade soup and sandwiches to homeless people at a park.
   Doraine Frick has been taking food, paid for through donations
of her prayer group and cooked in her own kitchen, to Pioneer Park
in this Phoenix suburb every Wednesday for about two years. But the
meal served Wednesday to about 30 people was the last, she said
Thursday.
   Mrs. Frick, 58, said she won't fight the edict by the Maricopa
County Health Department, adding that she considers it God's
message for her to move on to another ministry.
   ``But this isn't right,'' said Dave Peck, a homeless man who
said he's been hanging around Pioneer Park since 1982. ``These
ladies go out of their way to come down here to feed people that
are living on the streets.''
   Peck said Mrs. Frick and her helper, Lelia Parlier, also have
brought razors, blankets, clothing, toothpaste and toothbrushes to
the park.
   ``They go out of their way,'' he said. ``They'll walk around the
park and ask people if they are hungry.''
   Roy Willis, a Health Department supervisor, said the county had
no choice but to halt Mrs. Frick's operation after a city employee
filed a complaint with the department April 27.
   ``All food must come from an approved source and be prepared in
an approved kitchen,'' Willis said, calling Mrs. Frick's operation
``illegal under any circumstances.''
   ``You just can't prepare food out of your home and take it and
give it away or sell it or whatever to the general public or
anybody else,'' Willis said. ``By law, we have to have control over
how the food is prepared, handled and given away to prevent people
from getting sick.''
   He said the law protects Mrs. Frick, too.
   ``If we get a mass food-borne illness, her liability would be
unbelievable,'' Willis said.
   After a county health officer left a notice at her home to cease
feeding people from food made in her home, Mrs. Frick said, she
went to the park and told the homeless ``we would not be coming
back anymore.''
   Mrs. Frick said she went each Thursday to Hillman Catholic
Renewal Center in Glendale where her prayer group collected money
to buy the food she put into the weekly meals for the poor.
   She said she wanted to use the kitchen at Queen of Peace
Catholic Church, which she attends, but she said it is committed to
the church school's hot lunch program.
   Willis said if the meals were prepared in a church, his
inspectors would examine the kitchen and waive the permit fee.
   If someone doesn't feed the poor, Mrs. Frick said, ``you are
going to find more crime in the city. I feel I've done a lot of
good helping these guys and giving them hope. They know somebody
cares.''
</TEXT>
