<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Stallone     05-06 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Stallone,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Dept. Subpoenas Stallone Production Company Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Justice Department has subpoenaed the
records of Sylvester Stallone's production company as part of a
grand jury investigation of the Teamsters union's influence in the
entertainment industry, Daily Variety reported.
   The newspaper's sources said Stallone's White Eagle company was
not the focus of the investigation, but the government is
interested in its relationship with labor and studio consultant
Marty Bacow.
   The Justice Department also was looking into the relationship
between Bacow, the Teamsters and other unidentified Hollywood
production companies, Variety said Thursday.
   ``Let them keep fishing,'' Bacow told Variety. ``I haven't done
anything wrong. Let them do what they want.''
   Stallone attorney Steve Wehner declined to comment.
   Bacow's relationship with Stallone goes back to 1983, when Bacow
served as a consultant for the movie ``Rhinestone.''
   Bacow described Stallone, star of the ``Rambo'' and ``Rocky''
movies, as a ``square guy'' and said it was unfortunate his name
became involved in the investigation.
   ``It should never come to this,'' Bacow said.
   Variety said the Justice Department was trying to determine
whether any of Bacow's relationships might have violated the Hobbs
Act, which makes it illegal for a union representative to demand
something of value in return for labor peace; the Taft-Hartley Act,
which makes it illegal for an employer to give anything of value to
a union leader; or the broader Racketeer Influenced Corrupt
Organizations Act.
   Bacow said he has never acted secretly in his role as a
Hollywood labor consultant.
   ``Anything I've ever done for the studios, they've paid me by
check and I've paid my taxes on it,'' he said. ``I have never been
an official of any union, or a representative of such.''
</TEXT>
