<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Shepard     05-06 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Shepard,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First U.S. Astronaut Says NASA Did Good Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA may almost have been too successful in its
campaign to put men on the moon, said America's first astronaut in
a speech marking the 27th anniversary of his brief ride into space.
   ``NASA became overloaded, too successful. They did too good a
job,'' said Alan Shepard, commenting on the disaster that destroyed
the space shuttle Challenger.
   Shephard became the first to ride a Mercury capsule into space
on May 5, 1961; shortly afterwards President John Kennedy announced
that the nation would attempt to land men on the moon before the
end of the 1960s.
   Shepard followed his 15-minute suborbital trip aboard Freedom 7
by commanding the Apollo 14 mission to the moon in 1971.
   The former astronaut, now a businessman, spoke at a Rotary Club
of Houston luncheon Thursday.
   ``If, 30 years ago, we had said that we were only going to have
two incidents when we had fatalities, all of us would have said, `I
just hope we are that lucky,''' Shepard said. ``The odds were just
not that good 30 years ago.''
   Seven crew members died when Challenger exploded in 1986, and
three astronauts died in a 1967 fire at the Kennedy Space Center
during a training exercise.
</TEXT>
