<DOCNO> AP880506-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1854EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     05-06 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers, Judge Discuss Handling of Classified Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procedures for defense examination of
classified documents in the Iran-Contra conspiracy case were
discussed Friday in a closed hearing convened by U.S. District
Judge Gerhard A. Gesell.
   Gesell convened the hearing to question government security
officials about what he had termed a lack of progress in the
production of classified documents he ruled the defense could
examine.
   But after a lengthy discussion, Gesell reportedly told lawyers
in the case that progress had been made toward eliminating some
procedural obstacles to defense review of the material.
   Retired Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L. North, former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter and retired Air Force Maj. Gen.
Richard V. Secord attended the hearing with their attorneys.
   Businessman Albert Hakim, the fourth defendant in the case, did
not attend but was represented by his lawyers.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh has collected some 300,000
pages of classified documents, of which he says 50,000 are relevant
to the case. Gesell has ordered that the defense be allowed to
examine all 300,000 pages.
   The judge has said the defendants must be allowed to review the
material with their lawyers, but court security officials have
barred Hakim from seeing the documents because he has never had a
government security clearance.
   The other three defendants all had high-level clearances,
although Secord has been in private business for several years.
   Secord has also encountered procedural obstacles to his
examination of documents, according to court papers filed in the
case.
   Gesell convened the hearing after learning from Walsh earlier
this week that 105,000 pages of classified material had been
deposited in a special secure facility constructed by the Justice
Department for use by the defense lawyers to work with the
documents.
   The four defendants are charged with conspiring to defraud the
government by diverting profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   The judge had previously warned that unless the defense gets
access to the material and is able to obtain government
declassification of relevant documents, he might be forced to
dismiss charges in the case.
   Under the Classified Information Procedures Act, secret
documents must be declassified by government agencies before they
can be introduced as evidence.
   In ordering the hearing, Gesell said he was dismayed by ``the
apparent lack of progress being made in declassifying essential
papers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
