<DOCNO> AP880506-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0694 05-06 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0694,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Hostages Mistreated While Trying To Escape, Reports Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: In grafs 2-4 CORRECTS to give full name Frank Herbert Reed
(not Frank Herbert).
^LaserPhoto NY8</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American hostages in Lebanon were brutally
mistreated for trying to escape from their pro-Iranian captors, a
freed French hostage was quoted as saying Friday.
   Journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmann shared a cell recently with
American Frank Herbert Reed who was ``mistreated to the point of
being left prostrate,'' Kauffmann's sister, Marie-Genevieve Dagin,
was quoted as saying.
   Reed was director of the Lebanese International School when he
was captured Sept. 9, 1986.
   Mrs. Dagin's comments were reported by Agence France-Presse one
day after Kauffmann and two other Frenchmen arrived in Paris
following their release in Lebanon.
   Kauffmann and the other Frenchmen, diplomats Marcel Carton and
Marcel Fontaine, were released from Val-de-Grace military hospital
Friday after receiving medical examinations.
   Kauffmann, in his own interview Friday with the French news
agency, said the remaining Western hostages in Lebanon were ``my
main concern. I ask their families to remain patient and stay
confident.'' He was also quoted as saying he read the novel ``War
and Peace'' 21 times during his captivity.
   In a separate statement issued after the dispatch quoting his
sister, Kauffmann said he intended to comment more about the other
hostages next week and did not want anyone relaying his impressions
until then.
   A woman who answered Mrs. Dagin's telephone in Rennes on Friday
said she was out of town and could not be reached.
   Mrs. Dagin was quoted by AFP as saying Kauffmann told her the
American hostages held by the pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem group
Islamic Jihad were ``the object of brutality because they tried to
escape.''
   There are 18 foreigners missing in Lebanon, including nine
Americans. The hostage held longest is Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was captured
March 16, 1985.
   The AFP dispatch did not make clear if Kauffmann specified which
hostages were mistreated for attempting to get away.
   French officials, meanwhile, defended the circumstances under
which the hostages were released. Premier Jacques Chirac condemned
those who ``try to insinuate'' that France made a deal with Iran.
   ``I say solemnly, I say on my honor, that no negotiation, no
compromise, no bargaining, no deal took place with any foreign
government, or even less with any terrorist group,'' he said.
   Agence France-Presse, citing unidentified sources it said were
close to French negotiators, said France and Iran agreed to resume
formal diplomatic relations under a 40-day schedule beginning the
day the hostages were freed.
   France also has confirmed reports that one-third of a $1 billion
loan Iran made to France in 1974 has been paid. Other reports have
said the remainder is to be paid in return for freeing Kauffmann,
Carton and Fontaine.
   The widow of French hostage Michel Seurat said Friday she wanted
an official inquiry into her husband's death. Seurat was kidnapped
with Kauffmann in May 1985 and died in captivity.
   Mary Seurat said Chirac also should demand Seurat's body be
returned to France.
   ``I want his remains so I can bury them, in a country where even
dogs can have gravestones,'' she said.
   In her interview, Mrs. Dagin was quoted as saying that she
learned from her brother that Fontaine was briefly held with Terry
Waite, the special envoy of the archbishop of Canterbury. Waite
disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, while on a mission in Lebanon seeking
the hostages' release.
   She said her brother ``found no excuse for his kidnappers, for
whom he feels only hate.''
   The agency quoted her as saying Kauffmann considered using a
private signal to his son Gregoire _ wiggling his nose _ to
indicate he was lying when making videotapes under coercion in
which he appealed to the French government to do more to win his
freedom.
   He decided not to make the sign ``because he feared the
consequences if it were discovered,'' she quoted im as saying.
   Kauffmann was quoted as saying some of his captors treated him
humanely, but one ``never let up with the humiliations, not to
mention a simulated execution in June 1987 that was particularly
trying.''
   ``When I felt discouraged, I prayed and the next day some little
signs would let me climb back up again,'' he said.
</TEXT>
