<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Elections     05-06 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Elections,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialists Hail Advances As Proof Thatcher Has Gone Too Far</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The socialist Labor Party hailed its strong
showing in municipal elections Friday as a national rejection of
Conservative Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's right-wing program
and its shake-up of the welfare system.
   ``There's a sea change in British politics _ there's a direct
rejection of what the Tories are doing,'' Labor leader Neil Kinnock
declared, surrounded by jubilant party workers.
   Labor overtook the Conservatives, but the Tories tightened their
hold in the prosperous south. The two major parties captured
control of seven councils each where no party previously had
overall control.
   ``Very encouraging, very encouraging. We got many councils,''
Mrs. Thatcher told reporters outside her 10 Downing St. office.
   The major loser was the centrist Social and Liberal Democratic
Party, which lost support to the two big parties as it paid for
internal fueding that followed Mrs. Thatcher's third successive
victory last June.
   It was formed in March to merge the centrist Liberal Party and
Social Democratic Party, but a breakaway faction remained as a
separate party.
   With results in from all 211 local authorities contested, Labor
gained 104 seats, for a total of 1,898, the British domestic news
agency Press Association calculated. The Conservatives had a net
gain of five seats, for 1,135. The centrists lost 75 to end up with
365 seats.
   David Steel, the centrist party's co-leader, acknowledged, ``It
is bad, not good.''
   ``But it was not a disaster considering the appalling year it
has been for us ... I am relieved considering our internal
difficulties,'' he added.
   The Conservatives now control 48 of the contested cities and
towns, compared with 41 previously; Labor has 93, up from 91, and
centrists retained six. The Scottish Nationalists control one
district, while the rest belong to independents or have no party
with overall control.
   Labor retained control of major prizes, including Birmingham,
Britain's second largest city, and the Scottish capital, Edinburgh.
   But Labor lost control of Bradford, a key northern industrial
city, where no party now has an overall majority.
   No elections were held this year in London and Northern Ireland.
   The local elections were fought on national issues as Mrs.
Thatcher presses on with sweeping changes in welfare and education
and a controversial new property tax.
   The Conservative leader, having tamed labor unions and curbed
inflation since winning power in 1979, sees the changes as part of
her drive to bury socialism in Britain, increase personal
responsibility and end the ``dependency culture'' of the welfare
state.
   Critics, including some uneasy Tory rank-and-file legislators,
have criticized the changes for bearing unfairly on the poor.
   Environment Secretary Nicholas Ridley said the results were a
``remarkable achievement'' for a government pushing through major
changes.
   ``It has been a pretty difficult patch ... We are holding up,''
he said.
   The Conservatives, who lost all but 10 of the 72 Scottish
parliamentary seats in last June's election, again failed to dent
the deep-rooted hostility to the Thatcher administration north of
the border.
   Unofficial estimates by the British New Agency show an average
voter turnout of about 40 percent. The figure is normal for
municipal elections, which always register lower turnouts than
general elections.
   The Scottish National Party reported the turnout in Scotland's
53 districts was 48 percent, compared with 44 percent four years
ago when these seats were last contested.
</TEXT>
