<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0654,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians, Shiites Battle in Beirut; 28 Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with new casualties, dvpts, detail</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BE12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian factions battled for control
of Beirut's refugee camps Friday and rival Shiite Moslem militias
fought each other in the slums around them. Police said 28 people
were killed and 90 wounded.
   Ambulances raced through the streets of Moslem west Beirut. The
American University Hospital said its emergency wards were filled.
   Police said 16 people were killed and 50 wounded in the Shiite
slums, where the fight was between the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or
Party of God, and the mainstream Amal militia allied with Syria.
   The Lebanese Red Cross said its volunteers took at least 23
wounded from the slums to hospitals in west Beirut, which is
policed by the Syrian army.
   ``Dozens of other bleeding fighters lay on the streets,'' a Red
Cross official said. ``We could not help them because of the
intensity of sniping.''
   Twelve combatants were killed and 40 wounded in the Chatilla and
Bourj el-Barajneh refugee camps, police reported. The struggle
there involves PLO chief Yasser Arafat's Fatah guerrillas and Saeed
Mousa's Syrian-backed group Fatah-Uprising.
   Both intramural wars began before dawn and continued into the
night despite repeated calls for cease-fires. Mortar, rocket and
small-arms fire could be heard through the city.
   The Amal-Hezbollah confrontation began with the overnight ambush
of an Amal patrol in which four Amal militamen were killed,
including three brothers from the prominent Nassereddin clan. They
were included in the overall casualty count.
   Police said gunfire raked their jeep. Amal blamed Hezbollah, and
Amal militiamen went into the streets to hunt down Hezbollah
members.
   Fighting spread through several areas of the southern slums,
including the Hezbollah strongholds Bir el-Abed and Hay Madi and
the densly populated Ghobeiri and Haret Hreik districts.
   It was the heaviest fighting among Shiites since a four-day Amal
crackdown on Hezbollah in south Lebanon last month in which 62
people were killed and 150 wounded.
   Hezbollah is Iran's main ally in Lebanon and is believed to be
an umbrella for extremist factions holding most of the 18 foreign
hostages in the country.
   Amal's action against Hezbollah suggests that Syria wants to
crush Iran's challenge to its role as the main power broker in
Lebanon, where 25,000 Syrian soldiers are stationed.
   Syria backs Iran in the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war but has been
angered by Iranian efforts to dominate the 1.2 million Lebanese
Shiites, the largest sect in a nation torn by 13 years of civil war.
   About 7,500 Syrian troopers have policed west Beirut for more
than a year, but have not entered the Shite slums.
   They did not intervene in the Amal-Hezbollah collision but
surrounded Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh and were seen firing
heavy machine guns into the two Palestinian shantytowns.
   ``We are seeking to warn them to stop their stray fire against
our positions,'' a Syrian officer told reporters near Chatilla's
entrance. ``We're not intervening.''
   Another said: ``We are neutral. Syria is against any
inter-Palestinian fighting. We want the PLO to get reunited.''
   Palestinian antagonists pounded each other's positions in the
dusty camp alleys with 82mm and 60mm mortars, 106mm recoilless guns
and rocket-propelled grenades, police said.
   Each side accused the other of starting the fighting.
   In Baghdad, Iraq, an official of Arafat's Fata, the main
fighting force of the Palestine Liberation Organization, had asked
Syria to intervene with Fatah-Uprising to stop the battle.
   Police said Arafat loyalists controlled the eastern sector of
Chatilla and Fatah-Uprising dominated the western half near the
Syrians.
   Heavy sniping on the camp's only clear road made it difficult
for Chatilla's 3,000 residents to flee amd few tried.
   ``I don't know why they are doing this to us,'' a Palestinian
woman said at her home near the eastern entrance. ``We can't take
it any more. I already lost my husband in the camps war. I don't
want to lose my four children.''
   More than 1,600 people were killed and 3,600 wounded in a
three-year battle between the PLO and Amal that ended after the
Syrians intervened in April 1987.
</TEXT>
