<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Bridges,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actor Describes Trip To Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sight of people on the verge of starvation
in Ethiopia was nearly enough to make tough-guy actor Lloyd Bridges
cry.
   ``This one particular mother had a baby in her arms. She just
lost her husband,'' Bridges said Friday of his trip last month to
food distribution centers in Ethiopia.
   ``There were personal things like that ... that were hard to
accept, that a human being would have to go through such agony to
keep herself together,'' said Bridges, who starred in television's
``Sea Hunt.''
   ``It's hard to keep from bursting into tears. When you're a
parent yourself it's hard to take,'' he said. ``I certainly felt
like crying. I didn't actually weep. I'm still weeping internally.''
   Bridges was in Ethiopia shooting footage for commercials and
public service announcements for CARE, a relief agency. Dramatic
television footage in 1984-85 produced an international response to
massive starvation in Ethiopia.
   CARE spokesman George Wirt said that nearly 3 million are on the
verge of starvation in the same areas now: ``It seems to be coming
back.''
