<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     05-06 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments Delayed Until Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge agreed Friday to delay
closing arguments in the cocaine-smuggling trial of reputed
Colombian drug lord Carlos Lehder Rivas until Tuesday.
   U.S. District Judge Howell W. Melton granted the one-day delay
after defense attorneys sought a two-day postponement to make up
for time lost due to the illness of attorney Edward R. Shohat.
   U.S. Attorney Robert W. Merkle is to give his closing statement
Tuesday. Shohat will close for the defense on Wednesday and Stephen
Weinbaum, who represents co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, will
finish Wednesday afternoon or Thurday morning. Merkle also has
asked for three hours of rebuttal.
   The jury would get the case Friday, Melton said.
   The judge and attorneys met Friday to iron out jury instructions
and last-minute details to prepare for the closing of the trial. A
similar meeting is scheduled Monday.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise. Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged only with being a member of the smuggling conspiracy.
   Lehder, 38,is accused in the Jacksonville case of smuggling 3.3
tons of cocaine into the United States from his private island of
Norman's Cay in the Bahamas.
   Lehder also is also charged in separate indictments in Los
Angeles and Miami. The Miami indictment accuses Lehder of being one
of the leaders of the so-called Medellin Cartel, believed to be
responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine smuggled into United
States.
