<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Asylum     05-06 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Asylum,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romanian Violinists Granted Tentative Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Romanian sisters who are studying the violin
have apparently won their case for political asylum in the United
States, but they've been working too hard to celebrate.
   Rodica and Mihaela Oancea, students at Rice University's
Shepherd School of Music, said they received the news as the
semester ended.
   ``It came when we are so busy with school, so we haven't
celebrated too much,'' Mihaela, 18, said Thursday.
   The sisters arrived last July with tourist visas, planning to
visit Sergiu Luca, a Romanian concert violinist who teaches at
Rice, and defect.
   INS spokesman Mike McMahon said the two have received tentative
approval, but must be interviewed for a final determination. Their
attorney, Gordon Quan, said the sisters will soon be able to file
for permanent residency.
   Their father, Nicolae, a mechanical engineer, was known for his
anti-communist stance, the sisters said, and Romanian police
sometimes conducted random searches at their home.
   The women hope their father and mother, Elena, a high-school
chemistry teacher, can also come to the United States.
   Mihaela wants to continue her studies at Rice, while Rodica, 21,
will get her degree in another year and audition for a symphony
seat.
</TEXT>
