<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ValetParking     05-06 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Valet Parking,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Practical Pampering: Valet Parking Comes to Downtown Cedar Rapids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SPEER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the black Audi GT rolls to a stop,
a valet in a red vest and black bow tie opens the door, gives a
cheery ``Hello'' and zips the car away to park it for the driver.
   Is this a pricey restaurant? A swank hotel?
   No. Downtown Cedar Rapids.
   This eastern Iowa city with a population of 110,000 is giving
valet parking a three-month trial run in its congested downtown to
encourage people to shop and conduct other business there.
   ``No matter what it seemed like we did for downtown development,
we still had that one major pitfall _ parking,'' Mayor Don Canney
said.
   ``You think of valet parking at posh restaurants or at hotels
where parking is not highly visible,'' said Canney. ``In this case,
it's a service geared to eliminate the hassle of parking ramps or
meters.''
   In its first four days, the service parked 128 cars, from
Cadillacs to Yugos.
   The city-run service employs eight valets and two cashiers, and
is offered from 30 minutes before downtown stores open until 30
minutes after they close, Monday through Saturday. Four hours'
parking costs $2.
   Some motorists found it perplexing.
   ``How does this work?'' Chris Sterner, of Marion, asked an
attendant Friday. ``Will you give me enough time to get my stroller
out of the car?''
   Attendant Ira Hatter even offered to help.
   Mrs. Sterner used the valet parking as she took her 5-week-old
son Joey downtown to show him off to co-workers.
   ``When I'm not on maternity leave, I park downtown every day,''
she said. ``Let somebody else deal with it today.''
   Parking cashier Chris Elliott said the service was believed to
be only the second in the country for downtown shoppers. The other
is in Anaheim, Calif., he said.
   ``I think that generally, people still like to be pampered,''
Elliott said.
</TEXT>
