<DOCNO> AP880506-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Polio     05-06 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polio,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WHO Says Only Half Of World's Children Are Immunized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Health Organization said Friday only
half the world's children are immunized against polio and 275,000
children are still being stricken with the disease in developing
countries each year.
   Dr. Halfdan Mahler, outgoing director-general of the WHO, called
for a campaign to eradicate the disease worldwide by the year 2000.
   The WHO, the World Bank, the U.S. Agency for International
Development and other relief agencies already spend $150 million a
year to immunize children against polio and five other major
childhood diseases, measles, diptheria, whooping cough, tetanus and
tuberculosis.
   The WHO estimated that the agencies would have to raise that
budget to $500 million to achieve the goal of wiping out polio,
just as smallpox was eradicated a decade ago.
   In addition to the efforts by international agencies, individual
countries are spending $350 million annually to immunize their
children. That effort, too, needs to be stepped up, according to a
report from the Geneva-based health organization.
   Polio, which terrorized U.S. families in the 1950s before
development of vaccines, is now rare in developed countries. There
was only one reported case in the United States in 1986, and the
WHO said transmission of the polio virus is expected to be
eradicated from the Western Hemisphere by 1990.
   The disease attacks the central nervous system in severe cases
and causes paralysis; one in 10 people paralyzed by the infection
dies. In its mild form, polio is characterized by headaches, sore
throat and fever.
   Ten million people in the world today are lame from bouts with
polio, the WHO said.
   It said the countries with the most reported cases of the
disease in 1986 were: India 14,600 cases; Afghanistan 1,843;
Vietnam 1,600; China 1,537; Bangladesh 810; Brazil 665; Yemen 579;
Philippines 533 and Laos 523.
   The WHO believes only 1 in 10 cases worldwide is reported to its
Geneva headquarters.
   The organization said it costs $10 to immunize a child against
polio and other major diseases. The costs may be higher, however,
to reach children in remote parts of the world, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
