<2ND_LINE>AM-Officer Shot,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dallas Cop Shot With Own Gun; Suspect in Custody</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer was shot in the face with his own
gun Friday during a struggle with a burglary suspect outside a pawn
shop, officials said.
   Steven L'Huillier, 28, a six-year veteran and 1983 rookie of the
year, was in serious but stable condition after surgery at
Methodist Medical Center, spokeswoman Brenda Vrana said.
   Police said L'Huillier was shot in the cheek with his
.45-caliber gun and the bullet lodged in his jaw.
   A 20-year-old man arrested near the scene was being questioned,
although no charges have been filed, police spokesman Ed Spencer
said.
   Police said the suspect is a parolee released from the state
prison in March after serving 18 months on a five-year sentence for
theft. Spencer said the man faces charges of attempted capital
murder and burglary.
   The incident began when L'Huillier and his partner responded to
a burglary call early Friday at Weldon's Pawn Shop.
   The two officers split up and walked to different sides of the
building.
   Investigator Hollis Edwards said L'Huillier surprised a suspect.
``He struggled with the suspect, and the suspect gained access to
his weapon,'' Edwards said.
   A shot was fired, and his partner found L'Huillier kneeling on
the ground, wounded. Police said the suspect fled with the
revolver, which was recovered later from the back of pickup truck
near the scene.
   Police searching on foot and with helicopters later captured a
man matching the description given them by L'Huillier. The man had
blood on his clothes and he emerged from between two houses near
the shooting scene.
   The suspect told police that he was in the neighborhood looking
for lawns to mow.
   The suspect is black and the officer white, but Spencer said
race was not a factor in the shooting, the 11th this year involving
a Dallas officer. Three officers have been slain.
   The January fatal shooting of Officer John Glenn Chase sparked
tensions between the mostly white police force and the minority
community when then-police Chief Billy Prince blasted black elected
officials, saying their criticisms of the department helped foster
a climate of hatred of police.
