<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ConsumerCredit     05-06 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Consumer Credit,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Borrowing Shows Strong Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $4.46 billion more in
installment credit than they paid off in March, the fourth
consecutive strong monthly increase, the government said Friday in
a report that provided more evidence or strong consumer spending.
   The March gain in consumer debt was down from a $5.04 billion
increase in February, but still represented an annual rate of gain
of 8.6 percent, the Federal Reserve said.
   For the first three months of the year, consumer borrowing
increased at a 10.3 percent annual rate, compared with 7.2 percent
all of last year.
   However, analysts said rising interest rates and weak wage
increases likely would slow consumer borrowing in the months ahead.
   Sandra Shaber, an economist with the Futures Group, a Washington
forecasting firm, attributed the growth to strong pre-Easter
spending in March and to relatively high level of auto sales.
   The credit report said car loans increased $3.21 billion in
March, a 14.1 percent annual growth rate, compared with a 14.5
percent rate in February.
   The category which includes credit card debt grew $2.22 billion,
a strong 16.3 percent growth rate, which followed a gain at a 10.3
percent rate in February.
   The growth was offset by declines in borrowing to purchase
mobile homes and in the category including loans from banks and
credit unions not secured by real estate.
   Non-real estate loans fell by $796 million, a drop at a 5.4
percent annual rate, after rising at a 3.4 percent rate in February
and a 6.0 percent rate in January.
   Ms. Shaber said the evidence of strong consumer spending in
March, coupled with a drop in the civilian unemployment rate in
April to 5.4 percent, the lowest since 1974, may increase fears
that inflation will heat up.
   However, she said she expected growth in consumer spending to
slow in the months ahead because salary and wage increases have
been weak.
   ``My feeling is people will overstate what this means. ... Car
sales weakened a bit in April and department store sales were
terrible,'' she said.
   ``Consumer credit is not going to be growing in the months ahead
as it did in the first quarter. ... A lot people are working, but
on a per-worker basis, wages and salaries are not keeping up with
inflation.''
   She said consumer spending, which accounts for about two-thirds
of the nation's economy, would likely grow by 2 percent this year,
similar to the 1.9 percent growth last year, but only about half of
the growth rate earlier in the expansion.
   Analysts say rising interest rates, by boosting the cost of
credit purchases, are likely to dampen spending.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said Friday that fixed-rate
mortgages rose in the current week to 10.32 percent, up from 10.28
percent a week earlier.
</TEXT>
