<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Quake     05-06 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Quake,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Damages Some Houses But No Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake shook southern Nicaragua
Friday, damaging buildings and sending frightened residents rushing
into the streets. No injuries were reported.
   Alejandro Rodriguez, director of the government's Institute of
Land Studies, said a local seismograph registered the quake at 8:46
a.m. (10:46 a.m. EDT) and the tremor had a magnitude of 5.9 on the
Richter scale.
   He said the quake was centered near San Rafael del Sur, 15 miles
south of Managua, and there was no cause for alarm. Radio
broadcasts called on the public to remain calm.
   Managua was devastated by an earthquake in December 1972 that
killed at least 10,000 people. The city has not been completely
rebuilt and the shells of abandoned concrete buildings remain in
what was once the downtown area.
   Friday's quake was felt in northern Costa Rica, but officials
there said they had no reports of damages or injuries.
   Workers and residents in Managua returned to their daily
routines within minutes after the quake. Some said they had not
noticed any tremors.
   Radio Sandino reported some buildings were damaged in Rivas, 70
miles south of Managua. Landslides were reported in southern
Nicaragua near the Asososca lagoon, which provides a significant
part of Managua's drinking water.
   Earthquakes are common in Nicaragua. On April 21 a quake
registering 4.8 on the Richter scale rattled sections of the
country but caused no damage.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of energy released by an earthquake
as measured by ground motion recorded on seismographs. Every
increase of one number means the ground motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage in
populated areas and one registering 6 is capable of causing severe
damage.
</TEXT>
