<HEAD>Rebels Kill Two Policemen; 26 People Slain in 3 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers shot to death a police
captain and a retired sergeant in front of their homes Friday,
bringing the number of people killed in a three-day spasm of
violence to at least 26.
   Police said they believed the killers of Capt. Teofilo Tan, a
deputy station commander, and retired Sgt. Feliciano Belandrez were
members of the Alex Boncayao Brigade, the Manila unit of communist
guerrillas who have been fighting the government for 20 years.
   The brigade has been blamed for the killings of more than 100
policemen and soldiers in daylight ambushes in Manila and its
suburbs since early 1987.
   Military officials said communist rebels of the New People's
Army also killed a neighborhood leader and two soldiers in separate
ambushes Friday on the outskirts of Legaspi City, 215 miles
southeast of Manila.
   They said a fourth man was found dead at a school there, but
police did not know who killed him. Human rights groups in Legaspi
said the victim was a known leftist and they believed he was killed
by anti-communist vigilantes.
   Officials say at least 20 people have been slain since Wednesday
in clashes between soldiers and rebels.
   A senator quoted President Corazon Aquino as saying Friday she
did not want members of Ferdinand E. Marcos' immediate family to
attend the funeral of the exiled former president's mother because
they might be assassinated.
   Marcos, his wife and three children fled to Hawaii in February
1986 after a civilian-military uprising drove him from the office
he had held for 20 years and put Mrs. Aquino in power. Her
government has banned the Marcos' from the country.
   On Wednesday, after Josefa Edralin-Marcos died at age 95, Mrs.
Aquino said she would not allow Marcos to return for the funeral,
citing national security considerations.
   Asked by reporters Thursday if she would allow Marcos' son
Ferdinand Jr. to attend the funeral, the president said she had
received no such request and would respond only if one was made.
   Sen. John Osmena told reporters Friday: ``The president
expressed concern that security might be imperilled, and it could
be possible that enemies of the government will make attempts (on
the life of Marcos' son) so as to embarrass the government.''
   Osmena said Mrs. Aquino made the remark ``in passing'' during a
ceremony at the presidential palace. He said Mrs. Aquino scoffed at
suggestions that the body be flown to Hawaii so Marcos can pay his
respects.
   Ramon Mitra, speaker of the House of Representatives, said Mrs.
Aquino asked him if he thought Ferdinand Marcos Jr. should be
permitted to visit and he advised against it.
   ``I don't think any member of the Marcos family should be
allowed here,'' he said. ``It would only cause trouble.''
   A brother and sister of the former president said they hope Mrs.
Aquino will change her mind and have not set a funeral date.
