   Four other killings also were reported overnight in Punjab
state. The slayings raised to 900 the number of deaths blamed on
Sikh extremists this year.
   The lower house of Parliament voted Friday to extend federal
rule in Punjab for another six months. The upper house was expected
to approve the action.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi dismissed the Sikh-dominated state
government on May 11, 1987, for failing to curb the Sikh
separatists. Since then, the federal government has directed
security and day-to-day operations in the state. The federal rule
was due to expire Tuesday.
