<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-China     05-06 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-China,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pravda Praises Chinese Economic Innovations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pravda heaped praise on one of China's 14 open
economic zones Friday and suggested that the Soviet Union needs a
rebirth of working spirit to bring similar prosperity.
   The authors of the article on China's Tianjin region did not
draw direct lessons from it, but recited the accomplishments in the
open zones and said the success of ``Chinese perestroika'' was due
to an inspired work force.
   Perestroika is the name Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev gives
his plans for economic and social reform in the Soviet Union.
   Gorbachev has referred to the Chinese economic experiments
favorably but the article in the Communist Party newspaper was the
most complimentary to date about developments in the neighboring
communist country.
   Soviet supporters of perestroika, which means restructuring,
have encouraged broader use of joint ventures to attract foreign
investment.
   Many problems face foreign business executives in the Soviet
Union, however, including low worker productivity, unreliable
delivery of supplies, poor storage and transportation facilities,
and poor hotels and living accommodations.
   The fact that the ruble is non-convertible, not traded on world
currency markets, complicates joint ventures and has reduced the
number the Soviets have been able to negotiate.
   China's 14 open economic zones contain only 8 percent of the
nation's 1 billion people but account for more than one-quarter of
industrial production and 40 percent of exports, Pravda said. The
paper noted that they were established only four years ago.
   Its report was the second this week praising China's economic
policies. In the government newspaper Izvestia on Tuesday, writer
Chingiz Aitmatov criticized Soviet agriculture and pointed to a
Chinese move away from large collectives toward family farming.
   Pravda raised the question whether ``Chinese perestroika'' had
succeeded at the expense of workers and answered that it had not.
Pay in the open zones averages 50 percent more than for similar
jobs in other parts of the country, the newspaper said, but greater
productivity makes labor costs lower.
   China's special economic zones have attracted foreign capital
and joint ventures because the Chinese built the necessary support
facilities, Pravda said.
   In the Tianjin region, buildings ``literally pop up like a
mirage in the desert,'' it said, and developers built luxury
hotels, a golf course, sports clubs and other services that make
Western business executives feel comfortable while in the area to
oversee their enterprises.
   Transport problems were worked out ahead of time to ensure
enough shipping capacity and a lenient tax system has drawn more
foreign investment each year, the newspaper said.
   Pravda said the Tianjin region alone had 80 contracts for joint
ventures and more than $100 million was invested there in 1987.
</TEXT>
