<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Abortion     05-06 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Abortion,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Banning Late Abortions Fails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hisses and cheers rose from the gallery of the
House of Commons on Friday after a bill that would have restricted
the right to abortion was defeated by delay tactics.
   The measure would have been the first change in the law since
Britain legalized abortion in 1967. It would have barred abortions
after the 17th week of pregnancy instead of the 28th week, as the
current law allows.
   Conservative John Wakeham, the House leader, rejected a final
appeal for the government to provide extra time to secure passage
of the bill.
   During a heated debate, a spectator was ejected from the gallery
after shouting an expletive at a legislator who argued against
passage.
   Conservative Sir Bernard Braine denounced what he called ``the
scandal of late abortions for social or convenience reasons.''
   ``I'm talking about the right of life of the unborn,'' he said.
``We should remember that the unborn child marked down for abortion
has no choice at all.''
   Jo Richardson, a prominent feminist member of the opposition
Labor Party, accused supporters of taking an ``absolutist and
fundamentalist'' view of abortion.
   ``They are willing to barter with women's bodies and gamble with
children's lives to try to maximize support for this bill and
inflict a substantial blow on the 1967 act, which has given women
and doctors 20 years of safe, legal abortions,'' she said.
   Procedural wrangling left no time for a vote on whether the bill
should proceed to a final debate and vote in the House of Commons.
   Britain, by allowing abortions at up to 28 weeks, or about seven
months, of pregnancy, has one of the Western world's most liberal
abortion laws. In the United States, abortions are allowed without
regulation in the first three months of pregnancy.
   After that, some state regulation is allowed.
   Supporters of the new law argued that abortions should not be
allowed when a fetus might have a reasonable chance to survive
outside the womb. At 24 weeks, such survival is rare, but survival
at 28 weeks is estimated at 74 percent in optimal conditions. The
usual length of pregnancy is 40 weeks.
   Of the 172,286 abortions in England and Wales in 1986 _ the
latest year for which statistics are available _ 10,770, or 6
percent, were done after 17 weeks, according to the Department of
Health and Social Security.
   Opponents of the bill contended that an 18-week limit would deny
women the choice of abortion because of a fetal handicap, since it
might not be possible to detect the handicap at such an early stage
of pregnancy.
   Fourteen previous attempts to amend the 1967 Abortion Act have
failed, but Parliament's anti-abortion lobby had gained widespread,
bipartisan support for the latest bill.
   In January, the Commons approved the bill by a majority of 296
to 251 at a crucial parliamentary stage, leading to speculation
that it might be approved, albeit in a watered-down form.
   The medical profession and the government of Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher had supported a four-week reduction in the time
limit, to 24 weeks. By withholding government support for an
18-week cutoff, Mrs. Thatcher had significantly lowered its chances
of passage but left open the possibility of a compromise.
   The bill's sponsor, David Alton of the Social and Liberal
Democratic Party, has said he would mount another attempt to
tighten the abortion law if his bill failed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
