<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Kauffmann     05-06 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Kauffmann,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Hostage Says Jailers Were Unstable</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-Iranian Moslems holding foreigners hostage in
Lebanon often degraded their captives and ``took everything away
from us, even our first names,'' a freed French hostage was quoted
as saying Friday.
   Jean-Paul Kauffmann, one of three French hostages released
Thursday, said one jailer carried out a terrifying mock execution.
   ``As everywhere else, I imagine, some of our jailers were very
human, but in a very hard context,'' Kauffmann was quoted as saying
by Agence France-Presse.
   ``There was an Abu Hassan who didn't speak a word of French but
who was attentive, obliging, always in a good humor, which was not
the case with many of his fellows, very unstable, sometimes
perverse. Most of them were not able to maintain a constant
attitude. The best alternated with the worst for reasons that
escaped us.''
   Another of his guards, whom Kauffmann identified as Abu Ali, was
particularly cruel.
   ``He left us in filth, because for him we were impure,'' said
Kauffmann, a reporter for the weekly Evenement du Jeudi who was
abducted May 22, 1985. ``He continued to humiliate us, not to
mention a mock execution in June 1987 which was particularly
frightening.''
   The first year, and above all the first weeks, were the most
difficult, Kauffmann was quoted as saying, ``because it took some
time for me to become accustomed to being a prisoner.
   ``They tried to degrade us. They took everything away from us,
even our first names.'' He said the kidnappers gave each of the
three French hostages a new name _ Habib for Marcel Carton, Najib
for Marcel Fontaine, and Labib for Kauffmann.
   The journalist said he was moved 18 times in his nearly three
years of captivity. His worst memory, apart from the death of
fellow French hostage Michel Seurat, was in the beginning of 1987
when the Syrians entered West Beirut.
   He said he was bound with cloth strips like a mummy and placed
in a sort of coffin under the bed of a truck.
   ``Before leaving, we had to swear to be silent each time the
vehicle stopped or we would be executed,'' Kauffmann was quoted as
telling AFP.
   After each move, the hostages had to renegotiate even the
smallest privileges, he was quoted as saying.
   ``The smallest change had a considerable affect on our existence
and our morale. A cup of coffee was a real festival.''
</TEXT>
