<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     05-06 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Race Not Over, Talks to Teens About Gangs, Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>By RITA BEAMISH</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson declared Friday that
``California has the power to determine the next nominee of our
party'' and urged voters to ignore those who say the Democratic
race is locked up.
   ``California, here we are,'' he told a sun-soaked rally at Santa
Monica Community College.
   Earlier, in a dramatic speech to a high school rally, Jackson
spoke against gang violence, stating, ``I challenge you because I
love you, because I care, because I'm not scared of you.''
   ``When I become president, I'm going to break it up,'' he said
of the gang warfare.
   Referring to a rash of gang killings in the Los Angeles area,
Jackson said, ``You who are so precious, who are so dear, are
living beneath your privilege.''
   Some of the 3,000 Fremont High School youths in the athletic
field bleachers were wearing gang colors.
   Starting his campaign day at a labor breakfast, Jackson said the
race is still tight despite the wide delegate lead enjoyed by his
rival, Michael Dukakis.
   Speaking in a state with substantial dependence on military
contracts, Jackson also proposed non-military development of space
as a way to recover defense industry jobs that would be lost under
his proposed military budget freeze.
   He declined to give specifics when asked by reporters how many
jobs could be created in space development or how much spending he
proposed.
   With Dukakis holding nearly a 600-delegate lead, Jackson also
continued to call for party officials to ensure a ``reasonable
correlation'' between the primary popular vote, which stands at 37
percent to 28 percent against him, and the delegate count. There
are 314 delegates at stake in California's primary on June 7.
   ``This race is a close race, but it's about directions,'' he
told more than 400 unionists at a Los Angeles County Federation of
Labor breakfast.
   ``The press, the pundits, the party, the candidate _ it's not
just me and him; it's me and them,'' he said.
   After the speech, Jackson told reporters he does not consider
his call for fairness ``at all divisive.''
   But he said the party establishment ``super delegates'' should
wait until after the primary season ends before committing to a
candidate so they can help offset any imbalances in places where
the delegate count is not directly proportional to the popular vote.
   On another subject, he was asked by reporters what he sees as
Dukakis' weaknesses in the battle for Calfornia's delegates.
Jackson referred to what he said were state budget problems in
Massachusetts and said Dukakis as governor was cutting programs for
pregnant teens and for elderly people to make up revenue.
   Voters should consider, he said, ``As we look toward 1989, on
whose backs will we balance the budget?''
   The most dramatic event of Jackson's campaign day came after his
speech at Fremont High School in San Pedro. About 300 students came
down from the bleachers, admitted they used drugs and said they
would try not to any more.
   `If you've tried drugs and you want to get well, come on down,''
he said. ``Let them through the gate, our children want to get
well,'' Jackson told security officers at the fence separating his
stage from the bleachers.
   He had the teen-agers raise their hands and repeat the words,
``I can be and will be a better person.''
   Afterward, Stanley Chaney, 18, who said he had tried drugs once,
said, ``It was an experience for everybody.''
   ``It helped a lot. It makes you realize you're not by
yourself,'' said Gina Brooks, 17, who said she drank alcohol but
was not a drug user.
   One boy, who disavowed drug use, said he came down on the field
``because I just wanted to see him.''
</TEXT>
