<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GrowthHormones     05-06 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Growth Hormones,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leukemia Risk Not Great Enough to Ban Growth Hormone Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children who receive hormones to help them
grow may face a slightly higher risk of developing leukemia, but
the increased risk _ even if proven _ is not great enough to
warrant withholding treatment, scientists said Friday.
   Cancer and growth experts from several countries met this week
to review 15 cases of leukemia worldwide in patients treated with
synthetic growth hormones. The meetings were prompted by reports of
leukemia in five Japanese children who had received the treatment.
   ``There is no therapy that is risk-free,'' said a statement by
the Lawson Wilkins Pediatric Endocrine Society, which represents
doctors and scientists working in the field. ``Because GH therapy
is essential for optimal growth and development in GH deficient
children, it would be inappropriate and unwise to withhold such
treatment from needy patients.''
   The group said it has not been proven that there is an increased
risk and patients can be told that if there is one, it is small.
   The incidence of leukemia among patients taking growth hormone
worldwide is estimated at 1 in 21,000 patient-years of treatment,
the society said, while a reasonable estimate of the risk among
nonpatients in the same age range is 1 in 42,000.
   Among the 15 cases examined, four were deemed not to have been
caused by the treatment because they either occurred within two or
three months of treatment or there were compelling reasons to
suspect other causes, the group said.
   The society said that if there is a relationship between growth
hormone treatment and leukemia the cause could be the effect of the
hormone on bone marrow cells, a contaminant in hormone
preparations, or the combined effect of the hormone and genetic or
environmental factors in certain patients.
   The Human Growth Foundation, which is supported by 1,000
families with children having growth disorders, participated in the
meetings that examined the cases. Experts came from the United
States, Canada, Japan, Australia and several European countries.
   The foundation had no figures immediately available on the
number of children currently receiving treatment.
   Manufacturers of growth hormones estimate that about 2 million
U.S. children are in the lowest 2 percentile by height, meaning
they are shorter than 98 percent of children their age.
</TEXT>
