<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-NATO     05-06 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-NATO,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Assures West German on U.S. Support in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan assured a concerned West
German official Friday that U.S. commitment to Bonn and the NATO
alliance remains unshaken, the White House said.
   Reagan also told Dr. Alfred Dregger that ``U.S.-German
cooperation is the cornerstone of the NATO alliance,'' presidential
spokesman Roman Popadiuk said.
   Dregger is chairman of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's majority faction
in the Bundestag (parliament). He said he was satisfied and
relieved by assurances from Reagan and other U.S. leaders that
nuclear disarmament will not be allowed to break the strategic
unity of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Urging the United States and the West to seize the intiative as
soon as possible in negotiating with the Soviet Union a reduction
of non-nuclear weapons in Europe, Dregger also told Reagan that
Bonn would cooperate fully in maintaining NATO's strategy of
flexible response, Popadiuk said.
   Reagan told the West German that U.S. ``commitment to Germany
and Western Europe is unshakeable,'' Popadiuk said.
   ``I am very satisfied with my sessions in Washington and I am
convinced that the alliance will guarantee the security of the
(German) Federal Republic and Europe for (another) 40 years,''
Dregger told reporters afterward.
   Dregger said Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and arms
control adviser Paul Nitze had confirmed to him ``that we will
continue to have unbroken unity of deterrence and risk-sharing
between North America and Europe, that the entire alliance will
remain a strategic unity.''
   Dregger said he also confirmed in his talks that sea-launched
cruise missiles and airborne nuclear weapons of medium range would
remain after the dismantling of land-based intermediate systems
under the treaty signed by Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev at the Washington summit last December.
   ``Therefore we will still have medium-range missiles which
constitute a link between the strategic systems and the short-range
systems in Europe,'' Dregger said.
   The Bundestag defense expert said in a Thursday speech his
Christian-Democratic party would go along with plans for
modernizing short-range tactical nuclear weapons ``so long as
risk-sharing and deterrence sharing with respect to
intermediate-range weapons is maintained.'' This is because
``denuclearization of Europe would give full effect to the Soviet
Union's huge conventional and chemical superiority,'' he said.
   The Pentagon agreed with this but reacted sharply to Dregger's
statement that Germans want to pursue the question of ``whether
nuclear artillery is necessary and expedient.'' Dresser said this
should be covered in a comprehensive review of nuclear strategy for
disarmament ordered at the last NATO summit.
   When the issue of short-range nuclear weapons, those with ranges
of less than 300 miles, was raised with Reagan, the president said
their reduction would be discussed only after East-West balance is
achieved in conventional, non-atomic weapons, Popadiuk said.
   Dregger said the purpose of nuclear artillery ``can only be a
limited one'' such as ``to prevent the concentration of
conventional assault forces, especially tank armies.'' It should
not be relied on for a deterrent, he said, because the range is too
short to target eastward to Soviet territory, he said.
   But the Pentagon said Friday that ``modern nuclear artillery
rounds are an integral element'' of the minimum-level credible
nuclear deterrent posture approved in NATO's 1983 decision at
Montebello, Canada, and revalidated last month by the alliance's
defense ministers.
   ``Their elimination would have a number of adverse effects on
NATO flexible response strategy,'' the Pentagon said, starting with
reducing Soviet uncertainty as to ``when, where and how NATO would
respond to an attack.''
   Dregger said the greater the range of a modernized version of
the Lance missile, with a current range of 70 miles, the less will
be the need for nuclear artillery rounds. But the Pentagon declared
that ``both a follow-on to Lance and continued modernization of
nuclear artillery are necessary'' to keep NATO's nuclear deterrent
up to date.
</TEXT>
