<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSDrug     05-06 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Drug,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Used to Treat AIDS Patients to be Studied as Pre-Infection
Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The maker of the AIDS drug Retrovir, citing
studies that the drug shows promise as a preventive treatment in
animal experiments, is launching a study to find out if the drug
can prevent infection in health workers exposed to the AIDS virus.
   ``There is some previous work in animal models of retroviral
infection which indicates that administration of Retrovir, if begun
within a few days of viral exposure and continued for only a few
weeks, may prevent the establishment of retroviral infection or
significantly alter disease progression,'' said Dr. Sandra
Nusinoff-Lehrman, associate head of the infectious diseases
department at Burroughs Wellcome.
   This is the first study by Burroughs Wellcome, the only
pharmaceutical company that makes Retrovir, to determine the drug's
ability to prevent HIV infection, company spokeswoman Kathy
Bartlett said Thursday.
   Retrovir, formerly known as AZT, is the only drug that has
received federal approval as an effective treatment against the
human immunodeficiency virus. There is currently no therapy proved
to prevent infection upon exposure to the AIDS virus.
   Health care workers who treat patients with AIDS and
accidentally come in direct contact with blood products infected
with HIV will be given Retrovir shortly after the exposure, Ms.
Bartlett said.
   Burroughs Wellcome will examine how well patients tolerate the
drug. Ms. Bartlett said the same dose recommended for treatment of
AIDS patients will be administered to health care workers.
   Retrovir has been found to cause nausea, insomnia, muscle pains
and bone marrow suppression in HIV-infected patients taking the
drug. The relatively brief period of Retrovir therapy is likely to
produce few significant side effects in healthy individuals, Dr.
Lehrman said.
   Company officials said it is too early to determine whether the
drug could be used to prevent infection among individuals in
high-risk groups who think they have been exposed to the virus.
   The major cause of transmission in the health care industry is
accidentally puncturing the skin with a needle or other sharp
instrument contaminated with infected blood, said Dr. Wayne
Thomann, director of Environmental Safety and Hospital Epidemiology
at Duke University Medical Center.
   Contact with the HIV virus doesn't necessarily mean a person
will become infected, however. Studies show the chance of a health
care worker being infected with the AIDS virus is 1 in 200, Ms.
Bartlett said.
</TEXT>
