<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BigPay     05-06 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Big Pay,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chamber Head Says Executive Raises Should Inspire the
Rank-and-File</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new head of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce
said Friday hefty pay raises for corporate executives should
inspire rank-and-file workers to be ambitious rather than envious.
   William S. Kanaga, the 1988-1989 chairman of the board of
directors of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, was asked by reporters
at a luncheon what he thought of the fact that management salaries
have been increasing at a faster rate than the pay of lower-ranking
workers.
   He replied that he was reminded of a story told by Walt Frazier,
a former star for the New York Knicks basketball team.
   ``Frazier was asked, `What are you doing for the black race?'.
... He replied, `I drive my Rolls Royce through Harlem every Sunday
and if that won't motivate them, I don't know what will,''' Kanaga
said.
   Asked if it was healthy for executives, figuratively speaking,
to flaunt their Rolls Royces in front of workers, he said, ``One of
the beauties of the free enterprise system we have is if a fellow
wants to go down a certain avenue, he can make a lot of money.''
   He said Frazier's Rolls Royce ``may have driven some fellows
back to the basketball courts up there.''
   Kanaga, who is chairman of the advisory board of Arthur Young &
Co,. an accounting firm, was asked if he believed athletics were
the only route out of the ghetto for young blacks.
   ``I'm not suggesting it is the only one, no. There are others,''
he replied, mentioning education.
   The value of incentives, he said, is illustrated by the supply
of taxicabs in Beijing before and after economic reforms in China.
Before the reforms, taxis were nearly impossible to find at dinner
time because drivers were paid a flat monthly salary. Now that the
drivers get to keep a part of the fare, cabs are plentiful, he said.
   Kanaga also said that higher managerial salary hikes when a
company succeeds must be balanced against the possibility that they
will be out of the job if their company's fortunes take a downturn.
   He said Chrysler Corp. workers are probably delighted, even
though they earned far less than Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca,
because of Iacocca's leadership in saving the company.
</TEXT>
