<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0785 05-06 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0785,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 3d graf to read `prostrate.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the latest developments involving France:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PARIS _ The presidential campaign wrapped up Friday with
Socialist incumbent Francois Mitterrand and his conservative
challenger, Premier Jacques Chirac, both making appearances in
southern France. Mitterrand was favored to win the runoff Sunday,
but Chirac, who runs the government's day-to-day affairs, may
benefit from the release of three French hostages in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PARIS _ A leading Socialist Party official said Chirac arranged
for the hostage release to boost his campaign, but the premier
denied the allegations.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PARIS _ One of the freed hostages was quoted Friday as saying
Americans held in Lebanon were brutally mistreated after trying to
escape. Agence France-Presse quoted Marie-Genevieve Dagin, sister
of freed hostage Jean-Paul Kauffman, as saying American Frank
Herbert Reed was ``mistreated to the point of being prostrate.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NOUMEA, New Caledonia _ Thousands of security personnel were on
alert in the French South Pacific territory of New Caledonia.
Melanesian separatists there said they will avenge the deaths of 19
kidnappers slain when security forces rescued 23 French lawmen
Thursday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PARIS _ A French secret agent convicted in the 1985 sinking of a
Greenpeace ship off New Zealand was released from exile Friday
because she is pregnant, French officials said. France allowed
Capt. Dominique Prieur to leave exile on a South Pacific island
five months after the other agent convicted in the bombing was
returned to Paris. Both are seen as heroes in France.
</TEXT>
