<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SkyscraperFire     05-06 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skyscraper Fire,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Discounts Arson Rumors While Officials Call for Tougher Fire
Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that gutted four stories of
California's tallest skyscraper, killing one person and injuring
40, could have been prevented if City Council had done its duty 14
years ago, a lawmaker charged Friday.
   Meanwhile, First Interstate Bancorp officials discounted
speculation of arson prompted by fears of impending layoffs. City
fire officials had yet to determine the cause of the blaze at the
62-story First Interstate Bank tower.
   Councilman Nate Holden introduced a motion Friday to require all
high-rises to install sprinkler systems. A similar law that took
effect in 1974 did not apply to structures built before then. The
bank was built in 1973.
   Workers were installing a sprinkler system in the 859-foot
skyscraper when the fire _ the worst high-rise blaze in Los Angeles
history _ erupted late Wednesday.
   ``If you had done your duty in 1974, we wouldn't be here
today,'' charged Holden, who was elected last year.
   The motion was given little discussion because it was not on the
agenda. It was put on Tuesday's agenda.
   City officials said as many as two-thirds of the city's 765
skyscrapers lack sprinklers that could prevent fire catastophes.
   A First Interstate spokesman discounted arson speculation
prompted by news that the company's capital markets group was sold
in a deal that closed Wednesday night. The group employs 100 people
on the floor where the fire apparently broke out.
   Spokesman John Popovich said the sale was consummated after the
close of business and kept secret from workers until Thursday
morning, after the fire. Further, the bank had announced its
intention to sell the group, which buys and sells government bonds,
in October.
   ``I firmly believe that at this stage it's random chance,''
Popovich said of the timing of the sale and fire. ``If the idea is
that there is a disgruntled employee, that would have been six
months ago.''
   Printon, Kane & Co. of Short Hills, N.J., which bought the group
for $40 million, plans no layoffs or moves, said Robert Grimmig,
managing partner of the firm.
   The blaze that gutted the 12th through 15th stories and damaged
part of the 16th floor of the skyscraper, causing $450 million in
damage. A maintenance engineer was killed and 40 people were
injured.
   Agents from the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
were also investigating.
   Consumer services, including checking, savings and automatic
teller machines in the 19 states where First Interstate does
business continued except at the tower branch.
   Securities trading and electronic funds transfers from other
institutions continued smoothly, largely because the bank had
recently developed an emergency plan for use in an earthquake,
Popovich said.
</TEXT>
