<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0774 05-06 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0774,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Convoys Sailing Parallel Courses Toward Hormuz</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore missing copy.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and British convoys sailed
parallel courses down the Persian Gulf on Friday, with helicopters
scouting ahead for mines.
   Observers who saw the two convoys 30 miles off Dubai at midday
said the British group was made up of five tankers escorted by the
Royal Navy's 4,100-ton destroyer Gloucester.
   Associated Press photographer Greg English said the American
guided-missile frigate Jack Williams was escorting the U.S.-flag
79,999-ton Kuwaiti products tankers Chesapeake City and Ocean City
and had picked up a ``hitchhiker,'' the Liberian-flagged tanker
Neston.
   Other ships often follow those protected by warships through the
Strait of Hormuz, the narrow gateway to the gulf where Iranian
gunboats often attack unescorted ships. A total of about 500 ships
have been attacked by Iran and Iraq since the countries went to war
in September 1980.
   The U.S. convoy was the 29th of this year and the fourth in a
week. The convoys were disrupted last month by a confrontation
April 18 between U.S. and Iranian forces, in which two Iranian oil
platforms and six naval craft were destroyed or damaged.
   Gulf-based shipping executives and Pentagon officials in
Washington, all speaking on condition they not be named, reported
earlier that Iran's fleet of armed speedboats was increasing in
size and activity around the Hormuz naval base at Bandar Abbas, but
the reason was not known.
   Iran has said it will avenge its losses and Adm. William J.
Crowe Jr., chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, said during
a visit to the region that the threat could not be dimissed.
   Officers on the 3,700-ton Jack Williams were said to be more
concerned about mines than the reports of armed speedboats. The
Williams played a key role in the U.S.-Iran clash and was one of
three U.S. ships that came under Iranian missile fire near Hormuz.
   ``It could be anything. Who knows what they're up to?'' one
officer said, according to a report filed from the ship by a
Pentagon news media pool.
   Lookouts posted on the frigate's bow scanned the waters with
binoculars, looking for ``floaters,'' as the helicopters searched
farther ahead. Submerged mines sometimes can be seen from the air.
   Last month, the Jack Williams passed unscathed through an area
of the central gulf less than a day before its sister frigate
Samuel B. Roberts sailed into a field of newly laid mines and hit
one. Ten crewmen were wounded.
   Friday's convoy was the first to negotiate the 110-mile Hormuz
passage since Washington announced a new policy that allows U.S.
warships to intervene in Iranian attacks on commercial ships
bearing other flags.
   The policy applies to any ship in international waters and not
carrying war-related cargo for Iraq or Iran. Previously, U.S.
warships could defend only vessels flying the American flag.
   Since the U.S. Navy began escorting reflagged Kuwaiti tankers
last July, none of the 51 convoys has been molested by Iran's
surface raiders.
   Iran condemned the new U.S. policy as ``aggression'' and
promised to continue raids on shipping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
