<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1928EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PlantBlast     05-06 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Blast,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Damage Over $100 Million, Residents Nervous About Plant Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Damage estimates topped $100 million
Friday from explosions that demolished a rocket fuel plant, while
city officials tried to calm residents by meeting with a
neighboring company making the same product.
   ``We've created a monster of fear,'' said City Councilman
Michael Harris. ``I don't think anybody other than maybe some of
those that really knew the plants knew the potential hazard
inside.''
   Union officers, meanwhile, huddled to review safety records of
Pacific Engineering and Production Co., where a 1982 union letter
wondered why the plant hadn't already been ``blown off the face of
the earth.''
   Jim Barnes, state industrial relations director, said Pacific
underwent 11 inspections by the state Occupational Safety and
Health Division over the last five years.
   The inspections resulted in 10 citations as well as four fines
for incidents Barnes termed serious.
   ``There have been problems from time to time, mostly minor,'' he
said. ``Our opinion is that overall there record has been a good,
moderate record.''
   Executives of Kerr-McGee Corp., which manufactures the same
ammonium perchlorate a mile from the earthquake-force blast that
leveled Pacific, met with city officials amid calls from frightened
residents to shut the second plant down.
   ``It's too early to say we're going to run Kerr-McGee out of
town,'' said Harris. ``We have to wait and find out what caused
this. It may create a tremendous war out here.''
   Kerr-McGee voluntarily shut down Thursday.
   ``We will not resume until we're absolutely certain it's safe,''
said Kerr-McGee spokesman Paul Reed. ``But we've been operating 35
years without any sort of accident. We think our plant safety
record is exemplary.''
   Two Pacific executives were killed and 326 people were treated
at hospitals for injuries in Wednesday's blast, which threw houses
off their foundations and severely damaged buildings throughout the
city 10 miles southeast of Las Vegas.
   Six people remained hospitalized, including a 5-day-old child
cut over the eye by flying glass in a hospital nursery.
   Nearly a third of the city's 16,000 homeowners filed damage
claims by Friday. City Manager Gary Bloomquist said initial damage
estimates topped $100 million.
   ``The number of claims already has really startled me,'' said
Bloomquist. ``But things are going real well. Practically
everything is running again and people are ordering new windows and
garage doors.''
   President Reagan was asked on Thursday to declare a disaster
area to qualify the city for federal grants.
   John Molovich, a United Steelworkers union safety and health
expert, flew to Henderson from Pittsburgh to meet with local union
officials. ``The reports we're getting is they've had problems with
fires of late,'' said Molovich.
   Molovich wrote a 1982 letter that questioned plant safety after
he took a tour. In the letter, he wrote of fears of an explosion
because of the chemicals used at the plant.
   ``The company moved on some of the items,'' Molovich said
Friday. ``I'm not saying they didn't do anything. But they moved on
the minor things, some of the major things were just not being
done.''
   This city of about 55,000 grew up around an industrial complex
that began during World War II with a plant that produced titanium
for warplanes. Growth here has been sharp in recent years, making
it the third-largest city in Nevada.
   Although Pacific has vowed to rebuild the plant within six
months, Bloomquist said it had better be someplace else.
   ``We don't have a facility big enough here to hold all the
protesters if they try and rebuild there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
