<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese-INSLAW     05-06 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-INSLAW,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Says No Further Review of Meese Allegations Is
Warranted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has found that no
further review is warranted of allegations against Attorney General
Edwin Meese III involving the bankruptcy of a computer software
firm doing business with the department, a spokesman said Friday.
   The department said in a letter that allegations by INSLAW
Inc.'s president, William Hamilton, provided no basis for an
independent counsel to look into the charges. The letter was sent
to Charles Work, Hamilton's attorney.
   The criminal division's acting chief, John Keeney, has
concluded, ``There's no need for an independent counsel to
investigate this matter,'' said Justice Department spokesman Terry
Eastland.
   Meese is not under investigation by any section of the
department with regard to the INSLAW matter, said a department
source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Among Hamilton's allegations was that Meese interceded to have
the company's former attorney, Leigh Ratiner, dismissed from the
Washington law firm of Dickstein, Shapiro & Morin. Hamilton
contends in court papers that Ratiner was asked to leave shortly
after Meese discussed the INSLAW case with one of his politically
connected law partners, Leonard Garment.
   Garment called the allegation involving Meese ``pure baloney''
but said he was questioned about the allegation two months ago by
the Justice Department's public integrity section.
   Hamilton said he had not yet seen the letter, adding that public
integrity investigators never interviewed him, his wife Nancy, nor
Ratiner.
   ``We are surprised they reached a conclusion without talking to
either the complaining witnesses or one of the victims,'' Hamilton
said.
   Under the 1978 Ethics in Government Act, allegations must be
deemed to be specific and credible in order for a matter to be
referred to an independent counsel.
   Meese has been under criminal investigation since last May 11 by
independent counsel James C. McKay on other matters. McKay's office
had referred the INSLAW allegations about Meese to the Justice
Department's public integrity section to determine if they required
further investigation. If they had merited such further
investigation, the allegations would have been returned to the
independent counsel.
   INSLAW won a $6.8 million judgment against the Justice
Department from a federal bankruptcy judge who ruled that officials
used ``trickery, fraud and deceit'' to steal software the company
had developed under a $10 million government contract. The Justice
Department is appealing the ruling.
   The department's public integrity section is conducting an
investigation of possible perjury by government officials who
testified last year at a U.S. Bankruptcy Court proceeding involving
INSLAW, according to sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The perjury investigation stems from a ruling last year by U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge George F. Bason Jr. that there had been an attempt
by Justice Department officials in 1985 to force INSLAW into
liquidation of its assets, which would have put the firm out of
business.
   The judge expressed disbelief in testimony given by two former
bankruptcy trustees and Thomas J. Stanton, head of the department's
Executive Office of U.S. Trustees.
   Stanton denied that he tried to pressure the trustees to convert
INSLAW's Chapter 11 reorganization into a Chapter 7 liquidation.
Bason found Stanton's testimony ``utterly incredible and unworthy
of belief.''
   The judge also refused to believe the recantation of deposition
testimony by former U.S. trustee Cornelius Blackshear, that Stanton
had asked him to help liquidate INSLAW.
   Blackshear, now a federal bankruptcy judge in New York City,
signed an affidavit recanting the sworn statements a day after he
gave the deposition in his chambers. He said he had confused the
INSLAW case with another bankruptcy matter.
   The Senate Permanent Investigations Subcommittee, however, has
decided to conduct a full investigation of INSLAW's charges that it
was the victim of a vendetta by Justice Department officials to put
it out of business.
   The panel's chairman, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., decided last week to
conduct the investigation based on information compiled in a
preliminary inquiry, according to congressional sources, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Bason ruled last year that the Justice Department vendetta was
spearheaded by an official who administered INSLAW's contract. The
judge found that C. Madison Brewer was ``consumed by hatred and an
intense desire for revenge'' because he had been fired by INSLAW
before going to work at the Justice Department.
   Stanton agreed to help Brewer liquidate INSLAW to ``curry
favor'' with higher Justice Department officials, whose support he
needed to preserve the trustee's office, Bason said.

</TEXT>
