<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-Uruguay     05-06 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Uruguay,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Muted Welcome Expected For Pope In Uruguay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The yellow and white papal banners
that welcomed John Paul II last year were largely absent Friday on
the eve of the pope's second visit to South America's smallest
republic.
   And there were far fewer posters of the pontiff taped to
storefronts and home windows than before the March 1987 visit.
   ``His first visit here was cause for celebration. It brought out
those curious to see the pope, but this time nobody's quite as
excited. Perhaps the novelty is gone,'' taxi driver Arturo Branco
said.
   ``It's probably a bigger deal in the interior than it is in
Montevideo,'' said storekeeper Sara Beisso.
   The pope is scheduled to arrive Saturday at 5 p.m. (4 p.m. EDT)
in Uruguay's capital to begin a 12-day visit that includes stops in
Bolivia, Peru and Paraguay. It will be the pontiff's first trip to
landlocked Bolivia and Paraguay.
   During his South American visit last year, the pope met with
Chilean President Gen. Augusto Pinochet and caught a whiff of tear
gas during a clash between anti-Pinochet demonstrators and police
during an outdoor Mass.
   Among those the pontiff will meet during this trip are
Paraguayan President Alfredo Stroessner, a general in power since
1954, and Uruguay's president, Julio Sanguinetti, an agnostic.
   Uruguay, a country of 3 million, is considered the most
secularized nation in Latin America apart from Cuba. Uruguay has
permitted divorce and enforced separation of church and state since
1917.
   Church leaders say 80 percent of Uruguayans are Roman Catholic,
but studies indicate only 4 percent of Montevideo residents
regularly attend church. Montevideo accounts for almost half of
Uruguay's population.
   Regardless, 82,000 people are expected to hear the pope speak
Saturday night at Centenary Stadium shortly after his arrival at
Carrasco International Airport. He is scheduled to visit Catholic
University and spend the night at the Vatican envoy's residence.
   On Sunday morning, the pope is to fly to Melo, 250 miles
northeast near the Brazilian border. Authorities say up to 30,000
Brazilians are expected to cross the border to see him.
   He also is scheduled to have lunch with bishops from the
Uruguayan Episcopal Conference on Sunday and say Mass in Florida,
90 miles north of the capital.
   On Monday, the pope meets in the morning with President
Sanguinetti, then flies to the northwestern city of Salto, where
authorities expect up to 50,000 Argentines to cross the frontier to
hear him say Mass.
   The pope later leaves for Bolivia for a 5-day visit.
   The pontiff will spend a day and a half in Lima, Peru, which he
also visited in 1985, then fly to Asuncion, Paraguay, on May 16.
The pope will celebrate his 68th birthday on May 18 in Paraguay,
then leave that night for Rome.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
