<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Germany-HelicopterCrash 2ndLd-Writethru   05-06 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Helicopter Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0663,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Military Helicopter Hits Ramp At Air Show; Two Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with at least seven injured,
details. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British air force helicopter
taxiing during an air show burst into flames after one of its
rotors struck a loading ramp Friday. Two crewmen were killed and at
least seven people were seriously injured, officials said.
   Officials said ``numerous others'' suffered minor injuries from
flying debris in the accident at the Hanover Airport.
   A statement by the British Army of the Rhine said, ``We can
confirm that a Chinook Royal Air Force helicopter from Guetersloh
(air base) had a ground taxiing accident at Hanover Airport.'' It
said there were five British military personnel aboard the
U.S.-made Chinook helicopter and three survived but were injured.
   The Guetersloh base is 65 miles southwest of Hanover.
   Hanover Airport fire officials said at least four people near
the ramp were seriously injured.
   The ZDF television network said late Friday that at least 10
people were seriously injured, but it did not give attribution for
its account.
   ``It was like a bad dream, like a bomb went off,'' said Caren
Niewisch, 27, of Los Angeles, who had been watching the air show.
``People fell and tried to get away,'' she said. With her was
Marcus Fontaine, also of Los Angeles, who said he is a pilot.
   ``It wasn't the pilot's fault,'' Fontaine said. ``The man on the
ground (directing the helicopter) underestimated the radius of the
rotor blades in the turn.'' Neither Californian was injured.
   A British soldier who was guiding the helicopter to its parking
position with hand signals was among those seriously injured, the
Royal Air Force statement said.
   The twin-rotor helicopter flipped over onto one side before
bursting into flames. There were several explosions and flames shot
more than 25 feet into the air.
   British military officials said a board of inquiry was set up to
investigte the cause.
   Initial reports had said the helicopter belonged to the U.S.
military, but airport officials later said it was a U.S.-made
helicopter flown by the British military.
   The accident occurred at about 6 p.m. (12 noon EDT) shortly
after the air show's activities for the day had ended, officials
said.
   Witnesses said crowds of people were milling about the aircraft
exhibits at the time.
   It took fire crews more than 30 minutes to extinguish the fire.
   More than 420 exhibitors from 16 countries are participating in
the air show, which opened Wednesday.
</TEXT>
