<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AbandonedChild     05-06 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abandoned Child,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Of Frost-Bitten Child Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Same first name for mother and daughter is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CROWN POINT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose 9-year-old daughter lost
her lower legs to frostbite after being trapped for days in an
unheated apartment pleaded guilty Friday to felony child neglect.
   Darlwin Britt, who has been held in the Lake County Jail since
her arrest Jan. 20, agreed to plead guilty to one count after
prosecutors said they would drop two other felony counts of child
neglect.
   Under the plea agreement, Ms. Britt, 25, would be sentenced to
14 years in prison. But Lake County Superior Court Judge Richard
Maroc said he has the option of suspending part of that sentence,
and will make a decision at a May 27 hearing.
   Ms. Britt took the stand only briefly during the 40-minute
hearing. She admitted that her daughter, Darlwin Carlisle, needed
medical attention, yet she did not seek it.
   Off the stand, Ms. Britt told Maroc that she was taking cocaine
during the time in January that young Darlwin was forced to live in
the unheated attic apartment. Otherwise, she gave no explanation
for the incident.
   Ms. Britt showed no emotion at the hearing, and Maroc did not
admonish her.
   The spunky youngster, described as a good student by her
teachers and ``very courageous'' by hospital personnel, now lives
with her great-grandmother in Gary. After her ordeal was publicized
nationwide, at least $125,000 poured in to help pay her medical
bills and future expenses.
   Darlwin has learned to skip rope and roller skate on her
artificial legs, therapists said at the time she was released from
a Chicago hospital.
   The little girl was found in a freezing apartment in Gary on
Jan. 18 by a construction worker who had been sent to board up the
building after a mortgage foreclosure.
   At the time, Jeff Griffin said he heard a child pleading for
help, removed a refrigerator from the top of the stairway and
kicked open a padlocked door to rescue the girl.
   Prosecutors said she had been without food or water for three to
five days.
   Doctors at Chicago's Wyler Children's Hospital said her lower
legs could not be saved. Darlwin was fitted with artificial legs at
La Rabida Children's Hospital, also in Chicago, where she also
received therapy.
   The Rev. Cozetta Olive of First AME Church in Gary said she read
about Ms. Britt's arrest in January and has visited her weekly at
the county jail.
   ``She is very refreshed but despondent,'' Olive said outside the
courtroom. ``She loves her daughter and that needs to be
understood. She's just happy the child is alive. She believes God
has answered her prayers, but she knows that she has done wrong.''
   Lake County Prosecutor Jack Crawford said young Darlwin has not
visited her mother, adding, ``interestingly, she has not indicated
that she wants to.''
   ``It's a strange case,'' Crawford said. ``Ms. Britt would come
back to the apartment and visit her daughter but not spend the
night. Instead she was hanging out on the streets.''
   Crawford said electricity, heat and water had been turned off at
the building late last summer.
   Olive said Ms. Britt told her that she had left young Darlwin
unattended so she could go find money to buy food and water.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
