<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-06 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Storm Spins Off Snow, Rain, Hail and High Winds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An intensifying storm system moved through Wyoming on Friday,
spawning snow, thunderstorms, hail and high winds from Montana and
North Dakota into New Mexico.
   Snow fell in northern Nevada, where 9 inches had accumulated by
noon in Austin, 8 at Jackpot and 4 to 5 at Mountain City. A winter
storm watch was issued for Friday night and Saturday in the
mountains of central Montana.
   Heavy thunderstorms deluged western North Dakota and central
Nebraska. Alliance, Neb., received half-inch hail.
   Rain or snow, most of the West was buffeted by high winds. A
gust of 85 mph was clocked at the Arapahoe Baskin Ski Area in
Colorado. Just west of Colorado Springs, wind blew down a major
transmission line and cut off power to 9,000 utility customers.
Gusts of 63 mph were reported in Montrose and Gunnison, Colo.
   Rock Springs and Casper, Wyo., Milford, Utah, and Ruidoseo,
N.M., clocked gusts of more than 50 mph.
   The winds stirred up dust and limited visibility in eastern
North Dakota and northeastern South Dakota.
   Elsewhere, cool and rainy weather continued in the Middle
Atlantic states and southern New England. A flood warning was
issued for central and western Maryland, northern Virginia and
northeastern West Virginia.
   Temperatures were in the 80s along the Gulf Coast and across
much of Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Hailey, Idaho, and Elko, Nev., to 90 at Carlsbad, N.M.
The morning low for the nation was 20 at Truckee, Calif.
   Saturday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms
extending from Arkansas across the upper half of the Mississippi
Valley, the northern Plains, the northern Rockies and the
intermountain west to northern California and the Pacific
Northwest. Snow is predicted for the higher elevations from Montana
to Nevada.
   Highs should range in the 40s and 50s over the intermountain
west and the northern Rockies. Highs should hit the 80s from the
South Atlantic States across the Tennessee and lower Ohio Valleys
and the lower two-thirds of the Mississippi Valley to the Southern
Great Plains. Texas' Rio Grande region might get highs in the 90s,
with temperatures in the 60s and 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
