<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-06 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Regional Elections Postponed Until End of Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Provincial councils in the
Tamil-dominated Northern and Eastern provinces will not be elected
until the end of the officially declared emergency in the region,
the government said Friday.
   President Junius Jayewardene's government imposed emergency rule
in 1983 after separatists in the Tamil minority began a war against
the Sinhalese majority. More than 7,000 people have been killed in
the conflict.
   ``The nomination of candidates for the purposes of elections to
be held in the Northern and Eastern provinces shall not take place
so long as the provisions of the Public Security Ordinance are
effective,'' a government statement said.
   Elections for four of the nine provincial councils were held
last week and Jayewardene's United National Party won majorities.
The other three councils are to be elected next month.
   Provincial councils are part of an Indian-sponsored peace plan
designed to give greater autonomy to the provinces. The plan also
requires the rebels to surrender their arms in exchange for
participation in local government, but they rejected the plan and
violence has continued.
   India, which has a Tamil minority of 60 million, has sent more
than 50,000 soldiers to disarm the militants in this island off
India's southern coast.
   In Sri Lanka's Southern province, Sinhalese extremists have
sworn to kill supporters of the peace plan, which they say makes
too many concessions to Tamils.
   They also oppose the council elections and the underground
People's Liberation Front was blamed for the killings Wednesday of
three candidates.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese.
</TEXT>
