<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AutoTalks     05-06 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Talks,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler-UAW Settlement Goes to Local Union Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative contract covering 66,000
Chrysler Corp. employees in 15 states was approved by the United
Auto Workers' 140-member national Chrysler council Friday and goes
next to the rank and file.
   ``We believe it will be ratified overwhelmingly,'' said UAW Vice
President Marc Stepp, head of the union's Chrysler department.
   The two-year, job-protecting contract reached Wednesday would
replace a three-year pact that runs out Sept. 14. In 1990, all Big
Three contracts will expire together for the first time in a
decade, boosting the UAW's bargaining power.
   The Chrysler council approved the pact after a 5{-hour meeting.
A provision giving full Chrysler seniority to former American
Motors Corp. workers in 1990 was deleted by the council before it
gave its approval. GM acquired AMC last year.
   The contract, which also covers 65,000 retirees at the No. 3
automaker, will be presented to union members for ratification on
Wednesday.
   It is patterned on the contracts in place at Ford Motor Co. and
General Motors for the first time since 1979, when the UAW granted
Chrysler deep concessions to help rescue the automaker from near
bankruptcy.
   The contract prevents further plant closings and layoffs for any
reason other than slow sales, halves the attrition rate and
restricts the automaker's ability to transfer work to outside
suppliers or foreign countries.
   It also contains lump-sum bonuses equal to 3 percent of wages
each year and provides profit-sharing to Chrysler workers for the
first time.
   ``It should pass. The job security is there, that was the most
important issue,'' said Mike Allen, a union official with UAW Local
624 in Syracuse, N.Y.
   Stepp said the settlement and approval by the council had
brought to an end months of bitter conflict that led the two sides
to seek a solution by holding early contract talks. ``There's peace
in the valley,'' he said.
   Unlike the Ford and GM agreements, the Chrysler pact includes a
$1,000 signing bonus and prevents Chrysler from paying executives
cash or stock bonuses in years when the profit-sharing formula
generates no payout for workers.
   In addition, it covers 1,200 former AMC workers still on the job
in Wisconsin after a 5,500-worker AMC assembly plant in Kenosha,
Wis., closes at year's end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0216 </DOCNO>
