<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraDissidents     05-06 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Dissidents,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Dissidents Return to Miami After Expulsion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven dissident Contra field commanders detained
and expelled from Honduras arrived here Friday blaming their
military chief for their plight and pledging to seek total reform
of Nicaragua's rebel forces.
   The men were arrested without explanation in Honduras, held for
three days and put on a plane to Miami on Friday, they said here.
   The seven included military field commanders and top civilian
aides who had called for the removal of Contra military chief Col.
Enrique Bermudez.
   They have accused Bermudez of corruption and charged that he has
surrounded himself with supporters of deposed Nicaraguan dictator
Anastasio Somoza Debayle.
   One of the dissidents, Donald Lacayo, a legal adviser to the
rebel military, said the seven were expelled because they presented
Contra leaders with a petition demanding that Bermudez go.
   ``There is a total rejection of him by all the combatants,''
Lacayo said.
   The dissidents will go to the Contras' Miami headquarters next
week to demand a total restructuring of the rebel military, said
Lacayo.
   Field commander Walter Calderon Lopez, known as Cmdr. Tono, said
Bermudez was also trying to undermine the cease-fire agreement
signed March 23 in Sapoa, Nicaragua, by the Sandinistas and the
Contras.
   ``If Bermudez remains as head of the northern front, we will
never get back to Nicaragua,'' he said.
   The seven men said they had been well treated by the Hondurans
but were offered no explanation for their detention and expulsion.
Honduras has allowed the Contras to use the country as a staging
ground for attacks on the Sandinistas.
   Arriving with Lacayo and Tono were Enrique Sanchez; Orlando
Montealegre; Encarnacion Valdivia, who is known as Cmdr. Tigrillo;
Tirzo Roman Moreno, also known as Cmdr. Rigoberto, and Gustavo
Quezada.
</TEXT>
