<DOCNO> AP880506-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Newspapers     05-06 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspapers,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspapers Eye Minorities, Changing Lifestyles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers will survive and flourish if they
keep pace with the nation's changing lifestyles and growing
minority population, industry leaders said Friday.
   ``Doom-saying for newspapers is an old pastime, and it has been
booming in recent years,'' said Larry Jinks, senior vice president
for news and operations at Knight-Ridder Inc. ``We are, as an
industry, more clear-eyed about our problems and advantages, and
more determined to do what's necessary to flourish.''
   ``The future of newspapers is very bright, so long as we don't
take that future for granted,'' agreed Sam S. McKeel, chairman of
Philadelphia Newspapers Inc., which publishes The Philadelphia
Inquirer and the Philadelphia Daily News. Both are Knight-Ridder
papers.
   Jinks, McKeel and others spoke at a conference held by Columbia
University's Graduate School of Journalism, which is celebrating
its 75th anniversary.
   Jinks said during a panel discussion on the future of newspapers
that industry concerns include competition, illiteracy, a transient
population and a dwindling attention span among those ``raised in
front of the tube.''
   ``It's been the change in social patterns _ leisure time,
working women, changes in family structure _ that probably have
caused more changes in newspapers than technology has,'' added
Anthony J. Marro, editor and senior vice president of Newsday.
   Mark C. Miller, associate editor of the Berkshire Eagle in
Massachusetts, said afternoon papers are giving way to morning
editions because readers don't have time to sit down at the end of
the day.
   ``Most households have a couple of people who are earning their
living outside the home,'' he noted. ``We're competing with all
sorts of leisure time activities ... cable satellites, VCRs, people
jogging around with things stuck in their ears.''
   Dorothy Gilliam, a Washington Post columnist, cited figures
showing that minorities will account for 25 percent to 40 percent
of the population by the turn of the century.
   ``It seems to me what is too often missing in newspapers is the
authentic voice of the different groups that make up our society
today and that will increasingly comprise our society in the
future,'' she said.
   Jinks agreed, saying, ``You can't have a bunch of middle-aged,
white males sit around in a news conference and decide what to put
in tomorrow's newspaper and have a newspaper that's going to appeal
to the whole, general population.''
   More than half the nation's newspapers have all-white reporting
staffs, and non-whites account for only 5 percent of the
decision-makers at newspapers, Gilliam said.
   That shows the industry has fallen short the American Society of
Newspaper Editors goal of a minority representation that reflects
the population, she said.
   Marro said newspapers one day may stop offering stock tables,
sports agate, movie timetables or classified advertising _
information that might be obtained on home computers.
   That, he said, could leave more space for in-depth reporting _ a
trend he would welcome.
   ``I expect there'll be one. I suspect that most of them will
still land on a front porch with a thump _ but maybe not quite as
heavy a thump,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
