<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-France     05-06 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-France,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canada Suspends Fishing War Talks Over Trawler Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada suspended talks with France on their
fishing war Friday, the day after a Newfoundland trawler was
stopped at sea and taken to a port on the French-held islands of
St. Pierre and Miquelon.
   Foreign Secretary Joe Clark summoned French Ambassador Philippe
Husson and made a formal protest of what John Crosbie, minister of
international trade, described in Parliament as a ``provocation by
France.''
   In St. Pierre, charges of illegal fishing were filed against the
trawler Maritimer, and its five crewmen were released after the
Canadian government posted bail of $35,000 ($28,350 U.S.).
   Opposition parties demanded that Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's
Conservative government suspend negotiations with France for the
purchases of 10 nuclear-powered submarines and 34 European Airbus
jetliners.
   Clark said they wanted to start a ``casual trade war'' and
``there is no reason at this stage for us to contemplate that.''
   He called the trawler's interception by a French naval tug ``a
bizarre incident'' that could be resolved diplomatically.
   Mulroney, speaking to reporters in New Brunswick, promised
``vigorous action'' if the rights of Canadian citizens were
violated.
   French officials said the vessel was ``escorted into port,'' not
arrested, and the crew spent Thursday night at a hotel.
   In Newfoundland, provincial Premier Brian Peckford accused
France of infringing on Canadian sovereignty. His government
canceled a $729,000 (U.S.) offshore oil contract with a French
company and withdrew from a Paris food show scheduled for next fall.
   Clark said he had ordered talks suspended in the fishing
dispute. A Canadian negotiator had been scheduled to meet his
counterpart in Paris on Friday for discussions of fishing quotas in
the waters around St. Pierre and Miquelon, which are 10 miles south
of Newfoundland.
   Canada and France disagree over the international boundary of
the islands and quotas for cod and other fish in nearby waters.
France claims a 200-mile economic zone but Canada recognizes only a
12-mile limit around the islands.
   A French trawler, the Croix de Lorraine, was arrested last month
when it deliberately penetrated Canadian inshore waters to protest
fishing restrictions. All 21 men aboard, including four French
politicians, were jailed in St. John's, Newfoundland, until the
French government bailed them out.
</TEXT>
