<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Drugs     05-06 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Drugs,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seize 3,000 Pounds of Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and soldiers seized more than
3,000 pounds of cocaine in a raid on a big drug-processing
laboratory, the army announced Friday.
   More than 15,000 pounds of cocaine have been confiscated during
the past week in raids on 13 laboratories in a ranching and farming
area about 225 miles north of Bogota.
   Officials said the raids have been the biggest blow against drug
trafficking in Colombia since cocaine production became big
business in the 1970s.
   An army release said the latest raid was at a farm near the town
of Puerto Berrio on Thursday and that police found 3,080 pounds of
98 percent pure cocaine hidden among trees near the end of a paved
runway. Officials estimated the value of the cocaine would be about
$100 million in the United States even before it entered the street
market.
   The army statement by Gen. Raul Humberto Rojas said troops are
searching for 25 additional cocaine laboratories believed to be in
the same area north of the capital.
   It said police and troops also seized thousands of gallons of
ether and other chemicals needed to process coca base into cocaine.
   ``This is the biggest operation ever carried out against drug
trafficking in Colombia and we will continue it until we have wiped
out the scourge,'' Gen. Guillermo Medina Sanchez, the national
police commander, told a news conference Thursday.
</TEXT>
