<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     05-06 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels End Transportation Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels on Friday
announced an end to a ban on transportation that had drastically
curtailed traffic during the week.
   ``The national strike of transportation ends after three days of
guerrilla victories throughout the national territory,'' the rebels
said in a broadcast on their clandestine Radio Venceremos. ``From
the first hours of this Friday the national transportation strike
is suspended.''
   The armed forces' information office said guerrillas destroyed
six vehicles and damaged 11 during the action that began Tuesday.
It had no reports of injuries or deaths.
   It said the traffic ban had the most impact on eastern El
Salvador, where the guerrillas are most active, and in San
Salvador, the nation's capital and largest city.
   Public transportation employees estimated the ban affected about
90 percent of public transportation.
   The rebels ordered the ban because of what they claimed was an
increase in repression by police and the military.
   It was the third such ban declared this year by the rebels who
have been battling the U.S.-backed government for eight years.
   In the two previous actions this year four people were killed,
11 were wounded and 15 vehicles were burned or damaged by gunfire.
   The rebels said this week they would take the license plate
numbers of vehicles being operated during the ban and would take
retaliatory action.
</TEXT>
