<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Election     05-06 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Election,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Certifying Local Election Results Despite Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The government says it will certify
results of township elections held three months ago despite
protests from a group that is Haiti's most vocal defender of the
constitution.
   The Information Ministry said Thursday the results will be
binding when they are published in the official gazette, Le
Moniteur.
   It said everything was ready for publication after Prime
Minister Martial Celestin and Home Secretary Yves Auguste
accompanied Jean Gilbert to the office of a notary public Thursday
to authenticate Gilbert's copy of the results. Gilbert is past
president of the Provisional Electoral Council.
   Dr. Louis Roy of the Honor and Respect for the Constitution
Committee said: ``The Manigat government is taking us for idiots.''
   ``Officialization of the results will be one more illegal act of
his illegitimate regime,'' Roy said of President Leslie Manigat.
   He said the Provisional Electoral Council was dissolved Feb. 7
in conformity with the constitution and ``proclamation of the
results has come too late to be legally binding.''
   The original copy of the election results was said to have been
mislaid in the National Palace after the vote Jan. 31. Gilbert said
on television Thursday he sent copies to the relevant ministries
and the original to the president's office eight or 10 days after
the elections.
   The Honor and Respect for the Constitution Committee is an
association of Protestant and Roman Catholic Church leaders, human
rights groups, business people and private citizens formed to
defend the constitution approved in a referendum March 29, l987.
   A recent declaration by the committee listed 33 articles it said
had been violated, and Roy said ``this will be the 34th violation''
since Manigat took office Feb. 7.
   Two recent demonstrations against failure to publish results of
the township elections were dispersed without violence.
   Haiti has 567 township councils, which are the basis of
decentralized authority under the new constitution.
   Nine regional assemblies are composed of members from the
councils, which also are to provide the candidates for a permanent,
autonomous Electoral Council required by the constitution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
