<DOCNO> AP880506-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     05-06 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Clash With Police; Opposition Leader Demands Judicial
Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SEL3,4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police fired tear gas to disperse
about 1,000 students staging an anti-government protest Friday and
demonstrators responded with firebombs.
   The students from 10 schools in Seoul threw hundreds of
firebombs in sporadic clashes at Hanyang University.
   ``Topple the dictatorship controlled by Yankees,'' the students
shouted, referring to U.S. influence in their country.
   They also demanded that the government ensure North Korea's
participation in the Olympics, to be held in Seoul this summer.
Communist North Korea has demanded that it be made a co-host of the
Games in return for its participation.
   In another development, opposition leader Kim Dae-jung called
Friday for sweeping judicial reforms and charged that the courts
have been used as ``the maid of the government.''
   The opposition leader told a news conference that his Party for
Peace and Democracy will make changing the judiciary its highest
priority during the new National Assembly session.
   ``The fort of human rights has fallen down to the maid of the
government,'' Kim said.
   Kim, whose party emerged as the main opposition force after last
month's legislative elections, charged that many justices in the
Supreme Court ``have curried favors with suppression of human
rights.''
   Kim warned that the government would face ``serious troubles if
it wants to get the Parliament's approval by retaining judges who
have aided the government.''
   Following the governing Democratic Justice Party's loss of its
majority in the April 26 elections, President Roh Tae-woo said he
would work with the opposition to carry out democratic reforms.
</TEXT>
