<2ND_LINE>AM-Throat Slit,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assailant Killed After Slitting Boy's Throat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crazed man who slit the throat of a
6-year-old and refused to surrender when sheriff's deputies stormed
the apartment was shot to death Friday, still clutching the boy,
authorities said.
   The child, William Newby, died at Foothill Hospital shortly
after the 7 a.m. attack.
   The assailant, the live-in boyfriend of his mother, was
identified as Leonard W. Browne, 33. He died at University Medical
Center.
   The boy's mother, Glena Trammel, fled their North Point
apartment shortly before the attack and told neighbors Browne had
threatened to hurt the child.
   When deputies stormed the apartment, they found Browne lying on
his back on the kitchen floor, clutching the youngster across his
chest and holding a knife to his throat, said homicide Lt. Ray
Biondi of the Sacramento County Sheriff's Department.
   ``He was screaming like a wild man,'' Biondi said. ``He was
berserk.''
   ``The suspect was ... ripping at the throat at the child with
his hands, trying to rip the throat out of the child,'' said Lou
Blanas, a sheriff's spokesman.
   Biondi said Browne refused to let the boy go. A deputy fired a
shot into Browne's abdomen to force him to release the child, but
the shot ``only seemed to agitate him,'' Biondi said.
   A deputy then shot two more times into Browne's abdomen and ``he
went limp,'' the lieutenant said.
   Biondi said before the child was attacked there was a
disturbance in the bedroom where Browne and Trammel were. Browne
then grabbed the child, he said.
   Biondi said investigators discovered a cache of crack in the
apartment. Officers at the scene said Browne appeared to be under
the influence of drugs.
</TEXT>
