<HEAD>Japan Approves Entry Of North Korean Ping-Pong Team</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an easing of its sanctions against North Korea,
Japan will allow a North Korean ping-pong team to visit later this
month, the government said Friday.
   ``We concluded that the group's sole purpose (in visiting Japan)
is to participate in the Asian Table Tennis Championships and that
its lineup is bona fide,'' said Keizo Obuchi, the chief government
spokesman.
   Park Soo-gil, South Korea's assistant foreign minister, said in
Seoul on Friday that his government was studying the Japanese
decision.
   The North Korean team visiting for the May 15-22 tournament
includes two government sports officials.
   The sanctions were announced Jan. 26, after Tokyo blamed North
Korea for the disappearance of a South Korean passenger jet in
November.
   The measures restricted contact between Japanese and North
Korean diplomats and barred North Korean officials from visiting
Japan. The countries do not have diplomatic relations.
   Tokyo newspapers have reported that the Japanese government
wants to improve ties with the North and encourage it to
participate in the 1988 Olympic Games, scheduled to be held in
South Korea in September.
