<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     05-06 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slovenia Tells Deputies To Try To Unseat Federal Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Parliament of the republic of
Slovenia instructed its deputies in the federal Parliament on
Friday to try to unseat the Yugoslav government, the state news
agency Tanjug reported.
   The issue will be decided May 14-15 when a progress report on
the government of Premier Branko Mikulic will be discussed in the
Parliament.
   ``The Slovenian parliament is instructing its delegation in the
Council of Republics and Provinces of the Parliament of ...
Yugoslavia not to accept the report of the Federal Executive
Council (government) on its two-year work and at the same time
raise the issue of confidence in the federal government,'' Tanjug
said.
   If the six Yugoslav republics and two provinces withdraw their
support for the government through a vote of confidence in the
chamber, it would bring about the first resignation of a Communist
government in the country's history. The Yugoslav constitution,
which includes such a provision, made the country a federal
republic in 1946 under Marshal Josip Broz Tito, a Communist.
   Slovenia is Yugoslavia's most advanced constituent republic. It
has the highest standard of living and almost no unemployment,
although throughout the country more than 1 million of Yugoslavia's
23 million people are unemployed.
   Slovenia has repeatedly criticized the government's unsuccessful
attempts to solve Yugoslavia's economic problems and called for
radical changes in the single-party system.
   Yugoslavia has a 170 percent annual inflation rate and a $20
billion foreign debt.
   ``Although the government carried out numerous tasks, this has
not helped improve the economic situation of the country,'' Tanjug
quoted the Slovenian parliament as saying.
   ``As the source of a majority of laws and steps of economic
policy and its implementer, the Federal Executive Council
(government) is responsible.''
   The Slovenian parliament on Friday elected Janez Stanovnik,
executive secretary of the United Nations Economic Commission for
Europe, as president of the republic.
   He and other candidates for the pos had been given air time on
state-run Slovenian television to present their views on how the
crisis in Yugoslavia should be resolved, Tanjug said.
   A popular Belgrade TV commentator wryly observed that Stanovnik,
who receives a $2,000 monthly salary from the United Nations, will
be the first high-ranking Yugoslav official ``not to burden the
working class.''
</TEXT>
