^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the latest developments involving Poland's
labor unrest:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GDANSK, Poland _ Club-carrying police ringed the strikebound
Lenin shipyard Friday and a labor leader was sentenced to three
months in prison for organizing the illegal walkout. Workers inside
said they expected an assault and worried about food supplies.
After a striker tried to commit suicide, Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa gave an emotional speech that called for strikers to stick
to pay demands.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WARSAW _ The government proposed laws to punish organizers of
strikes and protests with up to one year's imprisonment. The draft
legislation also suspends the already limited right to strike by
officially recognized trade unions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   KRAKOW, Poland _ Workers at the Nowa Huta steel mill said a raid
by riot troops had not ended their strike although the state-run
radio said Friday work had resumed.
   Church-appointed mediators said they felt betrayed by the police
attack because an agreement had been within reach to end the
10-day-old strike.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WARSAW _ The Roman Catholic Church criticized the police raid at
Nowa Huta and said authorities apparently were planning similar
action against the shipyard workers in Gdansk.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MOSCOW _ Radio Moscow reported Friday that work resumed at the
Nowa Huta mill. The official Tass news agency said police broke up
the Nowa Huta strike Thursday without ``incidents.''
