<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Pope     05-06 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Pope,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peru Bans Meetings Prior to Papal Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday banned marches,
meetings and other large public gatherings in the capital before
and during a visit by Pope John Paul II.
   The order, published in the official gazette El Peruano, was
issued under a seldom-used clause in the 2-year-old
state-of-emergency decree. It takes effect Sunday.
   Security will be greatly increased during the Roman Catholic
pontiff's 40-hour stay in Lima to guard against violence by leftist
guerrillas, officials said.
   The Peru visit May 14-16 comes midway through the pope's
four-nation Latin America tour, which begins Saturday.
   While in Lima, the pope is scheduled to celebrate an open air
Mass, hold meetings with church, political and private groups and
close a conference of Latin American bishops.
   The Episcopal Conference of Peru, which is coordinating the
visit, said all of Lima's 50,000 police officers will be on duty
during the pope's stay.
   The conference said an undisclosed number of troops will also be
stationed around the city.
   Police declined Friday to comment on security plans.
   During the pope's only other visit to Peru, in February 1985,
Maoist Shining Path guerrillas caused a widespread power outage,
plunging Lima's airport into blackness as the pope's plane was
landing. The craft touched down safely.
   The Shining Path, Peru's largest and most violent guerrilla
band, has been fighting for eight years to topple the government
and install a worker-peasant state modeled on the China of Mao-Tse
Tung. The government says more than 10,000 people have died in the
fighting.
</TEXT>
