<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Fighting     05-06 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Fighting,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista Troops Say They Were Wounded by Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two soldiers said they and two other
troopers were shot and wounded by Nicaraguan rebels Thursday after
they tried to speak with the rebels. It was the second cease-fire
violation reported in two days.
   Forces of the leftist Sandinista government and the
U.S.-supported rebels, known as Contras, halted offensive military
operations on March 21, two days before Sandinista and Contra
negotiators reached a cease-fire pact. A 60-day truce went into
effect April 1.
   The two soldiers told The Associated Press they were among a
group of Sandinistas who approached about 40 Contras in the town of
El Colorado, about 140 miles southeast of Managua.
   Luis Noel Solano Jarquin, a Sandinista People's Army soldier,
said from his hospital room in Juigalpa, about 65 miles east of
Managua, that the Contras told the soldiers that only top rebel and
government leaders could conduct ``conversations between the two
sides.''
   ``Suddenly we heard shots and had to disband,'' Solano Jarquin
said.
   He said the incident occurred at 9 p.m. Thursday (11:00 p.m.
EDT). He did not specify how many Sandinistas were involved, but
indicated it was not a large group.
   Solano Jarquin nursed a wounded left arm. Another soldier,
Trinidad Bermudez, had fractured ribs and a broken forearm. They
said two other Sandinista soldiers were wounded and being treated
at a hospital in Ciudad Rama, about 140 miles east of Managua.
   A Defense Ministry official said he had no information on the
incident.
   Solano Jarquin and Bermudez said several armed confrontations
have occurred between Sandinista and rebel forces since the
cease-fire went into effect.
   On Thursday, the Defense Ministry charged that Honduras-based
Contras used speedboats to attack a Nicaraguan military position
Wednesday. The rebels did not comment on this.
   Adan Artola, a commander for the Indian rebel group known as
Yatama, said Friday that troops recently attacked rebel positions
in Auya-Pinhi, 270 miles northeast of Managua.
   In a telephone interview from Miami, he said Yatama killed seven
Sandinista soldiers and wounded 23 in the incident.
   The Defense Ministry offered no information on that report.
   Yatama claims to have more than 4,000 guerrillas whose objective
is autonomy for Nicaragua's Indian populations on the Caribbean
coast. It is not formally linked to the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
