<DOCNO> AP880506-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 3rdLd-Writethru a0837 05-06 0907</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0837,0931</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Leader Jailed in Gdansk; Walesa Speaks To Revive Workers'
Morale</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to INCLUDE church protest at end of Nowa
Huta strike; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``The government ...; INSERTS 1
graf details after 23rd graf pvs, ``At the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A labor leader in Gdansk was ordered
jailed Friday for organizing an illegal strike, and Lech Walesa
stirred workers with a speech in the city's strikebound shipyard
after a young man tried to jump from a window.
   Food and morale both were running low when the Solidarity leader
gave his impassioned, impromptu speech to the strikers.
   Poland's powerful Roman Catholic Church, whose mediators had
been trying to solve strikes at Gdansk and Nowa Huta, said in an
official statement that it regretted the government's decision to
end the Nowa Huta strike.
   Th government took steps to toughen its anti-strike laws one day
after police crushed a 10-day-old steelworkers strike at the Nowa
Huta mill in southern Poland.
   New signs cropped up that the government of Premier Wojciech
Jaruzelski was broadening its counterattack against the worst wave
of labor upheaval in Poland since a 1981 military crackdown.
   Jaruzelski, in a speech to a Polish bankers' group, said the
nation's economic difficulties were ``yet again being taken
instrumental advantage of against socialism and ... against our
entire society.''
   He did, however, admit that some mechanisms of the government's
reform program have been ``insufficiently effective,'' the PAP news
agency reported.
   At the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk, hundreds of police surrounded
the complex while 800 to 1,000 strikers remained inside. They are
demanding higher wages and union rights.
   Walesa has been in the shipyard since Wednesday.
   A young striker on Friday suddenly rushed to a window of the
big, second-floor cafeteria where most of the strikers have been
gathering, smashed the glass and tried to leap out, according to
Western reporters at the scene.
   Friends grabbed him, pulled him in and took him _ his hands and
face covered with blood _ to the nearby shipyard infirmary. Details
about him were not available, and witnesses could not say what
prompted his sudden action.
   Walesa immediately raced to the dining hall, mounted a chair and
gave an emotional, impromptu speech which had an obvious effect in
lifting spirits.
   Walesa told the strikers, holed up in the shipyard since Monday,
``You know that Solidarity is also taking care of the person next
to you.
   ``Everyone has a thousand problems: because he loves his wife
and he must stay here, another left 500 zlotys ($1.25) to his wife
when he left. Suddenly he realizes she has nothing to live on.
   ``Solidarity must be big here.''
   Reporters, speaking on condition of anonymity, said tension
eased and spirits rose after the speech.
   With food supplies to the shipyards stopped by police since
Thursday morning, the strikers had only sauerkraut soup to share.
   ``It seems they are going to use a different scenario than in
Nowa Huta,'' said senior Polish dissident Adam Michnik. ``They
probably want to take the shipyard by hunger.''
   Also Friday, a Gdansk court sentenced a union leader who called
the Lenin shipyard strike on Monday to three months in prison.
   Bogdan Lis, the head of the Gdansk region of the outlawed trade
union federation Solidarity, was convicted of calling an illegal
strike.
   At least five other Solidarity activists were detained Friday,
said Zbigniew Romaszewski, a Solidarity spokesman in Warsaw who
keeps tracks of arrests nationwide.
   The government drafted a bill that would punish organizers of
strikes and protests with prison sentences of up to one year.
   The draft, obtained by Western news agencies in Warsaw, also
would suspend the already limited right to strike by officially
recognized trade unions.
   At the Nowa Huta steelworks in Krakow, where police staged a
lightning raid with deafening percussion grenades Thursday while
strikers slept, sullen workers emerged after their shifts ended and
refused to talk with reporters. Some murmured that all was normal
in the plant.
   ``We express deep sorrow that an attempt of dialogue and social
conciliation did not bring the expected results,'' the Roman
Catholic Church secretariat said. ``This does not serve the welfare
of society or the country.''
   ``With outrage we protest the use of force against striking
workers and students. We think that the use of force leads to the
worst possible social effects,'' said a statement by Aleksander
Koj, rector at the Jagiellonian University in Krakow, a state-run
university.
   A local Solidarity leader, Stanislaw Wadolowski, said the threat
of force ended a one-day strike by bus drivers in the northwestern
city of Szczecin. He said riot police were put into position
outside bus yards Thursday, six strikers were briefly detained, and
the strike ended after 10 hours.
   Wage demands triggered by 42 percent inflation this year have
prompted at least five strikes since April 25, and the government
confirmed this week it would seek additional economic powers to
accelerate its program to reform the economy.
   The government has said the strikes could derail the reform
plans by making wages rise faster than prices. Plans call for
higher and more realistic prices, smaller government subsidies and
improved conditions for managers and private enterprise.
   Solidarity generally favors the reforms. But a statement by
Walesa Friday from inside the shipyard said that, ``Society must be
the co-author and partner in the solutions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
