<DOCNO> AP880506-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0814 05-06 1132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0814,1,090</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Troubled By Some Allegations Against Meese; Calls Jackson
`Hustler'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Bush comments about
Jackson, Dukakis, edit for transition; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs bgng,
`Of Meese'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BILLINGS, Mont</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush characterized
Jesse Jackson as a ``hustler from Chicago'' on Friday during a day
in which he said he was ``troubled by some of the allegations''
against Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   Bush's remarks about Jackson came on the way home from three
days of campaigning in the West.
   Addressing a Republican dinner at the University of Nebraska,
Bush said: ``It's a pleasure to be here. And I'll be back. And I'm
not going to be out-hustled by the hustler from Chicago or from
that traditional liberal Democrat from Massachusetts.''
   It was a clear reference to the two remaining Democratic
candidates: Jackson, who has a home in Chicago, and Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis, the front-runner.
   While Bush has called Dukakis a traditional liberal Democrat
before, his ``hustler'' remark was the first time he has described
Jackson in such terms.
   Bush spokesman Stephen Hart said the vice president ``was
talking about how hard he (Jackson) has hustled. It was nothing
derogatory.''
   Earlier, Bush said that comments by two senior campaign aides
suggesting Meese was a campaign liability had not been authorized
by him. At the same time, he said he was troubled by some of the
allegations against Meese.
   The vice president said that ``my position on Meese is that the
system is working, the investigation is going on and can't be
enhanced by my fine-tuning or criticizing.''
   Bush's comments, in a session with reporters, came after his
communications director Peter Teeley and Robert Teeter, a senior
campaign adviser, were quoted as saying that Meese has become a
liability in Bush's campaign for the presidency.
   ``I haven't authorized anything. Now I have to get on the phone
and find out what they said,'' Bush told reporters earlier in Twin
Falls, Idaho.
   In Billings, Mont., Bush said that he had talked to the aides
but declined to characterize his conversation. A campaign source,
who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said Bush was angry when
he talked with Teeley.
   Of Meese, Bush said in Billings: ``I know him well, favorably,
but I must say I am troubled by some of the allegations. I think
fair play dictates that the system go forward and make the
determination.''
   Asked if Meese had become an albatross on his campaign, Bush
said: ``An albatross? I don't think so.''
   Bush added that the independent counsel investigating the
attorney general's legal difficulties was due to release a report
soon, and said: ``We'll see what it says. It's only a matter of a
few days away.''
   The Detroit News, in a story published Friday, said Teeley and
Teeter made their comments in interviews this week in Washington.
   ``Meese is a liability,'' Teeley was quoted as saying.
   ``All things considered, you would rather not have that problem
going on right now,'' Teeter said, referring to the independent
counsel's investigation of Meese.
   In comments on other subjects:
   _The vice president called on the government of Poland to
negotiate with striking workers and to include the outlawed labor
union Solidarity in talks to end violence there.
   _Campaigning for farm-area support, Bush attacked Democratic
front-runner Dukakis for advocating a greater federal role in
control of Western water rights.
   ``We're going to have a lively debate in the fall,'' Bush said.
``He was wrong and I was right.''
   Talking with a group of farmers in a barn in Idaho, with a sleet
storm howling outside, Bush said water allocation for irrigation
should remain under state control.
   He also promised to keep sugar quotas and other government farm
trade supports in place, despite the Reagan administration's desire
for an eventual elimination of all farm subsidies and quotas
worldwide.
   Bush said the quotas should be maintained at least until other
countries eliminate their own farm subsidies.
   In Billings, Bush continued with his agricultural theme, telling
an airport rally, ``There will be no more grain embargoes against
the Soviet Union or anyone else. We are not going to use food as a
political weapon.''
   Former President Carter's grain embargo _ in response to the
sending of Soviet troops into Afghanistan _ was unpopular in
grain-producing states.
   Bush expressed surprise when told by reporters of the comments
on Meese by his two aides.
   In the past, Bush has said the Justice Department should be
``above reproach.'' But he has also said he does not want to
prejudge Meese, and the legal system should be permitted to take
its course.
   ``I've said about all I need to say on that for awhile,'' Bush
said on Friday.
   However, the aides' public comments that Meese's legal
difficulties have become a liability to the Bush campaign reflect
what other campaign advisers have said privately in the past.
   Campaign aides, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, have
said that Bush would be relieved if Meese would resign because the
situation had become an embarrassment for the campaign.
   The same sources said Bush had not urged Meese to resign nor
advocated such a course to the president.
   On Poland, Bush said the government there should recognize the
reality of the Solidarity movement and deal with its leaders to
avoid further violence in that strike-torn country.
   ``I know they consider Solidarity illegal. But given the state
of play there, they should talk to each other and get this under
control so people in Poland will not be hurt,'' he said.
   Speaking to students at the College of Southern Idaho, Bush
heralded the 5.4 percent unemployment figure for April reported
earlier in the day _ the lowest rate since 1974 _ and used it to
mount a new attack on Democrats.
   ``When I hear the political opponents going around about pink
slips and disaster, they're flying in the face of some
extraordinary economic progress. Yes, some people are still
hurting, but I want to see this recovery continue until everybody
benefits,'' he said.
   In comments to local reporters in Twin Falls, Bush made light of
the ``Massachusetts miracle'' of economic revival that Dukakis has
trumpeted.
   ``I think there will be plenty of things to use in our favor in
terms of who's responsible for the Massachusetts miracle,'' he
said. ``I happen to think the Reagan-Bush administration had
something to do with that.''
   Bush also asserted that although he expected the Iran-Contra
affair to be used against him in the general election, ``I'm not
worried. It's been tested and tried in the primary.''
   His involvement in the affair ``doesn't show up as a great
vulnerability,'' he has said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
