<2ND_LINE>BC-Fisher Grants,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grants to Young Instrumentalists Awarded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avery Fisher Career Grants, designed to assist
musicians believed to be on the threshold of major careers, were
awarded Thursday to two violinists, a pianist and a guitarist.
   Violinists Pamela Frank and Ida Kavafian, pianist Andrew Rangell
and guitarist David Starobin were named this year's recipients of
the grants of $1,000 each.
   Miss Frank, 20, born in New York and living in Philadelphia,
studies at the Curtis Institute of Music with Jaime Laredo. Miss
Kavafian, 35, born in Istanbul and living in New York, has a
masters degree from the Juilliard School. She was a founding member
of the group Tashi and has recorded for RCA and Nonesuch.
   Rangell, 39, born in Chicago and living in Hanover, N.H., has a
doctorate from Juilliard and was a Naumburg Competition finalist.
From 1977 through '85, he taught piano at Dartmouth College.
   Starobin, 36, born in New York and living in Great Neck, N.Y.,
is a member of and conducts the contemporary music ensemble
Speculum Musicae. In 1981 he founded Bridge Records. More than 150
guitar works have been composed for him.
   Three to five Avery Fisher Career Grants can be awarded each
year, all to U.S. citizens. Recipients are proposed by a large
board and chosen by a nine-man committee of musicians and arts
administrators. The grants are part of the Avery Fisher Artist
Program.
</TEXT>
