<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:BookOfExperts Adv13   05-06 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Book Of Experts, Adv 13,0655</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, May 13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Directory Is Source Of Sources</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER C. PUTNAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Need an expert on reincarnation? Nuclear power?
Economics? Sex? Boredom?
   Questions about computers, atheism or weight loss have you
stumped?
   The ``Directory of Experts, Authorities and Spokespersons''
offers to fill the void.
   The 1987-88 directory, the fourth annual edition, provides in
its 384 yellow pages an encyclopedia of sources of fact and opinion
on subjects ranging from AIDS to zoological parks. The sources
range from serious experts to whimsical organizations.
   Subscribers to what is subtitled the ``Talk Show Guest
Directory'' include the major TV networks, magazines, newspapers
and the U.S. bureaus of foreign publications and news agencies.
   ``This new edition has been written from scratch after directly
contacting tens of thousands of sources,'' said editor Mitchell P.
Davis. ``We have done the research to find 3,524 experts,
authorities and spokespersons who have stated their willingness to
be interviewed.''
   Subjects and sources are interspersed with advertisements,
similar to the Yellow Pages telephone directory. The book is
published by Broadcast Interview Source of Washington.
   ``More Americans are Trying Nude Recreation,'' says a full-page
ad by the American Sunbathing Association in Florida, which is
available for media questions regarding nudist viewpoints.
   The Society for the Eradication of Television has a cartoon
drawing of a man kicking in a TV. ``The battle over the future of
TV is looming as Eradicators challenge couch potatoes,'' the ad
says.
   The couch potatoes, so named because of a tendency to vegetate
in front of the telly, counter in a separate ad below with ``six
arguments in support of television.'' They include: ``TV viewing is
purely an American form of meditation.'' For information call head
spud Bob Armstrong in California.
   The ``minister of information'' for the Couch Potatoes, Jack
Mingo of Alameda, Calif., acknowledged that his group is mostly
tongue-in-cheek.
   ``But we practice what we believe, or else we would be
hypocrites, don't you think?'' Mingo said.
   He said the unpaid ad has brought numerous calls. Most of them
come from radio stations who enjoy getting the potatoes in debate
with the TV eradicators, whom Mingo described as ``grimly serious.''
   The Shameless Hussy Press pledges to provide speakers on women's
subjects. Various others offer expertise on handwriting analysis,
psychic phenomena and financial matters, including one which states
in bold letters ``Offshore Banking Is Not Evil.''
   The Boring Institute provides commentary on politics, show
business, televison films and personalities, ``plus some good
advice on how to avoid and overcome boredom,'' even in sex.
   ``We pursue those amusing ads because they interest people and
get them to read the book. It's not just a reference book,'' said
Davis, who got the idea from a monthly newsletter of sources put
out by a public relations firm for which he worked.
   About 95 percent of the ads are paid, he said. Some are offered
for public service or for graphic interest.
   One that falls in both categories is the full-page ad with
surprising photos of bruised, bare buttocks, put in by People
Opposed to Paddling of Students.
   Other advertisers in the directory use clever lead-ins.
   ``Totally `Childish' Conversation,'' is promised by a Cleveland
hospital offering ``expert conservation on all manner of childish
subjects: neonatology, birthing, obstetrics, pediatrics.''
   Others are more straightforward.
   School prayer, cults, creationism? ``American Atheists can speak
on all of them _ and more.''
   Davis said this year's book contains about 180 pages of ads at
$360 a page. Copies distributed, including free ones, total 4,000,
he said.
   According to Davis, the book is popular enough to be a viable
business.
   ``It'll be back next year in a fifth edition,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri May 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
