<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-06 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0517</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cool weather and an early Easter hurt retail sales in April,
reports from the nation's largest general retailers reveal.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. said Thursday its overall sales rose 4.8
percent from April 1987's results, while K mart Corp. was up 2.5
percent and J.C. Penney Co. Inc. fell 0.4 percent.
   Analysts said cool weather hurt sales of spring apparel as well
as lawn and garden and seasonal merchandise, while early arrival of
Easter this year meant consumers did their spring shopping in March.
   Although some retailers saw sales rise, analysts said the gains
were less than expected.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commisssion has
authorized brief trading halts across domestic markets when
important news affecting a specific stock is pending.
   The commission voted 3-2 Thursday to give the National
Association of Securities Dealers authority to ban over-the-counter
trading in exchange-listed stocks, a practice called ``third market
trading.''
   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder said it would reduce the opportunity
for illegal insider trading.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of stockbrokers has told a House
subcommittee that last October's financial crash and the prevalance
of program trading is frightening the average American away from
the stock market.
   The brokers, speaking Thursday before the House
telecommunications and finance subcommittee, said the dramatic
price swings that have characterized trading in recent months, and
computer-driven transactions by huge institutions, are making the
public reluctant to invest in stocks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. has agreed to sell its fast-growing
Duracell Inc. battery division to a group led by management and the
investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. in a cash deal worth
$1.8 billion.
   Kraft said Thursday it agreed to sell the world's leading maker
of alkaline consumer batteries in order to concentrate on its core
food business.
   Proceeds from the sale would be used to buy back up to 12
million Kraft shares, to reduce debt and for possible food-related
acquisitions, the company said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public school teachers now earn $28,031 on
average and in 10 states the typical teacher earns more than
$30,000 a year, the National Education Association says.
   The average classroom teacher, with 15 years of experience, got
a 5.6 percent pay raise last year that boosted her or his salary by
$1,477 from the 1986-87 level of $26,534.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel is urging the Department of
Transportation to broaden its probe of troubled Eastern Airlines
and its parent company, Texas Air Corp.
   On a voice vote, the Public Works and Transportation Committee
sent the legislation to the full House Thursday, giving the
carrier's labor unions another victory in their ongoing war against
the company's executives.
   On another front, Eastern asked a federal appeals court here to
overturn a lower court's ruling that blocks the airline from
selling its profitable Boston-New York-Washington air shuttle
service. The court reserved judgment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
