<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0488</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Transportation has proposed
random drug testing in the railroad industry, even as the agency
appeals a court ruling striking down its program of testing train
crews involved in accidents.
   At the same time, it moved Thursday to crack down on drunken
driving by commercial bus and truck drivers with the threat of
license losses for first-time offenders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Texaco Inc. and takeover
specialist Carl Icahn say they hope to have a lawsuit resolved
before the oil giant's annual meeting next month.
   Texaco has sued Icahn _ its largest shareholder _ over alleged
violations of federal securities laws. Among other things, the
lawsuit seeks to void a slate of five candidates Icahn has
nominated for election to Texaco's board of directors at the oil
giant's June 7 annual meeting in Tulsa, Okla.
   Attorneys for the two sides spent about two hours behind closed
doors Thursday working out a schedule for pre-trial preparations in
the case.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hawaii remains the most popular choice of
Americans for summer vacation travel, according to a survey by
American Express Co.
   The forecast, based on a mail survey of 350 American Express
travel agencies nationwide, said Thursday that 27 percent of the
agents polled named Hawaii as the top choice for vacation travel
this summer. Other leading vacation destinations were Europe with
21 percent, and Florida and the Caribbean with 18 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monsanto Corp. has refused a request by
advocacy groups to take Lasso, the nation's most widely-used
herbicide, off the market because of its cancer-causing potential.
   In a letter to Monsanto's chairman, the groups asked Thursday
that the company honor previous pledges not to sell unsafe products
``by recognizing the unacceptable risks posed by Lasso.''
   But Robert Harness, vice president for environmental affairs,
said Monsanto ``has absolutely no intention of pulling Lasso from
the market.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's money supply grew sharply in the
week ended April 25, the government reported. The increase had no
impact on financial markets and economists regarded it as largely
inconsequential.
   They attributed the rise reported Thursday to an unexpectedly
higher rate of federal tax refunds as well as government
sluggishness in cashing taxpayer checks, which inflated the
categories of money included in the supply figures.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Thursday for the second straight session,
sending the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials down 16.08 to
2,020.23 after a 22.05-point decline the previous day.
   Bond prices were unchanged to slightly higher.
   The dollar edged up in domestic foreign exchange trading after
falling overseas.
   Pork futures prices climbed, cattle futures advanced and energy
futures rose but grains and soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
