<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-06 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refinery Fire Helps Send Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have strengthened in the wake
of a Gulf Coast refinery explosion that tightened gasoline
supplies, and amid market sentiment that domestic demand for crude
is accelerating, analysts say.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, June contracts for
wholesale unleaded gasoline closed up 0.89 cent at 50.61 cents per
gallon on Thursday. Wholesale heating oil rose 0.37 cent to 46.57
cents per gallon.
   June contracts for West Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark
crude, also closed higher Thursday, rising 19 cents to $17.39 per
barrel.
   In Norco, La., an early morning explosion and fire devastated a
Shell Oil Co. refinery and much of the surrounding town. The
accident ruptured the refinery's catalytic cracker, which converts
crude oil to gasoline, and seriously damaged control rooms and
other facilities.
   Greg Dreis, an analyst at Merrill Lynch Energy Futures, said the
destruction created a squeeze in the Gulf Coast, sending gasoline
futures prices up in New York when the market opened.
   Bob Baker, a Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. analyst, said he
agreed that the explosion ``clearly gave some relative strength to
gasoline here.''
   He also said crude moved higher because ``people realize we're
going to be needing crude oil here _ and (foreign) oil producers
are still holding the reins'' of production.
   ``They're not talking with each other all the way. But they're
talking enough,'' he said, referring to both the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries and independent producing nations.
   OPEC and several major independent producers failed earlier this
week to reach an accord on joint output cuts aimed at boosting
prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
