<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     05-06 0119</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0124</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on 52-Week Bills Highest Since December</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on 52-week Treasury bills rose
in the government's latest auction to the highest level since
December.
   The Treasury Department sold $8.8 billion of the bills at an
average discount rate of 6.74 percent on Thursday, up from 6.57
percent at the last auction on April 7.
   The rates were the highest since Dec. 17, when the one-year
bills also sold at a 6.74 percent rate. The last time the rate was
higher was Sept. 30, 1987, when the bills sold at 7.32 percent.
   The new discount rate understates the actual return to investors
_ 7.20 percent with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,318.50.
</TEXT>
