<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoTalks Bjt   05-06 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Talks, Bjt,0695</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>With Chrysler Back on Pattern, UAW and Big Three Can Aim at
Japanese</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers union has brought the Big
Three U.S. automakers back under an industry pattern contract for
the first time in a decade, with this week's settlement at Chrysler
Corp.
   But since the UAW first allowed Chrysler to negotiate a separate
concessionary contract in 1979, the U.S. auto industry has changed,
and the pattern contract that is shaping its future has changed
with it.
   Instead of just the Big Three _ Chrysler, General Motors Corp.
and Ford Motor Co. _ and American Motors Corp., eight U.S. and
foreign companies build cars in the United States.
   Chrysler bought AMC in August and Volkswagen, the only European,
will leave the picture later this year when it closes its
Pennsylvania assembly plant.
   That leaves Honda Motor Co., Toyota Motor Corp., Nissan Motor
Corp. and Mazda Motor Corp. _ all strong Japanese competitors as
importers and all promising strong futures as domestic makers.
   So far, the UAW represents only Mazda and one of Toyota's two
U.S. plants.
   By 1990, Mitsubishi Motors Corp., Fuji Heavy Industries, the
maker of Subaru, and Isuzu Motor Co. also will be building cars in
this country.
   That means although the UAW will be bargaining with the Big
Three simultaneously in 1990, it must face competitive market
realities it may have ignored before 1979.
   The pattern contract is helping reshape Big Three labor and
management through 1990 so the companies can survive the
increasingly intensive competition on their home soil.
   ``The union and the companies are riding down a rough river with
rapids and rocks ahead _ in the same raft. They know that if either
kicks a hole in the bottom, they'll sink together,'' said David
Cole, director of the Office for the Study of Automotive
Transportation at the University of Michigan in Dearborn.
   Chrysler's 66,000-worker contract must be approved today by
leaders of its local unions before it can be presented to the rank
and file for ratification.
   The contract gives workers greater job security. In turn, it
gives the automakers a chance to use workers more flexibly by
removing national union leaders' opposition to Japanese-style work
agreements negotiated at the plant level.
   Furthermore, while basic wage levels are the same at all three
companies, workers' earnings can vary by an unprecedented amount
from company to company because of a profit-sharing formula.
   The formula generated nearly $4,000 a worker at Ford from 1987
profits, $1,500 for Chrysler workers _ paid as a $500 bonus from a
previous contract and a $1,000 contract-signing bonus _ and nothing
for GM workers.
   In the past, the purpose of pattern bargaining was to remove
wages from competition _ essentially saying the Big Three could
compete among each other on the basis of productivity and quality,
but could not compete on the basis of wage costs, said Harley
Shaiken, labor and technology expert at the University of
California at San Diego.
   Now, part of workers' annual pay is dependent on their
companies' performance.
   ``We've seen a tremendous increase in union emphasis on quality
issues. They're saying `If quality sells, we're going to support
everything in this company that improves quality because we know
it's going to affect our compensation,''' Cole said.
   Increasing recognition of the interdependence between management
and workers is key to the Big Three pattern. But at Chrysler, the
UAW took it a step farther, forbidding payment of cash or stock
executive bonuses in years when the profit-sharing formula
generates no payout for workers.
   The clause largely is symbolic: it doesn't affect payouts
promised in executives' contracts, limit the size of bonuses,
prevent lost bonuses from being recovered in later years or
prohibit stock options _ the main source of the whopping $17.9
million Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca took home in 1987.
   But, Cole said, it is a first step toward making sure executives
and hourly workers ``understand they are all playing the same
game.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UMW-Pittston Bjt   05-06 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UMW-Pittston, Bjt,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coal Talks Take New Twist As Miners Work With No Contract At
Pittston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the last contract between the United
Mine Workers and Pittston Coal Group Inc. ran out earlier this
year, people in the southern Appalachian coalfields braced for a
potentially violent strike.
   But this past weekend marked three months that some 2,000 UMW
members have remained on the job with no contract at Pittston's
mines in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky.
   There have been no bombings, no sabotage, no snipings, and no
strike.
   Instead, both sides have waged corporate and public relations
campaigns while contract talks plod along on a two-days-a-week
circuit that alternates between Norton, Va.; Charleston, W.Va.; and
Washington, D.C.
   The company also has changed its tight-lipped media stance of
the past in favor of an unprecedented openness that has been dubbed
``coalfield glasnost,'' in reference to the Soviet Union's new
self-stated policy of openness.
   Neither side seems able to predict where this new type of labor
battle will lead in an industry where just a few years ago union
miners would not have worked a minute without a contract.
   ``I think that unions are becoming more inclined to do that
today,'' Pittston Coal President Gene Matthis said in a recent
interview from his Lebanon, Va., office.
   The negotiations mark the first time Pittston, a subsidiary of
Greenwich, Conn.-based Pittston Co., has tried to reach its own
contract with the UMW. Last May, the company dropped out of the
industry group that has done the bargaining on past contracts, the
Bituminous Coal Operators Association.
   In February, for the second straight contract, the BCOA reached
a new UMW pact without a strike, but Pittston would not go along.
   UMW leaders repeatedly have accused Pittston of trying to break
the union, a charge Matthis denies. Matthis also disputes the
suggestion that Pittston may be winning the battle by keeping
employees on the job with no contract.
   ``I don't think that it gives us an upper hand,'' Matthis said.
``We still have to hammer out an agreement.''
   UMW officials claim Pittston refuses to bargain in good faith.
But although the UMW negotiating team has the authority to call
strikes at any or all of Pittston's mines, it has not done so.
   Instead of striking, the union has launched a corporate
campaign, aimed at putting pressure on Pittston in the boardroom
instead of at the mines.
   This past week, union members and supporters protested Pittston
twice in Richmond, demonstrating against the re-election of
Pittston Co. Chairman and Chief Executive Paul W. Douglas to the
board of Philip Morris and then at the offices of Pittston lender
Crestar Bank.
   The union also has demonstrated at the New York offices of Chase
Manhattan Bank, another Pittston lender, and union officials have
contacted state government officials in Michigan, one of Pittston's
biggest stockholders.
   Matthis said he has gotten no heat from the corporate campaign.
He could not say if any waves have been made with his superiors at
the Greenwich headquarters. A spokesman there did not return a
phone call.
   Union officials say their corporate attacks on Pittston are not
entirely new to the labor movement, but they certainly are
different from the violent strikes of the past.
   During a rally in Lebanon earlier this year, while guitarists
sang old labor ballads, UMW International President Richard Trumka
lashed out at Pittston in the language of the modern business
world. He blasted the parent corporation for setting up ``golden
parachute'' severance agreements for its executives and accused
Pittston of trying to force a bad deal on miners to make its coal
operations bear the costs of unwise acquisitions in the air freight
business.
   UMW spokesman Ken Zinn said the union has tried to convince
banks to let Pittston know that settling with the union would be in
its best interest.
   ``The loan they have extended to Pittston is a high-risk one,''
Zinn said. He said the company's working capital has plummeted from
$90 million in 1984 to $2.1 million last year. Moody's Investor
Service has downgraded Pittston's debt rating during that time.
   ``They lost over $133 million last year,'' Zinn said. ``They
haven't paid a dividend to their stockholders in the last five
years.''
   The union tells the banks that if Pittston is struck, its
moneymaking coal operations could suffer, making debt repayment
impossible. Pittston has said it would operate through a strike.
   Zinn declined comment on whether the corporate campaign was
working. Other UMW officials have said they believe a strike is
inevitable, but they won't say when.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
