<HEAD>Allegheny Creditors Seeking To Halt Proxy Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bankruptcy court judge has scheduled a
hearing on a request by Allegheny International Inc.'s unsecured
creditors to halt a proxy fight being waged by two investment firms
for control of the company.
   Judge Joseph Cosetti set a hearing for next Thursday over the
creditors' request to block the firms, Spear Leeds & Kellogg and
Bomar Holdings, from trying to gain control of the 13-member board
in a May 20 shareholder vote.
   The dissident firms contend Allegheny International's top
managers are more interested in keeping their jobs than in
preserving shareholders' interests as the company reorganizes under
federal bankruptcy protection from creditors.
   The firms are trying gain seven seats on the company's board.
   On Thursday, Allegheny International announced it planned to
send letters to shareholders urging them to oppose the dissident
shareholders group. But the company later said it had canceled
those plans.
   Allegheny International's prime businesses are the consumer
products produced by Sunbeam, Oster, Northern Electric,
Almet-Lawnlite, Springfield Instrument, Soloray and Hanson Scale.
