<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Tax-Mail 1stLd-Writethru f0025 05-06 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax-Mail, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0025,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sneaky Mailing Method For Late Taxpayers May Not Work</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs new to remove pvs attribution. Picks up 4th graf
pvs, The way; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special service offered to stamp collectors
could make it possible for late taxpayers to mail their returns
this month and still beat the April 15 filing deadline, but
government officials say the practice is questionable.
   People using the special ``First Day of Issue'' service can
still get envelopes with postmarks dated in March, Linn's Stamp
News, a newspaper for collectors, points out in its May 9 edition.
   The way it works is that the Postal Service allows collectors to
buy stamps, put them on envelopes, and mail the envelopes in bulk
to the post office where the first-day ceremonies were held.
   The first-day cancellations are then affixed, often as much as a
month after the event, and the envelopes returned to the collector.
   This is done for stamp collectors, since most of them are unable
to travel to each city where new stamps may be issued, and the new
stamps cannot be purchased in other cities until the day after
issue.
   Offering the first-day cancellations for 30 days or so takes
pressure off the issuing post office and gives collectors time to
buy the new stamps and send them in for the cancellations.
   Thus, a collector could put the new ``E'' stamps on an envelope
containing tax forms, send it to Washington for the first day
cancellation, and it would then be delivered with the date March 22
on the envelope.
   The deadline for First Day cancellations of the ``E'' stamps is
May 21, slightly longer than normal because of the short notice
before the stamps were put on sale.
   The ``E'' stamps were issued March 22 in anticipation of new
postage rates, which took effect April 3.
   Technically, then, a taxpayer could still send in the forms ``on
time,'' under court decisions that have held a postmark is evidence
of filing.
   But Dick Rustin, manager of the post office's stamp information
branch, says cancellations for the first day of issue look
different and are treated differently from regular-date
cancellations affixed to mail.
   Regular cancellations do confirm the date something was mailed,
he said. But, for those which state ``first day of issue,'' he
said, ``we would not verify that the mail entered the system on
that day.''
   Generally collectors send in envelopes addressed to themselves
for these cancellations, he said.
   Rustin said postal officials might raise a question and contact
a collector ``if it appeared obvious that their intent'' in getting
the special cancellation was to defraud. But, he added, ``we're not
a police state, either.''
   Tax forms arriving a month late with a March 22 cancellation
might also raise questions at the IRS, said spokeswoman Johnell
Hunter. She said the tax agency might check to see if the
individual sending in the form had a history of being late.
   The IRS says perhaps 3 million tax forms have yet to be sent in,
although many of those are for Americans who live overseas and have
more than a month left to file.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   05-06 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unemployment Rate Slips In April</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with April unemployment, new
jobs figures; uppicks 2nd graf pvs: On Wall...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The national unemployment rate has hit its lowest level since
June 1974, dropping to 5.4 percent in April, the government said
today.
   With 606,000 people finding jobs, the number of unemployed
Americans fell by 191,000 to just over 6.6 million, shaving 0.2
percentage point from March's 5.6 percent level.
   A separate survey of business payrolls showed a gain of 175,000
jobs in April, more than one-fourth of them on factory assembly
lines in industries that have increased their exports in recent
months.
   The Labor Deparment's figures came one day after the nation's
largest retailers issued April sales figures that analysts
described as disappointing.
   On Wall Street, stocks fell Thursday for the second consecutive
session as traders awaited today's report on April employment. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 16.08 points to close
at 2,020.23, following a 22.05-point retreat on Wednesday.
   The sluggish April retail sales results were blamed on cool
weather and the early arrival of Easter this year, which pushed
spring shopping into March. Although several major retailers
reported their sales rose during the month from a year earlier, the
gains were deemed lackluster.
   Jeffrey B. Edelman, a retail industry analyst with the
investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., said the sales
increases were ``below expectations.''
   ``Put it all together, it's a dismal picture,'' said Linda
Kristiansen, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest retailer, said its
overall sales rose 4.8 percent from April 1987, while sales from
stores open at least a year were up 2 percent for the month.
   K mart Corp. said its overall sales rose 2.5 percent last month,
but the so-called same-store sales fell 0.6 percent. Wal-Mart
Stores Inc. said its overall sales climbed 32 percent in April
while same-store sales rose 12 percent.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc., which emphasizes its apparel lines, saw
sales decline by 0.4 percent last month.
   In other economic news on Thursday:
   _The nation's money supply rose sharply in the week ended April
25, the government reported. The increase had no impact on
financial markets and was regarded by economists as largely
inconsequential.
   _Assets of the nation's 426 money market mutual funds rose
$611.7 million in the week ended Wednesday to $273.61 billion, the
Investment Company Institute said. The increase followed a revised
$1.47 billion decline the previous week, the Washington-based
mutual fund trade group said.
   _Ward's Automotive Reports said domestic automakers were
scheduled to produce 249,292 cars and trucks this week, virtually
unchanged from last week's 249,889.
</TEXT>
