<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WPPSSSuit     05-06 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WPPSS Suit,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Some WPPSS Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dismissed the claims of some
of the bondholders suing the Washington Public Power Supply System
over the scrapping of two nuclear plants.
   Judge William Browning, at a pretrial hearing in Seattle
Thursday, granted a defense motion ruling out the damage claims of
people who bought bonds used to finance the plants, Nos. 4 and 5,
but who bought them after the projects were stopped in early 1982.
   Browning appeared to reverse an earlier decision in which he
included bondholders who had bought bonds for the plants between
Jan. 22, 1983, when the projects were terminated, and June 15,
1983, when the Washington Supreme Court invalidated the agreements
under which the projects were financed.
   It was not immediately clear how many of the approximately
35,000 bondholders in the suit were removed by the ruling. Clearing
Up, an energy and utility newsletter published in Seattle, last
September placed the number of ``post-termination'' bondholders at
4,800.
   The ruling pleased defense attorneys, who maintained that after
WPPSS terminated Plants 4 and 5, bond buyers should have been aware
WPPSS was having difficulties.
   The suit alleges WPPSS, underwriters and others misled bond
investors by withholding information about WPPSS' financial
problems and alleged mismanagement of the projects.
   But after the projects were scrapped, ``the (bond) market was
aware of the matters that the plaintiffs were claiming had been
concealed,'' said David Jurca, attorney for a group of utilities.
   Arthur Hoffer, a Hauppauge, N.Y., resident who chairs a national
committee of WPPSS bondholders, said the judge should have kept
bondholders in the case based on how much each knew about WPPSS
problems when they invested.
   The Washington Public Power Supply System, headquartered in
Richland, attempted to build five nuclear power plants in the 1970s
to serve Northwest customers. Of those, one plant, WPPSS No. 2 at
the Hanford nuclear reservation, is operating.
   Two others, WPPSS No. 1 at Hanford and No. 3 at Satsop, west of
Olympia, were mothballed while still unfinished in the early 1980s.
   WPPSS terminated its other two plants, No. 4 at Hanford and No.
5 at Satsop, in 1982, after $2.25 billion had been invested.
   Termination of the plants eventually resulted in default on the
$2.25 billion in bonds sold to finance the construction of WPPSS
Nos. 4 and 5. It was the biggest default in the history of the
municipal bond market.
   Most of the litigation has been consolidated in one case that is
set to go to trial on Sept. 1 in Tucson, Ariz., if an out-of-court
settlement cannot be reached.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0925EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Icahn     05-06 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Efforts Made to Settle Icahn Case Before Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge will hear a Texaco
Inc. lawsuit against Carl C. Icahn by June 3, four days before the
oil giant's annual meeting at which Icahn has threatened to stage a
fight for five board seats.
   But attorneys for both sides said Thursday they hope to have the
suit resolved before then.
   Texaco has sued the takeover specialist over alleged violations
of federal securities laws. Among other things, the lawsuit seeks
to void a slate of directors that Icahn its largest shareholder, is
seeking to elect to the company's 14-member board at Texaco's June
7 meeting in Tulsa, Okla.
   Icahn, who owns 14.8 percent of Texaco's stock, has maintained
that the company was badly run and should be restructured or sold.
He has offered to withdraw his slate if the company puts itself up
for sale at at least $55 per share. Texaco's management refuses to
to do that.
   His lead lawyer, Raymond Falls, told U.S. District Judge Geard
Goettel that the two sides would file pre-hearing materials by May
27.
   Goettel set a hearing for June 3, but said the hearing could
occur as early as May 31.
   Texaco's suit, filed Tuesday, charged that Icahn, his associates
and companies he controls used ``deceptive and manipulative means''
to either force the company to pay greenmail, force its sale to a
third party, or to acquire it in order to break it up and sell the
pieces, ``in each case thereby obtaining vast profits for
themselves in disregard of federal law and the long-term interest
of the shareholders.''
   Greenmail refers to a transaction whereby a target company buys
back its stock held by an unwanted suitor at a premium price not
available to all shareholders.
   Texaco filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
the federal bankruptcy code a year ago. It emerged last month and
has launched a restructuring plan that includes the sale of $5
billion in assets.
   The bankruptcy was brought on by a 1985 Houston jury ruling that
it had improperly interfered with a Pennzoil Co. acquisition of
part of Getty Oil Co., then bought Getty itself.
   The jury awarded Pennzoil $10.53 billion, an amount that had
been reduced through court action to $10.3 billion when Texaco
filed for Chapter 11 protection on April 12, 1987.
   Dennis O'Dea, the attorney who represented the shareholders
committee during the oil company's Chapter 11 bankruptcy
proceedings, said the committee was ``caught in the middle'' of the
litigation.
   Another attorney, Stanley Bernstein, told Goettel that he was
representing a class of shareholders who planned to sue Icahn,
charging that Icahn manipulated stock prices when he bought shares
from Bernstein's clients.
   Bernstein said the suit would be filed in the next few days,
seeking damages for shareholders who claim they did not receive
fair prices because of Icahn's alleged manipulation of the market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880506-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0937EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers     05-06 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beazer Offers Vague Employment Guarantees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British industrialist Brian C. Beazer offered
employees of Koppers Co. unspecified job guarantees in exchange for
a friendly merger with the cement concern.
   Koppers did not immediately respond to the offer, made in a
letter dated Thursday. Beazer, together with the investment bank
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and a British bank, has a hostile
$1.7-billion tender offer on the table.
   Beazer wrote that in exchange for ``an immediate merger
agreement that avoids further waste and delay, we will offer
substantial and important employment guarantees to every single
employee ... other than senior management.''
   Beazer spokeswoman Lissa Perlman said today from New York that
she could not elaborate on whether Beazer is offering guaranteed
employment, severance pay or some other form of compensation.
   The chairman of the British construction company Beazer PLC said
he was renewing an earlier invitation to negotiate, which Koppers
rejected, in order to quell employees' fears that jobs will be cut
after a takeover and to ``end further senseless and expensive
litigation.''
   That litigation has resulted in federal court orders in
Pittsburgh and Los Angeles blocking the $60-per-share tender offer,
which is set to expire May 18 unless extended.
   Beazer claims that as of May 4, nearly 16.4 million common
shares had been tendered. Those shares combined with the two
million shares the group already owns represent 65.7 percent of
Koppers' outstanding common shares, he has said.
   ``An overwhelming majority of your shareholders wish to accept
our offer,'' Beazer said. ``They obviously prefer it to your
mythical recapitalization.''
   Koppers management has said it is studying various restructuring
plans in order to boost stock value.
</TEXT>
