down and 480 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.19 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Before the market opened the Labor Department reported that the
civilian unemployment rate fell to 5.4 percent in April from 5.6
percent the month before.
   There had been concern on Wall Street that stocks might suffer a
setback on signs of continuing strength in the economy, because of
concern that upward pressure might be increasing on inflation and
interest rates.
   However, the reported increase in nonfarm payroll employment of
174,000 came in toward the low end of advance estimates.
   And analysts said it looked as though stocks had taken into
account any worries the job data might pose with their decline
Wednesday and Thursday.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up { at 44]; USX,
up ] at 32[; American Telephone & Telegraph, up [ at 26\, and
Bethlehem Steel, up ] at 19{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.28 to 146.79. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .03 at 302.36.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 16.08 to
2,020.23, bringing its loss over the past two sessions to 38.13
points.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 558 up, 904 down and 507 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 171.84 million shares, against 141.32 million in the
previous session.
