<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-USTrade     05-06 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-US Trade,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-South Korean Trade Talks End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and South Korean negotiators said
Friday they reached agreement on cigarette imports and made
progress on other issues in five days of trade talks aimed at
opening the South Korean market to American goods.
   Local trade analysts estimated that U.S. cigarettes could
capture 10 percent of the South Korean market as a result of the
agreement.
   A U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said in
addition to full agreement on cigarettes, there was ``good
progress'' on other issues such as agricultural products and
intellectual property rights.
   ``The talks were more organizational than before and the results
were very good,'' said the official. However, the agreements still
must be approved by senior officials in each government.
   The U.S. side declined to disclose details of the talks, but
South Korean officials said they agreed to allow greater American
cigarette sales by lowering prices and ending most sales
restrictions.
   South Korean officials said the prices of foreign cigarettes
would be lowered from the present $1.76 per pack to $1.03 effective
July 1. The prices could go down further next year after South
Korea revises its laws, cutting tariffs and various excise taxes
levied on tobacco, they said.
   The U.S. government has been pressing South Korea to cut its
growing trade surplus by opening its market wider to foreign goods
and services.
   South Korea opened 1 percent of its $2.1 billion cigarette
market last September, but U.S. cigarette sales have remained below
the quota.
   Under the agreement reached this week, import quotas and sales
restrictions on imported cigarettes will be abolished. After next
year, foreign exporters will be able to set their own retail
prices, officials said.
   U.S. negotiators also sought to open the South Korean market to
54 American agricultural products, but South Korea agreed only to
allow imports of avocados, meat extracts, most vegetable juices and
frozen potatoes for use in French fries, effective July 1.
   South Korea agreed to honor U.S. intellectual property rights
for 911 ``pipeline products,'' which are patented in the United
States but not yet sold in South Korea, for 10 years, retroactive
from last year, the officials said.
   No agreement was reached, however, on wine and advertising, for
which the United States sought to open the South Korean market
immediately, the officials said.
   South Korea said it would open its wine market in 1990, one year
ahead of schedule, but proposed no specific time frame for
advertising, they said.
   The talks, originally scheduled to run from Monday to Wednesday,
were extended until Friday to solve last-minute differences on
cigarettes and other issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
