<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade. Wheat was a little lower, corn was
nearly unchanged, and soybeans were slightly higher.
   The modest rally in the soybean complex was led by soybean meal,
which enjoyed fairly strong European demand, analysts said.
   Weather forecasts reducing the amount of rain expected to fall
over the weekend in soybean-growing states lent further support to
the soybean complex.
   Some chart theorists believe soybean futures may be nearing the
end of their recent rise, said Steve Freed, an analyst in Chicago
with the investment firm Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``I think we're going to make one more attempt at contract
highs, then we'll be done for a while,'' he said.
   Wheat and corn retreated in response to slack export demand,
analysts said. Wheat also was pressured by expectations of a
bountiful winter wheat harvest.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents lower to \ cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $2.96 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to { cent higher with May at $2.03\ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1 cent higher with May at $1.61 a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 2{ cents higher with May at $6.91{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .05 cent higher with June at
72.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .32 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with May at 79.60 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to
.05 cent higher with June at 51.40 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .07 cent to .27 cent lower with May at 52.15 cents a
pound.
   Most livestock and meat futures settled higher on Thursday.
</TEXT>
