<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ContinentalTrial     05-06 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Trial,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Former Bankers Face Retrial In Federal Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors say they have decided to retry two
former bank executives whose first trial on federal fraud charges
related to the near-collapse of Continental Illinois National Bank
and Trust Co. resulted in a hung jury.
   John Lytle, a former Continental vice president, and William
Patterson, former head of energy lending at Penn Square Bank of
Oklahoma, will be retried on 11 counts of bank fraud, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Duffy.
   ``These defendants deserve to be held accountable for their
actions,'' he said.
   Prosecutors have charged that Lytle accepted kickbacks from
Patterson in exchange for buying Penn Square loans that violated
Continental's lending policies. The kickbacks came in the form of
nearly $600,000 in unsecured personal loans extended to Lytle by
Penn Square, prosecutors contend.
   But jurors who heard the lengthy trial failed to reach a verdict
against Lytle and Patterson and a mistrial was declared on Tuesday.
   A third defendant, Tulsa oil contractor Jere Sturgis, was
acquitted. He had been accused of aiding the alleged scheme by
purchasing oil wells from Lytle at a 300 percent return in hopes of
obtaining a Continental loan.
   Duffy said the overwhelming majority of jurors in favor of
convicting Lytle and Patterson was a factor in the decision to
retry the case.
   ``The fact it was 11-to-1 demonstrates the strength of the case
and that we were able to convince 11 people beyond a reasonable
doubt,'' he said.
   Penn Square collapsed in July 1982 under the weight of energy
loans it could not collect. In 1984, Continental needed a $4.5
billion government bailout to survive one of the largest runs on
deposits in banking history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
