<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WesternPublishing     05-06 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Western Publishing,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children's Book Publisher Says It's Talking With Gulf & Western</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western Publishing Group Inc., a children's book
and printing company, says it is discussing a possible merger with
Gulf & Western Inc., the entertainment concern that been expanding
its publishing interests.
   Both companies noted, however, that there were a number of
issues still open and there were no assurances an agreement would
be reached.
   Western Publishing disclosed a week ago it was taking about a
possible merger with an unidentified company.
   On Thursday, it said the talks were with Gulf & Western, which
subsequently confirmed that preliminary discussions were under way.
   Western Publishing said there were unresolved tax issues arising
from the proposed combination, but said its board wanted to
continue the talks with Gulf & Western on a non-exclusive basis.
   Before any transaction is completed, Western said, it intends to
spin off its Penn Corp. division to its shareholders.
   The Penn division makes party goods such as napkins and plates
and also makes pens and creates vinyl products that can be
imprinted with various corporate names and logos for use as
giveaways.
   Western Publishing said its board intended to review the status
of merger negotiations and the proposed spinoff of Penn in about
two weeks.
   In trading at midday Friday, Gulf & Western was up 50 cents a
share to $38.12{ in trading on the New York Stock Exchange, while
Western Publishing was off $1 a share at $22.25 in over-the-counter
trading.
   Western Publishing is best known for its Golden Book series for
children, has an extensive distibution system for its books,
puzzles, games and crayons and is a major commercial printer.
   For its fiscal year ended Jan. 30, Western earned $21.6 million,
or $1.08 a share, on revenue of $457.4 million.
   The company said that if Penn had been a separate company last
year, Pennt would have reported on a pro-forma basis pre-tax income
of $1.4 million on revenue of $71 million.
   Western was acquired by Mattel Inc. in 1979, was taken private
five years later and emerged again as a public company in 1986.
   Gulf & Western has spent more than $1 billion over the last few
years to expand its publishing business.
   A longtime owner of Simon & Schuster, which publishes books for
mass circulation, Gulf & Western bought the elementary school
publisher Esquire Inc. and the college and professional business
publisher Prentice-Hall Inc. in 1984.
   It bought Ginn & Co., an elementary and high school publisher,
in 1985 and acquired Silver Burdett Co., an elementary textbook
publisher in May 1986.
   Gulf & Western also has extensive interests in entertainment and
financial services.
</TEXT>
