<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0295</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today in a muted
response to the latest news on employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.80 to 2,025.03 by
noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 6 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 681 up, 584 down and
548 unchanged.
   Before the market opened the Labor Department reported that the
civilian unemployment rate fell to 5.4 percent in April from 5.6
percent the month before.
   There had been concern on Wall Street that stocks might suffer a
setback on signs of continuing strength in the economy, because of
concern that upward pressure might be increasing on inflation and
interest rates.
   However, the reported increase in nonfarm payroll employment of
174,000 came in toward the low end of advance estimates.
   And analysts said it looked as though stocks had taken into
account any worries the job data might pose with their decline
Wednesday and Thursday, when the Dow Jones industrials dropped
38.13 points.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up } at 44|; USX,
up { at 32\; American Telephone & Telegraph, up [ at 26\; American
Express, up \ at 23~, and Bethlehem Steel, up \ at 19].
   Micron Technology rose 1] to 22~ in the over-the-counter market.
The stock has recently been recommended by investment adviser Yale
Hirsch and other analysts as a beneficiary of heavy demand and
rising prices for computer memory chips.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .36 to 146.87. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .10 at 302.29.
</TEXT>
