<TEXT>
   Here are some of the major business events and economic events
scheduled for the coming week (some dates are tentative):
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>MONDAY, May 9</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ATLANTA _ The eighth annual Comdex conference, billed as the
world's largest computer industry trade show, opens a four-day
session with some 850 companies showing off the latest in computer
technology.
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court is in recess until May 16.
   DENVER _ A news conference is scheduled by Young Americans Bank
to review progress of the unique institution for children.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TUESDAY, May 10</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   WASHINGTON _ The National Economic Commission, created to
recommend solutions to the budget deficit, holds its first public
hearing.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>WEDNESDAY, May 11</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Nothing scheduled.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THURSDAY, May 12</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   WASHINGTON _ The Commerce Department is scheduled to report on
overall retail sales in April; due at 8:30 a.m. EDT.
   HOT SPRINGS, Va. _ The Business Council, a group of 220 leading
corporate leaders, begins its three-day spring meeting on the
economy. (Skidmore will cover)
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Ford Motor Co. holds its annual shareholders
meeting.
   NEW YORK _ Sentencing is scheduled for the 23-year-old Wall
Street ``whiz kid'' who admitted bilking $10 million from investors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>FRIDAY, May 13:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   WASHINGTON _ The Labor Department is to release the Producer
Price Index for April; due at 8:30 a.m. EDT.
   WASHINGTON _ The Commerce Department is reporting on business
inventories and sales during March; due at 10 a.m. EDT.
   DETROIT _ Domestic automakers are to report on their sales of
cars and light trucks during the first 10 days of May.
