<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Northwest-HotDogs 1stLd-Writethru   05-06 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest-Hot Dogs, 1st Ld-Writethru,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Denies Banning Hot Dogs, Ice Cream Cones for Women
Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to CORRECT base manager's last name to
Wells, sted, Evans, and UPDATE with photo set up, effort to reach
Daugherty this morning.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines has denied a Teamsters
union claim that it ordered female flight attendants not to eat hot
dogs or ice cream cones while in uniform because it may be sexually
suggestive.
   The Teamsters union, which represents the airline's flight
attendants, said an employee bulletin circulated at Detroit
Metropolitan Airport contained the directive. The airline says the
bulletin is a fake.
   ``That's absurd,'' Northwest spokesman Redmond Tyler said. ``We
certainly don't have a policy of this type.''
   Tyler said Northwest's Detroit base manager, Wendy Wells, and
some uniformed flight attendants will eat hot dogs and ice cream at
the airport.
   Teamsters spokesman Ken Daugherty said the policy came out in
the monthly Northwest Detroit Inflight, a newsletter for employees.
   He said it was signed by Wells, but Wells called the document a
fake.
   Daugherty did not return a telephone call this morning seeking
comment on Northwest's response.
   Northwest operates one of its three hubs nationwide from Detroit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
