<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HelpWanted     05-06 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Help Wanted,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Help-Wanted Ads Little Changed In March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While businesses placed slightly more
help-wanted advertisements in March than they did in February, the
volume of ads has basically remained unchanged since November, a
business information group reported Friday.
   The Conference Board said its seasonally adjusted Help Wanted
Advertising Index rose 3 points in March to 159.
   The index, which measures the volume of classified advertising
in 51 major newspapers around the nation, is an indicator of
changes in demand for labor and general business conditions.
   ``Want-ad volume peaked in November 1987 (at 164) and has been
basically marking time since then,'' said board economist Kenneth
Goldstein.
   ``The consensus of economic forecasts indicates the unemployment
rate will inch up from 5.6 percent in March to 6.3 percent this
summer, and the latest readings on help-wanted advertising are
certainly not consistent with that scenario,'' he said.
   Also Friday, the Labor Department reported that unemployment
fell in April to 5.4 percent, the lowest it has been since 1974.
   The Conference Board said advertising volume rose modestly
around the nation in March, picking up most in the Pacific region,
with a 3.3 percent gain, and least in the Middle Atlantic Region,
with a 0.2 percent increase.
   Other regional gains were: East South Central (3.2 percent);
West North Central (2.2 percent); New England (1.8 percent) and
Mountain (0.7 percent).
</TEXT>
