<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Rowntree     05-06 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rowntree,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jacobs Suchard Raises Stake in Rowntree to 29.9 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacobs Suchard SA, a Swiss food and confectionery
maker, raised its stake Friday in the British confectioner Rowntree
PLC to 29.9 percent, the maximum allowed under British law short of
a full takeover bid.
   Jacobs Suchard has paid an estimated 450 million pounds, or $841
million, for the Rowntree shares, which it has acquired gradually
since it accumulated a 14.9 percent stake on April 13. It held a
23.5 percent stake on Wednesday.
   A full Jacobs Suchard bid would have to top the 2.1
billion-pound takeover bid for Rowntree launched last week by rival
Swiss foods giant Nestle SA.
   Nestle has built up a 7.1 percent holding in Rowntree, or 15.4
million of the company's 215 million shares.
   London analysts said they doubted Jacobs Suchard would try to
outbid Nestle in a takeover battle for Rowntree.
   ``My guess is that they will use the stake as some sort of lever
against Nestle,'' said John Mozley, an analyst at the brokerage
Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.
   Jacobs Suchard could use its stake to force a higher offer from
Nestle or gain some influence over the future management of the
company, but it declined to comment on its next move.
   ``We won't reveal our strategy,'' a company spokesman said.
   Nestle wrote Friday to Rowntree shareholders recommending they
accept the Nestle offer. Nestle stressed the company's role as a
food manufacturer in Britain in an apparent effort to deflect
mounting criticism in Britain of the takeover bid.
   ``We have the resources to help Rowntree grow faster than it
could on its own, particularly in Europe and the U.S.,'' wrote
Nestle managing director Helmut Maucher.
   Nestle said it was not worried about the possibility that a
takeover could be referred to Britain's Monopolies and Mergers
Commission to determine if the buyout would be in the public
interest.
   ``We have a lot of understanding for the fact that this
acquisition has some emotional value, but there is no monopoly
point of view that could be realistically justified,'' said Nestle
spokesman Francois Perroud.
   He said Nestle was not likely to make a new, higher offer for
Rowntree soon. ``It's a good price, a fair price, and there are a
lot of people suggesting it's actually too much to pay for
Rowntree,'' he said.
   Rowntree spokesman Gavin Russell said the company has not
directly approached the government to suggest the Swiss purchases
should be referred.
   It has relied instead on British legislators who are lobbying
the government to block the purchases, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
