<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TWA-Icahn     05-06 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TWA-Icahn,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TWA Approves Sweetened Icahn Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. said Friday its board
has approved a sweetened offer from its chairman, Carl C. Icahn,
for the shares in the company that he does not already own,
removing one barrier in his effort to take the airline private.
   The takeover specialist controls TWA through eltities that own
77 percent of its 30 million common shares outstanding. He dropped
a similar proposal after the Oct. 12 stock market crash, then came
back with a revised bid on April 22.
   Under the bid approved by TWA's board Friday, shareholders not
affiliated with Icahn would receive for each share of common stock
$20 in cash and $30 in face amount of 12 percent notes due in 2008.
   Those notes had carried a $29 face value in Icahn's April 22
offer.
   At the same time, the entities controlled by Icahn would
receive, for each common share, $20 in cash and a new issue of
preferred stock and a retained share of common stock, a TWA
statement said.
   Once completed, Icahn and entities controlled by him would own
about 90 percent of the airline's stock. The remaining shares would
be owned by an employee stock ownership plan.
   The airline also said that upon closure of the deal, it intended
to:
   _Pay off at least $64.5 million of debt.
   _Seek the consent of holders of some preferred stock to
eliminate voting rights on that stock and to exchange other
preferred issues for 12 percent notes.
   The transaction is subject to various conditions, including
regulatory clearance and approval by a majority vote of
shareholders unaffiliated with Icahn. A vote on the proposal is to
be conducted at TWA's annual meeting, to be held toward the end of
the year.
   TWA said an independent committee was selected by its board to
evaluate the fairness of both of Icahn proposals to the public
shareholdeps of TWA's common stock.
   ``The Independent Committee has determined that Icahn's revised
offer is fair to the public holders of TWA common stock from a
financial point of view and will recommend that the common
stockholders approve the transaction,'' the statement said.
   It added that the investment banking firm of Dillon, Read & Co.
Inc. had told the committee orally that the Icahn's latest offer
``is fair to public holders ... from a financial point of view.''
   Industry analysts had been generally positive about Icahn's
April 22 offer, putting a value on the combined package of cash and
note at levels between $35 and $45 per outstandinf share.
   That would make the offer worth at least $276 million, at $40
per share for the 6.9 million outstanding shares Icahn does not
already control.
   The April 22 offer sent TWA's stock up $7 a share to $35.12{.
The stock rose $1.12{ a share Friday to close at $35.50 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Despite the response in April, it appeared Icahn faced pressure
raise it anyway.
   ``He had several conversations with the investment bankers who
had been retained by the independent committee, and maybe they
persuaded him it should be made a little sweeter,'' said Mark
Buckstein, a TWA spokesman.
   John Pincavage, who watches TWA for the PaineWebber Inc.
securities firm, said Friday that he had priced the April offer at
$36 to $38 a share.
   ``So maybe this makes it $39,'' he said.
   ``I think it's a good deal for shareholders,'' Pincavage added.
``After all, Icahn could have bought it on the market at a lower
priae, if he wanted to.''
</TEXT>
