<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-06 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower in Domestic Trading; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mostly lower in domestic
trading Friday after rising overseas on the strength of a favorable
report on U.S. unemployment.
   Gold prices fell. In New York, Republic National Bank quoted
bullion at $443.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $445.25
on Thursday.
   The dollar finished mostly higher overseas and moved up sharply
in early domestic trading on the heels of a Labor Department report
that said the nation's unemployment rate fell to 5.4 percent in
April, its lowest level since 1974.
   A separate survey of business payrolls showed a gain of 175,000
jobs in April. Growth in new factory jobs, which had been sluggish
the previous three months after rising dramatically in 1987,
accounted for more than one-fourth of the payroll increase.
   Leading the surge were export-related industries such as
machinery and fabricated metal products.
   ``The market interpreted it as slightly bullish for the
dollar,'' said Robert Ryan, senior trader at Irving Trust Co.
   But the dollar began to drift lower once the reaction to the
Labor Department data had run its course. The currency was met by
strong resistance when it tried to break out of the narrow range it
has held to for the past several weeks, and trading tapered off to
a trickle, dealers said.
   The dollar typically does not respond to employment data, but
dealers hoped Friday's announcement would provide some fresh
fundamentals on which to trade.
   ``People are looking for a catalyst to get us out of this
range,'' said James McGroarty, vice president at Discount Corp.
   The dollar closed at 124.88 Japanese yen in Tokyo, where markets
reopened after a three-day holiday, higher than 124.32 yen in
London late Thursday. The unemployment report was issued after the
close of trading in Tokyo.
   Later, in London, the dollar fell to 124.85 yen. In New York the
dollar closed at 124.77 yen, down from 124.905 yen on Wednesday.
   The British pound rose in London to $1.8730 from $1.8665 late
Thursday. In New York it cost $1.8630 to buy one pound, more
expensive than Thursday's $1.8620.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's prices, included: 1.67935 West German marks, down from
1.68405; 1.3995 Swiss francs, down from 1.4035; 5.7090 French
francs, down from 5.7275; 1,252.375 Italian lire, down from
1,258.00, and 1.23725 Canadian dollars, up from 1.23365.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.6805 West German marks, up from 1.6780; 1.4015
Swiss francs, up from 1.3955; 5.7230 French francs, up from 5.7052;
1.8860 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8790; 1,254.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,253.25; 1.2375 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2333.
   Gold prices were buoyed by the U.S. unemployment data, but then
retreated amid profit-taking, dealers said. In London, the metal
fell to a late bid price of $442.10 a troy ounce, down from $445.25
bid late Thursday. In Zurich, it fell to $443 bid from $445.50 bid
late Thursday.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold closed at $443.70 a troy
ounce, down from $445.40 on Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $448.71 from
$447.07 bid at Thursday's close.
   Silver finished higher at $6.381 a troy ounce on New York's
Comex, up from $6.327 on Thursday. In London the metal fell to a
late bid price of $6.36 a troy ounce from $6.37 bid late Thursday.
</TEXT>
