<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USGSuit     05-06 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USG Suit,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Settles Shareholder Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. said Friday it has proposed a
settlement to lawsuits filed by shareholders who objected to parts
of the company's plan to recapitalize in the face of a hostile
takeover bid.
   An unspecified number of suits were filed in Delaware Chancery
Court sometime after Monday, when USG unveiled details of its $2.2
billion recapitalization plan. The Chicago-based building products
company is incorporated in Delaware.
   The proposed settlement, which still must be approved by the
court, would add $92.4 million to the cost of the recapitalization.
   The investor group pursuing a $2 billion takeover bid, Desert
Partners LP of Midland, Texas, said in a statement it did not
believe the settlement would be approved.
   Shareholders objected to aspects of the recapitalization plan
that would dilute the value of their shares, USG spokeswoman Randi
Killian said.
   Under its initial plan, USG proposed to pay shareholders $37 in
cash, debentures with a face value of $5 and a share of stock in
the recapitalized corporation for each common share.
   But each of the 2.2 million shares held by the company's
employee investment plans instead were to be swapped for eight
shares in the new company. USG would have had to issue 17.9 million
new shares to the investment plans, which irked some shareholders
over dilution of their holdings.
   As part of its proposed settlement, USG agreed the shares held
by the employee plans would receive the same payout of cash, notes
and stock as other sharesholders, rather than just straight stock.
   The settlement proposal would keep the number of outstanding
shares at 54 million, down from the 70 million called for under the
original plan.
   ``It is now costing USG more, but the shares are worth more''
because there are fewer outstanding, Killian said.
   Desert Partners called the proposed settlement a ``thinly
disguised public relations gesture to bolster (USG's) position in
the upcoming proxy contest.'' The two sides are building up to a
showdown at USG's annual meeting on May 11. Desert Partners has
nominated a slate of six candidates to USG's 15-member board.
   The partnership noted in a statement that USG is not obligated
to go through with the terms of the settlement if it is not
approved by the court.
   Desert Partners, a partnership headed by two Texas oilmen, has
been trying to acquire USG for months. The partnership has a
$42-a-share tender offer outstanding that values USG at $2.16
billion, but has made repeated efforts to negotiate a merger at a
higher price.
   Earlier this week Desert Partners offered to acquire USG in a
deal Wall Street sources estimated would be worth $50 a share, or
about $2.58 billion.
   Desert Partners, headed by Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E. Brown,
owns about 9.9 percent of USG's shares and said that as of last
Friday about 19.3 million shares, or 37.5 percent, had been
tendered under its $42-a-share offer.
   USG is the holding company for United States Gypsum Co., USG
Interiors Inc., Masonite Corp. and several other operating
subsidiaries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
