<HEAD>Shareholders Sue Icahn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A class action suit was filed Friday
on behalf of Texaco Inc. shareholders who claim takeover strategist
Carl Icahn manipulated the price of the oil giant's shares so he
could buy them cheaply.
   The suit is a companion to one filed by Texaco earlier this week
alleging massive securities law violations by Icahn, who is
Texaco's largest shareholder and chairman of Trans World Airlines
Inc.
   Stanley Bernstein, an attorney who helped file the shareholder
suit, said he expected the case to be joined with the main Texaco
action at U.S. District Court in White Plains. Texaco is
headquartered in nearby Harrison, N.Y.
   The shareholder suit claims that Icahn, along with associates
and companies he controls, deceived, manipulated and harmed other
Texaco shareholders to advance his own interests since buying a big
block of Texaco stock last fall.
   Icahn was out of his office and unavailable for comment on the
suit.
   He began buying the stock while Texaco was negotiating a
settlement with rival Pennzoil over a $10.3 billion judgment
awarded Pennzoil after a Texas jury found Texaco had illegally
interfered with Pennzoil's merger with Getty Oil Co.
   Texaco filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
the bankruptcy code last year and emerged last month under a
court-approved reorganization plan.
   The shareholder suit charges Icahn interfered with the
reorganization process, traded on inside information, circulated
false and misleading information and otherwise engaged in acts
which constituted a ``manipulative or deceptive device'' prohibited
by the federal securities laws.
   Such actions allowed Icahn to purchase an estimated 30 million
shares of Texaco between October 1987 and May 1988 below market
value, the suit said.
   The suit seeks unspecified damages on behalf of all those Texaco
shareholders who sold stock during the period Oct. 2, 1987 and May
3, 1988.
   The suit was filed in Manhattan but was expected to be
transfered to White Plains.
   Texaco's suit, filed Tuesday, seeks to invalidate Icahn attempt
to install himself and some associates on the company's board of
directors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
