<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-TexasAir     05-06 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Texas Air,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Air Posts $124.3 Million Loss for First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. on Friday reported a net loss of
$124.3 million for the first quarter, which the airline giant
blamed largely on labor troubles at Eastern Airlines and bad winter
weather affecting Continental Airlines.
   Texas Air, the nation's largest airline holding company with
about 20 percent of the market, is the parent of Eastern and
Continental. Its overall loss of $124.3 million widened from a
$100.7 million loss in the first three months of 1987.
   The latest loss occurred despite an increase in revenue, to
$2.13 billion from $2.04 billion in the year-earlier quarter.
   Texas Air attributed the losses at Miami-based Eastern to a
``crippling'' campaign being waged by the Eastern pilots and
machinists unions against the carrier.
   Eastern and Texas Air sued the two unions Friday for $1.5
billion, accusing them of ``Eastern bashing'' to drive down the
airline's value so they could buy it cheaply.
   Eastern posted a net loss of $31 million for the first quarter,
compared with net income of $2.1 million a year earlier. Revenue
declined to $1.1 billion from $1.2 billion.
   The company said Houston-based Continental's losses were caused
by bad weather and the costs of integrating the airline into the
parent, which had also been problems in late 1987.
   Continental recorded a first-quarter loss of $80.6 million on
revenue of $1.1 billion, narrowed from a loss of $97.9 million on
revenue of $900 million.
   Continental's earnings for first-quarter 1987 were restated to
include the results for People Express, New York Air and Rocky
Mountain Airways, which Continental purchased from Texas Air in
April 1987.
   ``The losses reported by both (Eastern and Continental) are
close to our expectations and reflect the unusual operating
environments which each airline faces at this time,'' Texas Air
spokesman Bruce Hicks said.
   He said Continental experienced a difficult first quarter but
ended the period ``on a positive and profitable note.''
   Improving fare levels, operating performances and generally
positive traffic trends are producing a marked change in
Continental's financial performance, Hicks said.
   At Eastern, ``aggressive'' cost control and the elimination of
non-economic services helped reduce the first-quarter loss from the
level of losses incurred in the second half of 1987, Texas Air said.
   Texas Air officials have blamed the pilots and machinists unions
at Eastern for the current investigations of both big Texas Air
carriers by the Department of Transportation and the Federal
Aviation Administration.
   The investigations have turned up no major safety flaws in the
planes.
   Hicks said the past several weeks have been ``most difficult and
challenging'' because of the investigations.
   ``We strongly believe that Texas Air and its airlines will
emerge from this process with renewed confirmation of our
objectives,'' he said.
</TEXT>
