<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Gillette-Coniston     05-06 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gillette-Coniston,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proxy Count Review Confirms Gillette Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recount of shareholder ballots confirmed that
Coniston Group's attempt to oust four Gillette Co. directors
failed, the toiletry maker said Friday.
   Gillette spokeswoman Joan Fitzgerald said the review of
Tuesday's proxy ballot results by Corporation Trust Co. settled
Coniston's challenge of the count.
   Coniston, a New York-based investor group, has been maneuvering
to take over Gillette, a major maker of men's toiletries that has
battled other takeover attempts in the past.
   Coniston principal Paul E. Tierney Jr. downplayed the
significance of the recount and said an upcoming trial in U.S.
District Court will determine if there were any irregularities in
obtaining the votes.
   ``What it shows is that Corporation Trust ... did in fact add
them up correctly,'' said Tierney. ``It did not show that those
votes were legally obtained or properly obtained.''
   A final report and certification of the ballot count is expected
next week. The trial stemming from challenges filed by both
Gillette and Coniston during the proxy fight is scheduled to begin
June 13.
   On Tuesday, a preliminary count of about 87 million shares
voting in the proxy election showed 48 percent support for
Coniston's four director candidates, who pledged to try to convince
the other eight directors to sell Gillette's personal care empire.
They needed a simple majority to be elected.
   The proxy ballots were submitted during Gillette's April 21
annual meeting in Andover following a three-month battle
highlighted by full-page newspaper advertisements and several
mailings to shareholders.
   New York-based Coniston, which controls 6.76 million shares,
about 5.8 percent of Gillette's 115.5 million shares outstanding,
immediately challenged the results of the preliminary count.
   Gillette fell 75 cents a share Friday to $38.62{ in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading Friday.
   Besides Tierney, the Coniston candidates were Coniston
principals Augustus K. Oliver and Keith R. Gollust and former cable
executive David Strassler.
   The Gillette directors up for re-election to three-year terms
were Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Colman M. Mockler Jr.,
Lawrence E. Fouraker, Herbert H. Jacobi and Joseph F. Turley.
   In 1986, Gillette halted several takeover attempts by Revlon
Group Inc. by signing a 10-year no-takeover pact and buying back
Revlon's stock for nearly $580 million.
</TEXT>
